[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4{ After being a  1.e4  player all my life (with infrequent excursions into  1.c4  territory) I started a switch to  1.d4  in 2008. The reason for this was my feeling that I needed to become a more universal player in order to improve my chess understanding by incorporating new openings and positions in my repertoire. This meant that I needed to construct my  1.d4  repertoire from scratch. The process of constructing a repertoire taught me a lot about how one should go about when learning new openings. Ever since then I have honed my  1.d4  repertoire and today I can confidently say that I am universal when it comes to openings - I can play  1.e4 ,  1.d4  and  1.c4  equally well. I used all this knowledge when creating this repertoire.  With the state of modern theory today, I sought variations that are positionally solid, yet contain a certain amount of originality and surprise value. I looked for variations where one doesn't need to memorize a lot of lines, but ones where a profound understanding of the plans and ideas should be sufficient for successful navigation of the opening phase. Creativity, originality and the element of surprise are all present in the variations you are about to learn.  Nowadays it is impossible to find an advantage for White. You will rarely find one in the lines that follow, but what you will find are variations that lead to original positions where superior knowledge and understanding can serve as basis for outplaying your opponents. I wish you good luck in your studies and I hope you win many games by confidently playing  1.d4 . }
