[Black "QS: 1...Nf6 2.c4 g6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6{ With the fianchetto Black intends to play either the King's Indian Defence (KID) or the Grunfeld Defence. While the KID cannot be avoided, the Grunfeld can be, and White's next two moves are aimed at exactly that. }
3. Nf3( { White doesn't play }3.Nc3 { because after }3...d5 { we land in the Grunfeld Defence. Therefore White first develops the kingside, postponing the development of the knight on  b1  until the moment when Black commits the d-pawn. } )
3. Bg7
4. e3( { This system became very popular after GM Alexander Grischuk used it with great success to beat GM Ian Nepomniachtchi, one of the biggest proponents of the Grunfeld, in 2013. Its popularity continues to this day.  White's idea is simple - without a knight on  c3  the Grunfeld doesn't really work because after the exchanges in the centre with }5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 { , }{ White can continue with  e4 , hitting the knight on  d5  and Black can no longer take on  c3  (because the square is empty now!) and continue with ... c5 , attacking White's centre. He would be forced to move the knight from the centre, but this will give White time to consolidate and not allow the typical Grunfeld counterplay. } )
4. O-O
5. Be2{ Still waiting with the development of the knight on  b1 . As you can see, White has more useful moves than Black - he can castle, play  Qc2  and so on. Black is already hard-pressed to move the d-pawn and continue with his development. }
5. c5{ With this move Black wants to transpose to the Benoni in case White pushes  d5 . While that is perfectly possible, White has an easier solution. }
6. dxc5{ With this exchange White obtains a pawn structure that is very easy for him to play. Its essence is in the control of the  d5 -square: after  Nc3  White would control that square three times. If allowed, he will then develop with  b3 ,  Bb2  and after preparation will play  Nd5 , obtaining space advantage. This is the ideal scenario for White, which, if Black is careful, shouldn't really happen. }
6. Na6{ One of the ways to regain the pawn. }( { Another move is }6...Ne4 7.Nd4 { (closing the long diagonal in order to allow for smooth development with  Nc3  and  b3 ,  Bb2 ) }7...Nxc5 8.Nc3 Nc6 9.O-O { with  b3  and  Bb2  to come, leading to a complex middlegame. } )
7. O-O{ White castles and waits for Black to take on  c5  when he can advance with  b4 . }
7. Nxc5
8. b4{ White gains a tempo to develop the bishop on  b2 . }
8. Nfe4( { This is critical because now play becomes concrete. Putting the other knight there is possible, it leads to simpler play, for example }8...Nce4 9.Bb2 d6 10.Nbd2 Nxd2 11.Nxd2 b6 12.Qb3 { with easy development: White puts the rooks on the c and d files and then he can try the typical manoeuvre  Nb1 - c3  and if appropriate,  Nd5 , or play  Bd4  and  Qb2 , to increase the control of the long diagonal. } )
9. Nd4{ The only way to block the long diagonal and not to lose material. }
9. Ne6{ Black puts more pressure on the knight on  d4 . }
10. Bb2{ White develops and defends the knight. }
10. Qb6{ Black also develops and continues to attack White's position. }
11. a3{ White is very solid so he can calmly defend the pawn on  b4 . }
11. d5{ Active counterplay in the centre. }
12. Bf3{ By latching onto the knight on  e4  White prevents the capture on  c4 , since now the  d5 -pawn must stay put to defend the knight on  e4 . }
12. Nxd4( { In case of }12...Rd8 13.Nxe6 Bxe6 14.Bxg7 Kxg7 15.c5 { White obtains a strong queenside majority in addition to the control of the dark squares in the centre. } )( { After }12...N6g5 13.cxd5 Rd8 14.Bxe4 Nxe4 15.Qb3 { play is rather unclear, if Black goes after the  d5 -pawn then White can use the d-file and the  Nb5  idea to harass Black's pieces. } )
13. Bxd4( { White can also keep more pieces on the board by capturing with the pawn, for example }13.exd4 { with  c5  next, obtaining a mobile queenside majority. By taking with the bishop White wants to obtain that same queenside majority but in an endgame. } )
13. Bxd4
14. Qxd4{ The queen exerts a lot of pressure in the centre, so Black must exchange on  d4 . }
14. Qxd4
15. exd4{ The tension between  c4  and  d5  and the bishop on  f3  and the knight on  e4  will allow White to play  c5  next and obtain a mobile queenside majority with easy play, for example }
15. Rd8
16. c5{ White has a comfortable endgame. The plan is obvious, to push the queenside pawns further. Ideas include putting a rook on  d1  or  c1 , perhaps exchanging the knight on  e4  and then developing with  Nc3 . }
