1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6{ With the fianchetto Black intends to play either the King's Indian Defence (KID) or the Grunfeld Defence. While the KID cannot be avoided, the Grunfeld can be, and White's next two moves are aimed at exactly that. }
3. Nf3( { White doesn't play }3.Nc3 { because after }3...d5 { we land in the Grunfeld Defence. Therefore White first develops the kingside, postponing the development of the knight on  b1  until the moment when Black commits the d-pawn. } )
3. Bg7
4. e3( { This system became very popular after GM Alexander Grischuk used it with great success to beat GM Ian Nepomniachtchi, one of the biggest proponents of the Grunfeld, in 2013. Its popularity continues to this day.  White's idea is simple - without a knight on  c3  the Grunfeld doesn't really work because after the exchanges in the centre with }5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 { , }{ White can continue with  e4 , hitting the knight on  d5  and Black can no longer take on  c3  (because the square is empty now!) and continue with ... c5 , attacking White's centre. He would be forced to move the knight from the centre, but this will give White time to consolidate and not allow the typical Grunfeld counterplay. } )
4. O-O
5. Be2{ Still waiting with the development of the knight on  b1 . As you can see, White has more useful moves than Black - he can castle, play  Qc2  and so on. Black is already hard-pressed to move the d-pawn and continue with his development. }
5. d6{ With this move Black enters KID territory. }
6. Nc3{ Now that the Grunfeld is no longer an option, White can develop the knight on  c3 . It's important not to castle too early, as sometimes this gives White additional options like castling queenside. }
6. Nc6{ An attempt to reverse the move-order - Black now wants to play ... e5 . }
7. d5{ A typical reaction in similar situations - the knight is chased away and White gains space in the centre. This idea to play  d5  against ... Nc6  is typical and is often seen in the chapter  Modern Attempts . }
7. Nb8( { The alternative is }7...Nb4 { but after }8.O-O Re8 { White has two good options, one is }9.a3!? Na6 10.Ra2 { (removing the rook from the long diagonal and intending  b4 ) with  b4  next, or }9.e4 e5 10.dxe6 Bxe6 11.Nd4 { with a comfortable position thanks to the solidity of the position and the space advantage. } )
8. O-O
8. e5{ Black aims for a KID structure, but White won't allow it. }
9. dxe6{ White transforms the pawn structure. }
9. Bxe6( { After }9...fxe6 10.Rb1 { White will continue with  b3  and  Bb2 . } )
10. Nd4{ Centralising the knight and threatening to win the bishop pair by taking on  e6 . }
10. Bd7
11. b3( { It's possible to play }11.e4 { , but that would transpose to mainstream KID territory after }11...Re8 12.f3 Nc6 { where Black has the extra tempo ... Bd7 . It's still playable for White, though! } )
11. Nc6
12. Bb2{ White has an easy plan to follow - exchange on  c6 , put the queen on  c2 , rook on  d1  and possibly the other on  c1 , and eventually jump  Nd5 . If Black recaptures on  c6  with a pawn, so as not to allow  Nd5 , White will place his bishop on  f3 , targeting the pawn on  c6  and pinning down the bishop on  d7  to its defence. Then an idea for White is the manoeuvre  Ne2 - d4  (probably first prepared by  Qc2  or  Qd2 , defending the bishop on  b2 ). }
