1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. Bf4{ A recent trend. This leads to novel and less explored positions as White avoids most of the openings Black can play against  1.d4 . With the bishop on  f4 , White can develop the queen's knight on  d2 , giving the position a more original flair. Naturally, Black has a wide variety of options now. }
3. b6{ A move in line with the QID. It still offers Black a chance to play ... d5  later, but it keeps flexibility for the moment. }
4. a3( { Similar to the Petrosian Variation in the QID (  }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 b6 4.a3 { ) White prepares the development of the knight to  c3  by preventing the pin ... Bb4 . } )
4. Bb7( { Black can also play the move }4...Ba6 { , an option that also exists in the Petrosian line mentioned above. After }5.Qa4 { (stopping ... c5  in view of  Bxb8  and the bishop on  a6  is lost) }5...Bb7 6.Nc3 c5 7.d5! { White has the initiative, for example }7...exd5 8.cxd5 Nxd5 9.Qe4 Qe7 10.Qf3! { maintaining the pin on the long diagonal. White can also increase the pressure on the  d5 -knight with  Rd1  if necessary. White already has an advantage here, the line can be taken further after }10...Nxc3 11.Qxb7 Qe4 12.Qc8 Ke7 13.Bxb8 Qc2 { and here the key maneuver is }14.Qc7! { with the idea of  Qe5  (check) -  Qg5  (check) -  Qc1  and the queen is in time to defend the queenside. } )
5. Nc3{ White threatens  d5 , so Black's next move is practically forced. }
5. d5( { Without a knight on  f3  the move }5...Ne4?! { doesn't work so well for Black here because after }6.Nxe4 Bxe4 { White has the important move }7.f3! { with  e4  next, building a strong centre. } )
6. e3( { An interesting alternative is }6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nxd5 Qxd5 { (Black should keep the long diagonal open, otherwise the bishop on  b7  becomes a bad piece) }8.e3 { when Black has the options of }8...c5 { and }8...Bd6 { , both of which lead to interesting middlegames and are worth exploring further. } )
6. dxc4( { This is probably Black's best. In view of the attack on the  g2 -pawn White cannot immediately regain the pawn. In case of }6...Bd6 7.Bg5 { the pin is somewhat unpleasant, as after }7...h6 8.Bxf6! Qxf6 9.cxd5 exd5 10.Qa4 { White creates confusion in Black's camp - the bishop on  b7  is already very limited and now in order not to lose the right to castle Black must put it on the awkward  c6 -square. So after }10...Bc6 11.Qb3 O-O 12.Rc1 { White has a pleasant position with pressure on the c-file. It's important to note that the light-squared bishop is best placed on  g2  in order to put pressure on the  d5 -pawn, so  Nf3 ,  g3 ,  Bg2  and  O-O  would be White's development. } )
7. Nf3{ White blocks the long diagonal with this developing move and wants to take on  c4  next. }
7. Nd5{ Black seeks simplifications. }
8. Bxc4{ White regains the pawn and completes the development of his light pieces. }
8. Nxf4{ May look good, gaining the pair of bishops, but in fact the  f4 -pawn is quite useful in controlling the  e5 -square. }
9. exf4
9. Bd6
10. O-O{ With the king safe on the kingside White is ready to play in the centre with  d5 . }
10. O-O( { The pawn on  f4  cannot be taken as }10...Bxf4?! 11.d5! { is excellent for White after }11...O-O 12.dxe6 fxe6 13.Nd4!  )
11. d5{ This central thrust opens the central files that White can use to exert pressure on Black's position. }
11. exd5
12. Bxd5{ After the exchange of the bishops Black will no longer have the advantage of the bishop pair. }
12. Bxd5
13. Qxd5{ Continuing to play with tempo. }
13. Nd7{ Black develops, but this leaves a hole on  c6 . }
14. g3{ White defends the pawn on  f4 , at the same time limiting the activity of the bishop on  d6 . White's play now is based on using the good squares for the knights,  d4 ,  b5  and  c6 , attacking Black's position from any of them. White can also double rooks on the d-file to make it even more difficult for Black to activate his pieces. }
