1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. Bf4{ A recent trend. This leads to novel and less explored positions as White avoids most of the openings Black can play against  1.d4 . With the bishop on  f4 , White can develop the queen's knight on  d2 , giving the position a more original flair. Naturally, Black has a wide variety of options now. }
3. Bb4+( { This move can be played by players who play the Nimzo-Indian or the Bogo-Indian. A move that leads to a transposition to the QGD is the strange-looking }3...Nh5 4.Bd2 d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.Nc3 Nf6 7.Bf4 { and we are in QGD territory. } )( { Another rare move to mention is }{ . After }4.Nf3 d5 5.Nbd2 { White uses the prematurely exposed knight to speed up his development. He will continue with the usual moves  e3 ,  Bd3 , which will now attack the knight on  e4 . } )
4. Nd2( { One of the main points of  3.Bf4 , White is able to cover the check without allowing the exchange on  c3  as in the Nimzo-Indian, thus keeping his structure intact. Another advantage, compared to the Bogo-Indian (after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 Bb4 4.Nbd2 { ), is that the bishop is already developed on  f4  and not stuck on  c1 . } )
4. c5( { Black immediately attacks White's centre, similar to the Nimzo-Indian. Black has many other options. Note that in case of }4...Nc6 5.Nf3 { we have a transposition to the line analysed after   }3...Nc6 4.Nf3 Bb4 5.Nbd2 { . } )
5. dxc5( { The pawn was attacked, so White takes on  c5  in order to continue with development. There is also an interesting alternative in }5.e3!? { , which also deserves independent exploration. } )
5. Bxc5
6. e3{ White's development is natural, the knight comes to  f3 , the bishop to  d3  and short castle. }
6. O-O
7. Ngf3{ In this position Black has a choice - to start with ... b6  and ... Bb7  and later decide whether to play in Hedgehog style with ... Be7  and ... d6  or play ... d5 , or to play in the centre immediately with ... d5 . }
7. d5{ Immediate play in the centre is possible, though again the most natural development of the light-squared bishop will be on  b7 . }
8. cxd5{ This capture gives Black a choice: to play with an IQP after ... exd5  or to enter a symmetrical position after ... Nxd5  when White's lead in development will guarantee some initiative. }( { A curious alternative is the move }8.Be2!?  )
8. exd5
9. Rc1{ White develops with tempo, bringing the rook in the game before continuing development of the kingside. }
9. Bb6{ Black keeps the bishop on the  g1 - a7  diagonal in order to advance with the IQP. }
10. Bd3{ White develops the pieces on their most natural squares. }
10. d4{ Black wants to get rid of the IQP, but in these situations White can advance with the e-pawn and create a pawn majority in the centre. }
11. e4{ Now White's plan is to find a way to advance with the e and f-pawns. If successful this advance will give White good attacking chances on the kingside (imagine the pawns on  f5  and  e5  for example). A move that White would like to make now is  h3 , to preserve the dark-squared bishop, so Black's next move is critical. }
11. Nh5{ Going after the bishop. }
12. Bg3( { The enterprising }12.Bg5 f6 13.Nh4!? { only leads to a draw when Black accepts the sacrifice with }13...fxg5 14.Qxh5 gxh4 15.e5 g6 16.Bxg6 hxg6 17.Qxg6 { and White has nothing more than a perpetual. } )
12. Nc6
13. O-O{ Both sides develop. White wants to save the bishop by playing  Bh4  now. }
13. Nxg3{ Taking the bishop, especially as now after  hxg3  the h-file can no longer be used by the rook on  h1 . }
14. hxg3{ We have arrived at a complex middlegame where White is very strong on the light squares (the bishop on  d3  is an excellent blockading piece, making Black's bishop on  b6  passive since Black's  d4 -pawn cannot move forward; the pawn on  e4  is safely defended and the knight from  d2  can come to  c4 ). Therefore, the plan is to continue with play on the light squares with  Nc4 ,  Re1 ,  Qd2  and possibly  e5 ,  Qf4 , taking over some dark squares, too. }
