1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. dxc4
3. e3{ The fastest way to regain the pawn. }
3. Nf6{ This is the main move, which in the vast majority of cases would lead to the main line and tabiya that arises on move 6. }( { Black can also start with }3...e6 4.Bxc4 Nf6 { etc. or   }3...a6 3.Bxc4 e6 4.Nf3 c5 5.O-O Nf6 { . } )( { Another transposition occurs after }3...c5 4.Bxc4 cxd4 5.exd4 Nf6 6.Nc3 e6 7.Nf3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Qe2 { , }{ which is analysed via the 3... Nf6  move-order, when on move 6 Black plays 6... cxd4  ( }{   }3...Nf6 4.Bxc4 e6 5.Nf3 c5 6.O-O cxd4 { ). } )( { One of the oldest opening traps in chess happens after the naive }3...b5? 4.a4 c6 5.axb5 cxb5 6.Qf3 { , }{ when White wins a piece. Surprisingly, this still happens a lot in online chess! } )( { Black can try to defend the pawn on  c4  with }3...Be6?! { but this leaves him with clumsy development after }4.Nf3 c6 5.Nbd2 b5 6.a4 Qa5 7.Ra3! { and White will regain the pawn and remain with a better structure after }7...b4 8.Ra1 c3 9.bxc3 bxc3 10.Nb3 Qc7 11.Nc5 { as the pawn on  c3  won't live for long. } )
4. Bxc4{ Pawn regained. }
4. e6( { Black's moves include  ...c5  and  ...a6  later on, though it's also possible to start with }4...a6 5.Nf3 e6 { . } )
5. Nf3{ White continues the development of the kingside. The queenside remains still for the time being as White keeps the flexibility with the development of the queen's knight as depending on circumstances it can be developed to  c3  or  d2 . }
5. c5
6. O-O{ White finished with the development of the kingside. The queenside will follow, but this will depend on how Black develops, as the queen's knight can be developed either on  c3  or  d2 , depending on circumstances. }
6. a6( { Traditionally this is the main move, but Black can also try to exchange on  d4  early on. In case of }6...Nc6 7.Qe2 { we will have a transposition either to the lines after   }6...a6 7.Qe2 Nc6 { or to the lines after   }6...cxd4 7.exd4 Be7 8.Nc3 O-O 9.Qe2 Nc6 { , }{ depending on whether Black plays ... a6  (the former) or takes on  d4  (the latter). } )
7. Qe2( { In this tabiya of the QGA White has many moves at his disposal, ranging from the endgame after }7.dxc5 { to the pawn sacrifice }7.e4 { , to Botvinnik's positional preference for }7.a4 { , to the modern 'little moves' }7.b3 { and }7.Nbd2 { . }{ The development of the queen on  e2  vacates the  d1 -square for the rook, supports the  e4 -push and lines up with the light-squared bishop on the  f1 - a6  diagonal to target Black's pawns with  a4  in case Black plays ... b5 . } )
7. b5( { The main response. Note that in case of }7...cxd4 8.exd4 Be7 9.Nc3 O-O 10.Rd1 { we have a transposition to the lines arising after   }6...cxd4 7.exd4 Be7 8.Nc3 O-O 9.Qe2 a6 10.Rd1 { . } )
8. Bd3{ The bishop stays on the  f1 - a6  diagonal as White intends to attack Black's expanded queenside pawns with  a4 . }
8. cxd4{ A principled choice, aiming to create an IQP on  d4 . }
9. a4( { White tries to take advantage of the lead in development to become active while Black still has almost all the pieces on their initial squares. It's also possible to start with }9.Rd1 Nc6 10.a4 { . } )( { The most commonly played move }9.exd4 { allows Black the time he needs as after }9...Be7 { Black is one move away from castling and obtains good play. } )
9. bxa4( { Removing the attack on the  b5 -square. Pushing the b-pawn forward now gives White an advantageous version of the IQP after }9...b4?! 10.exd4 { as it's possible to continue with  Nbd2 - c4  and  a5 , putting pressure on Black's queenside. } )( { Taking on  e3  is possible, }9...dxe3 10.Bxe3 b4 11.Rd1 Nbd7 12.Nbd2 { gives White typical compensation in an open position thanks to the lead in development. The main idea then is to improve the position of the pieces even more with  Nc4  or  Ne4 ,  Be4 ,  Bd4 , and possibly  Ng5  if there are direct threats against  e6 . } )
10. Rxa4{ The rook is very active on  a4 , both along the fourth rank and also on the a-file. }
10. dxe3{ The critical move, winning a pawn. Allowing White to capture with  Rxd4  will give White the initiative with equal material. }
11. Bxe3{ White sacrificed a pawn for free and fast development. It's notable that White doesn't really risk much here as in many lines it's possible to take the pawn on  a6  and establish material parity. }
11. Bb7( { This may be a bit counterintuitive, but it's better than the fast development of the kingside with }11...Be7?! { which allows }12.Ne5! O-O 13.Rd1 { with strong initiative after }13...Qc7 14.Bd4 { as White threatens  Rc4  and Black is in great difficulty. } )
12. Rd1{ White continues to develop with tempo. }
12. Nbd7
13. Nc3( { All White's pieces are developed now. This is more ambitious than the capture of the  a6 -pawn with }13.Bxa6 Bxa6 14.Rxa6 Qc8! { (the only move that keeps Black afloat, White was threatening  Ne5 ) }15.Rxa8 Qxa8 16.Qb5 { . }{ This is objectively equal, though White has a passed b-pawn as a good asset and still some initiative ( Ne5  is still a threat). } )
13. Be7
14. Ng5{ A move that is tricky to meet. The knight introduces tactical ideas on  e6 ,  f7  or  h7 . }
14. O-O( { One of the ideas is that }14...h6? { is bad in view of }15.Nxe6! fxe6 16.Bg6 Kf8 17.Bf4 { and Black is busted as it's not possible to defend the pawn on  e6 . } )
15. Nxh7( { This is another idea. If White wants to keep the game more complex, it's possible to play }15.Rd4 { , }{ introducing threats on the d-file in addition to the ideas like  Nxh7 . } )
15. Nxh7
16. Bxh7+{ The idea of the sacrifice was to open the d-file. White regains the material after }
16. Kxh7
17. Qd3+
17. Kg8
18. Qxd7{ Now simplifications occur, though after }
18. Bd5
19. Qxd8
19. Rfxd8
20. Nxd5
20. exd5
21. Bd4{ White can still play on in this objectively equal endgame: the bishop on  d4  is excellent, blockading the  d5 -pawn and defending the pawn on  b2 . White can double on the a-file to attack the pawn on  a6  and the kingside majority can also start moving forward. }
