1. d4
1. d6{ Black keeps the options to play the Old Indian or lines with early ... Bg4 . Transpositions to positions where Black fianchettoes the dark-squared bishop are also possible. }
2. e4{ This crosses out all Black's options in the closed openings and forces either a Philidor or Pirc. }
2. Nf6( { In case of }2...g6 3.Nf3 Bg7 4.Bd3 { we have a transposition to the lines analysed after   }1...g6 2.e4 Bg7 3.Nf3 d6 4.Bd3 { . } )
3. Bd3( { This developing move has two ideas: the first is to defend the pawn on  e4  and the second one is to keep the  c3 -square free so that White can strengthen the centre with  c3  and blunt Black's fianchettoed bishop on  g7 . Now Black has two main options: the Philidor players would likely play }3...e5 { , while the Pirc players would choose }3...g6 { . } )
3. g6( { The move }3...c5 { is rare. It's best met with }4.dxc5 Qa5 ( { Or }4...dxc5 5.Nc3 Nc6 6.Nf3 Bg4 { (otherwise White plays  h3  and the bishop will have problems developing) }7.h3 Bxf3 8.Qxf3 { with a comfortable development for White in addition to the bishop pair. } )5.Nc3 Qxc5 6.Be3 Qa5 7.f4 { with easy play for White after  Nf3  with a possibility to castle on both wings. } )
4. Nf3{ Now both sides develop their kingsides and castle. }
4. Bg7
5. O-O
5. O-O
6. Re1{ An important move that gives more power to the possible  e5 -push. Generally speaking, now Black has only one critical plan and that is to push ... e5 . This is so because the other undermining move ... c5  is easily parried with  c3 , when Black doesn't really put any pressure on White's centre. White's play in the upcoming lines is guided by several rules of thumb.  They are the following: if Black threatens to push ... e5  in any other way than ... Nc6  (for example with ... Nbd7  or ... c6  and ... Qc7 ) the reaction is to push  e5  (here the importance of the position of the rook on  e1  becomes visible); the move ... Nc6  is met by  d5 , forcing the knight to move either to  b8  or  b4 ; then Black will either undermine White's  d5 -pawn by ... c6 , in which case White will support it with  c4 , or will go for KID structures with ... e5 , in which case White will prevent that by taking en passant. Following these general guidelines White can navigate the opening with ease. }
6. Nc6( { Black's best plan. He wants to play  ...e5  and with the knight on  c6  to exert more pressure on the centre. As mentioned earlier, the undermining with the c-pawn brings little, for example }6...c5 7.c3 cxd4 8.cxd4 Bg4 9.Nbd2 { shows all the advantages of White's set-up with  Bd3 : he used the c-pawn to keep his centre intact and the  b1 -knight went to  d2  to replace the one on  f3  in case Black exchanges on  f3 . Next comes  h3  and White will either gain the bishop pair or in case the bishop retreats White can develop further with  a3 ,  b4 ,  Nb3  etc. } )( { The move }6...c6 { is met by }7.h3 { and then both }7...Nbd7 8.e5! { and   }7...Qc7 8.e5! { illustrate White's idea that prevents Black's ... e5 . } )( { The pin }6...Bg4 { is harmless as White has }7.Nbd2 { followed by  h3  when the  b1 -knight replaces the knight on  f3 . Black can now achieve ... e5  with }7...Nc6 8.h3 Bxf3 9.Nxf3 e5 { but without the light-squared bishop his position lacks punch. White simply strengthens his centre with }10.c3 { and develops with  Qb3 , targeting Black's weakened queenside. } )( { The move }6...Nbd7?! { is met by the thematic }7.e5 { and Black's knight on  d7  is quite passive. After }7...Nd5 8.c4 Nb4 9.exd6 exd6 10.Bf1 { with  a3 ,  Nc3  and  h3  to come White enjoys a comfortable space advantage when Black has problems developing his queenside, especially the light-squared bishop. } )
7. d5{ White stops Black's plan immediately. Black won't get a position with a King's Indian structure after ... e5 . }
7. Nb4{ This is an alternative, Black wants to take the bishop on  d3  and gain some space on the queenside by ... a5 . }
8. Bf1{ White keeps the bishop. }
8. Bg4{ Black threatens to take on  f3  and then double White's f-pawns as the queen must remain on  d1  to protect the  c2 -pawn. }
9. Na3{ White develops and defends the pawn on  c2 . }
9. e5( { Black goes for a KID structure. In case of }9...a5 10.h3 Bd7 11.c3 Na6 12.Bf4 { White will aim for the  e5 -push. } )
10. h3( { This is the only exception to the usual rule to always take en passant when Black goes for  ...e5 . It's possible even here, for example }10.dxe6 fxe6 11.h3 Bxf3 12.Qxf3 Nh5 13.Qb3 { with rather unclear play, but the main move is just stronger because of the difficulty of the stranded knight on  b4  to return to the game. } )
10. Bc8{ If Black takes on  f3  his kingside play will lack the necessary control of the light squares, while if Black retreats to  d7  White continues in the same manner with  c3  and  b4 . }
11. c3{ The knight has a very tough time getting back into the game. }
11. Na6
12. b4{ Taking away the  c5 -square. The knight on  a6  is stranded and needs even more time to go to  b8  and  d7  but even on  d7  it doesn't have clear prospects. This means that White's queenside play is so much faster than Black's play on the other side of the board as  Rb1 ,  c4 - c5 ,  Nc4  come very fast. }
