[White "1) ...g6 Systems: Introduction"]
[Black "...g6 Systems: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6( { When Black plays }2...g6 { there are two openings that he can choose from - the King's Indian Defence (KID) and the Grunfeld. While the former cannot be avoided, the latter can be, and this is what my choice is all about. } )
3. Nf3
3. Bg7
4. e3{ This move allows White to avoid the Grunfeld Defence by not putting a knight on  c3  before Black has committed with the d-pawn.  To my mind, the Grunfeld is an equivalent to the Najdorf - a dynamic, yet positionally sound opening, with a lot of theory that gives Black excellent counterchances. The Grunfeld was Kasparov's main opening for more than a decade and this says a lot about its objective value. The Grunfeld is very difficult to tame in view of its inherent dynamism, making it an excellent choice for active players. While the Grunfeld offers many choices for White, today's theory confidently claims that Black is more than fine against all of them. Therefore White players usually hop around changing the lines they play in every game and rely on one-game ideas.  All these considerations led me to the logical conclusion that it is much easier and very practical to avoid the Grunfeld! The price White has to pay for avoiding it is a more modest choice against the KID, but this choice leads to very interesting and original positions, not unlike the more ambitious choices, so the benefit of this approach is obvious without any serious shortcomings. }
