[White "2) ...g6 Systems"]
[Black "...g6 Systems #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6{ With the fianchetto Black intends to play either the King's Indian Defence (KID) or the Grunfeld Defence. While the KID cannot be avoided, the Grunfeld can be, and White's next two moves are aimed at exactly that. }
3. Nf3( { White doesn't play }3.Nc3 { because after }3...d5 { we land in the Grunfeld Defence. Therefore White first develops the kingside, postponing the development of the knight on  b1  until the moment when Black commits the d-pawn. } )
3. Bg7
4. e3( { This system became very popular after GM Alexander Grischuk used it with great success to beat GM Ian Nepomniachtchi, one of the biggest proponents of the Grunfeld, in 2013. Its popularity continues to this day.  White's idea is simple - without a knight on  c3  the Grunfeld doesn't really work because after the exchanges in the centre with }5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 { , }{ White can continue with  e4 , hitting the knight on  d5  and Black can no longer take on  c3  (because the square is empty now!) and continue with ... c5 , attacking White's centre. He would be forced to move the knight from the centre, but this will give White time to consolidate and not allow the typical Grunfeld counterplay. } )
4. O-O
5. Be2{ Still waiting with the development of the knight on  b1 . As you can see, White has more useful moves than Black - he can castle, play  Qc2  and so on. Black is already hard-pressed to move the d-pawn and continue with his development. }
5. c6( { This is a rare choice, Black wants to transpose to the Schlechter Variation of the Slav Defence (arising after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 g6 5.Nc3 Bg7 { ). I say rare because there aren't many KID or Grunfeld players who also employ the Schlechter Variation, known for relatively passive play. } )
6. O-O( { White can also start with }6.Nbd2 { . The idea of the development of the knight on  d2  is two-fold: one is not to transpose to the Schlechter Slav and two is to keep the long diagonal for the bishop open, after White expands on the queenside with  b4  and  Bb2 . } )
6. d5
7. Nbd2{ The knight on  d2  dissuades Black from capturing on  c4  because in that case, after  Nxc4 , White will have excellent control of the  e5 -square. }
7. Bf5( { Black can also develop with }7...Bg4 { , but that doesn't alter White's plan of queenside expansion with }8.b4 { , }{ followed by  Bb2 ,  a4 ,  b5  etc. } )( { In case Black stops the expansion with }7...a5 { , then }8.b3 { with  Bb2  will finish the development for White. Then he can continue with  Rc1 ,  Ne5  or  a3 ,  Bc3  and  b4 , resuming the queenside expansion. } )
8. b4{ White's plan is simple, he expands on the queenside with the intention of playing  a4  and  b5 . }
8. Nbd7
9. a4{ Continuing the plan. The bishop stays on  c1  for now as it can also be developed on  a3  in some cases. }
9. Ne4{ Threatening ... Nc3 , so the bishop should now be developed on  b2  to stop that threat. }
10. Bb2
10. Nxd2
11. Nxd2{ White has easy play, the queen comes to  b3 , the rook to  c1 , and  b5  is the move to aim for. }
