1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6{ With the fianchetto Black intends to play either the King's Indian Defence (KID) or the Grunfeld Defence. While the KID cannot be avoided, the Grunfeld can be, and White's next two moves are aimed at exactly that. }
3. Nf3( { White doesn't play }3.Nc3 { because after }3...d5 { we land in the Grunfeld Defence. Therefore White first develops the kingside, postponing the development of the knight on  b1  until the moment when Black commits the d-pawn. } )
3. Bg7
4. e3( { This system became very popular after GM Alexander Grischuk used it with great success to beat GM Ian Nepomniachtchi, one of the biggest proponents of the Grunfeld, in 2013. Its popularity continues to this day.  White's idea is simple - without a knight on  c3  the Grunfeld doesn't really work because after the exchanges in the centre with }5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 { , }{ White can continue with  e4 , hitting the knight on  d5  and Black can no longer take on  c3  (because the square is empty now!) and continue with ... c5 , attacking White's centre. He would be forced to move the knight from the centre, but this will give White time to consolidate and not allow the typical Grunfeld counterplay. } )
4. O-O
5. Be2{ Still waiting with the development of the knight on  b1 . As you can see, White has more useful moves than Black - he can castle, play  Qc2  and so on. Black is already hard-pressed to move the d-pawn and continue with his development. }
5. d5{ This move would be the choice of the inexperienced Grunfeld player who can no longer wait for the development of the knight on  b1 . But this is exactly what White's set-up is aimed against. }
6. cxd5
6. Nxd5
7. e4{ This is the point - Black cannot avoid this attack with tempo by exchanging on  c3 , like in the Grunfeld, and the knight on  d5  must lose time now to move away from the attack. }
7. Nb6( { I once faced the worse option }7...Nf6?! { and after }8.Nc3 { White had a full centre with little compensation for Black. Play can continue with }8...c5 9.d5 e6 10.Bg5 h6 11.Be3 b6 12.Qd2 { , }{ attacking the pawn on  h6  with  O-O  and  Rad1  to follow when White's play will evolve around supporting the passed  d5 -pawn. } )
8. O-O{ White finishes the development of the kingside. He wants to defend his pawn centre with  Be3  and  Nbd2  (or  Nc3 ). }
8. Bg4( { Black puts pressure on White's centre in Grunfeld fashion, but it's much less effective here. In case of }8...c5 9.d5 e6 10.Bg5 Qd7 11.Nc3 { White has easy development. Taking the pawn is very dangerous for Black as he has to give up his strong fianchettoed bishop: }11...exd5 12.exd5 Bxc3?! 13.bxc3 Qxd5 14.Qc1 { with excellent compensation for White in view of Black's weakened dark squares around his king. } )( { A move like }8...Nc6 { just allows White to solidify his centre with }9.Be3 Bg4 10.Nbd2 { and Black painfully lacks his Grunfeld-like counterplay against White's central pair. A sample line is }10...f5 10.exf5 Bxf5 11.Rc1 { with a further  Nb3 - c5 . } )
9. Nbd2{ Here we see another advantage of the delay of the development of the knight from  b1 : it can also go to  d2 , ready to replace the knight on  f3 , thus maintaining a strong defence of the  d4 -pawn. }
9. e5( { This is Black's best bet. In the aforementioned game Nepomniachtchi chose }9...Nc6?! { and after }10.d5 Nb8 11.a4! { (intending to harass the knight on  b6 ) he was already in trouble. } )( { Similarly, }9...c5 10.dxc5 N6d7 11.h3 Be6 12.Nb3 { gives White an advantage as it's not so easy for Black to regain the pawn, unless he gives up the bishop pair with }12...Bxb3 13.Qxb3 Nxc5 14.Qc2 { , when White's bishop pair is the main factor in the position. } )
10. dxe5{ White naturally takes the pawn. }
10. Nc6
11. h3{ A useful move to open a luft for the future and forcing the bishop to retreat. }
11. Be6( { Taking the knight on  f3  gives White the free advantage of the bishop pair after }11...Bxf3?! 12.Nxf3 Nxe5 13.Nxe5 Bxe5 14.Qc2 { with ideas of  a4 - a5  to harass the knight on  b6  (a typical advance in similar positions as the knight have a safe spot anywhere) and  f4  to advance with the pawn majority, when White will expand in the centre and decide on future pawn advances as appropriate. } )
12. Nb3( { Another use for the knight on  d2  - from  b3  it aims to jump to  c5 , a square from where it poses unpleasant threats against the bishop on  e6  and the pawn on  b7 . A good alternative is the move }12.Qc2 { . } )
12. Qxd1( { In case of }12...Nxe5 13.Nxe5 Bxe5 14.Qc2 { White has a pleasant position, threatening  Nc5  and wanting simply to develop with  Be3 ,  Rd1 , possibly  f4  etc. } )
13. Rxd1
13. Nxe5
14. Nxe5{ With this exchange White frees the path of the f-pawn so he can activate his pawn majority. }
14. Bxe5
15. f4{ Natural expansion on the kingside for White. }
15. Bg7
16. Nc5{ White's has a very pleasant endgame: his pawn majority in the centre is more active than Black's on the queenside and the knight on  c5  exerts pressure on Black's position. }
16. Bc4
17. Bf3{ Safely defending the pawn on  e4  and intending to win the pawn on  b7 . Black is now under pressure and his best option is to give up the pawn and seek compensation, which is not so easy to muster. }
