5. c5{ With this move Black wants to transpose to the Benoni in case White pushes  d5 . While that is perfectly possible, White has an easier solution. }
6. dxc5{ With this exchange White obtains a pawn structure that is very easy for him to play. Its essence is in the control of the  d5 -square: after  Nc3  White would control that square three times. If allowed, he will then develop with  b3 ,  Bb2  and after preparation will play  Nd5 , obtaining space advantage. This is the ideal scenario for White, which, if Black is careful, shouldn't really happen. }
6. Qa5+{ This is another way to regain the pawn. }
7. Bd2{ White covers with the bishop and transfers it to the long diagonal to oppose Black's fianchettoed bishop. }
7. Qxc5
8. Bc3{ Completing the bishop transfer. }
8. d5( { An attempt to solve the issue with the space disadvantage by exchanging the  c4 -pawn. In case Black aims for a Hedgehog setup with }8...d6 { White develops with }9.Nbd2 Qc7 10.O-O b6 11.b4 Bb7 12.Qb3 { with the rooks coming to  c1  and  d1 . Then one positional idea to have in mind is the knight transfer to  c3  by removing the bishop from that square and going  Nb1 - c3 , with the idea to eventually jump to  d5 . Otherwise White will try to advance further on the queenside with moves like  Nd4 ,  a4 , possibly  Qb2 ,  Nb3  and  a5 . } )
9. cxd5{ The pawn on  c4  was hanging, so White doesn't waste time and captures on  d5 . }
9. Nxd5( { It's possible to take with the queen, }9...Qxd5 10.Nbd2 b6 11.Bc4 Qh5 12.O-O { with  Rc1 ,  Qb3  etc. to come. In these symmetrical positions, White's play is easier thanks to his better central control and more active pieces. } )
10. Bxg7{ Naturally, White exchanges Black's strong bishop. }
10. Kxg7
11. Nbd2{ The knight develops and allows for  Rc1 , targeting the exposed queen on  c5 . }
11. e5( { This move vacates the  e7 -square for the queen. Black can also play in other ways, for example }11...Nc6 12.Rc1 Qa5 13.O-O Rd8 ( { The pawn on  a2  is taboo in view of }13...Qxa2? 14.Nc4 { with the threat of  Ra1  trapping the queen and  Qxd5 , winning the knight) } )14.Nc4 Qc7 15.Qb3 { with easier play for White as his pieces are better placed and Black's queen still hasn't found a safe spot. } )
12. Rc1{ Activating the rook with tempo. }
12. Qe7( { Following the idea, especially as }12...Qb6?! 13.Bc4 { gives White the initiative. } )
13. Ne4{ White uses his development advantage to activate his pieces even more. Now the knight on  d5  is attacked and in case it moves White can play  Qd6 . }
13. Qb4+( { After }13...Nb6 14.Qd6 { White obtains a favourable endgame. } )
14. Nfd2{ After castling the knight can come to  c4  and target the  d6 -square. }
14. Rd8( { The pawn on  b2  is taboo, }14...Qxb2? 15.Rb1 Qxa2 16.Bc4 { wins the knight on  d5 . } )
15. O-O{ The king is safe now and the knight on  d2  can enter the game. }
15. Nc6( { The pawn on  b2  is still taboo, }15...Qxb2? 16.Nc4 Qb4 17.Ncd6 { is winning for White as the knight on  d5  is hanging and it cannot move away in view of  Nf5  (check!) winning the rook on  d8 . } )
16. a3{ Attacking the queen and intending to gain space with  b4  next. }
16. Qe7( { Again Black cannot take on  b2 , }16...Qxb2? 17.Nc4 { and Black loses material, for example }17...Qa2 18.Ra1 { traps the queen. } )
17. b4{ White wants to continue with  Qb3  or  Qa4  and further advance with  b5 . He has some initiative on the queenside where he can also use the  c5 -square or even at a later stage double rooks on the c-file. }
