10. Nf8{ Here I'd like to describe the possible plans and scenarios that can happen in the middlegame. Black's piece arrangement is pretty automatic: ... h5 , ... N8h7 - g5 , ... Bf5  and then ... h4 - h3  to weaken the light squares on White's kingside.  If the pawn on  e4  is attacked Black will defend it with ... Qe7 . If Black manages to get his pawn to  h3 , forcing White to respond with  g3 , then he can continue play on the light squares by exchanging the light-squared bishops with ... Bg4  and using the  g4 -square for his knight. White shouldn't allow this, so a correct reaction to Black's ... h4  is to play  h3 , preventing Black's pawn advance.  With a white pawn on  h3  and provided White has castled short, Black has two possible ways to attack:  1. to push ... g5 - g4 , but this weakens the  f4 -square so the knight manoeuvre  Ne2 - f4  gains in strength, or  2. to sacrifice a piece on  h3 , which is most often dealt with  Bf1 ,  Qd1 - f1  and/or  Kh2 . }
