1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. g6{ With the fianchetto Black intends to play either the King's Indian Defence (KID) or the Grunfeld Defence. While the KID cannot be avoided, the Grunfeld can be, and White's next two moves are aimed at exactly that. }
3. Nf3( { White doesn't play }3.Nc3 { because after }3...d5 { we land in the Grunfeld Defence. Therefore White first develops the kingside, postponing the development of the knight on  b1  until the moment when Black commits the d-pawn. } )
3. Bg7
4. e3( { This system became very popular after GM Alexander Grischuk used it with great success to beat GM Ian Nepomniachtchi, one of the biggest proponents of the Grunfeld, in 2013. Its popularity continues to this day.  White's idea is simple - without a knight on  c3  the Grunfeld doesn't really work because after the exchanges in the centre with }5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 { , }{ White can continue with  e4 , hitting the knight on  d5  and Black can no longer take on  c3  (because the square is empty now!) and continue with ... c5 , attacking White's centre. He would be forced to move the knight from the centre, but this will give White time to consolidate and not allow the typical Grunfeld counterplay. } )
4. O-O
5. Be2{ Still waiting with the development of the knight on  b1 . As you can see, White has more useful moves than Black - he can castle, play  Qc2  and so on. Black is already hard-pressed to move the d-pawn and continue with his development. }
5. d6{ With this move Black enters KID territory. }
6. Nc3{ Now that the Grunfeld is no longer an option, White can develop the knight on  c3 . It's important not to castle too early, as sometimes this gives White additional options like castling queenside. }
6. Nbd7( { This is the typical KID move - Black prepares the  ...e5  push. In case of }6...c5 { (Black still wants a Benoni, but without allowing White's option of  dxc5  as on the previous move.) }7.O-O { shows that White is not forced to push  d5  nor to take on  c5 . Maintaining the tension is easy for White since he can continue with  b3  and  Bb2 . } )
7. b4( { This is a fresh development. The main line goes }7.O-O e5 8.Qc2 Re8 9.Rd1 { and is analysed in detail in the model game  Grischuk-Caruana . With  b4  White immediately advances on the queenside, and by postponing castling the possibility to castle long appears in some lines, leading to very sharp play. } )
7. e5{ Black continues with the standard KID play. }
8. Bb2{ White completes the development of his light pieces. }
8. Re8
9. Qb3{ White advances his queenside play while keeping the king in the centre. }
9. e4( { This is still possible even with a white king still on  e1 . It's the sharper choice compared to the capture on  d4 . The waiting move }9...c6 { is possible, but it allows White to play in the centre after }10.O-O e4 11.Nd2 Nf8 12.d5! { with ideas like putting the knight on  d4 , or  dxc6  and  b5 , weakening the light squares in the centre. } )
10. Nd2{ No other reasonable square for the knight to retreat to. }
10. Nf8{ Here I'd like to describe the possible plans and scenarios that can happen in the middlegame. Black's piece arrangement is pretty automatic: ... h5 , ... N8h7 - g5 , ... Bf5  and then ... h4 - h3  to weaken the light squares on White's kingside.  If the pawn on  e4  is attacked Black will defend it with ... Qe7 . If Black manages to get his pawn to  h3 , forcing White to respond with  g3 , then he can continue play on the light squares by exchanging the light-squared bishops with ... Bg4  and using the  g4 -square for his knight. White shouldn't allow this, so a correct reaction to Black's ... h4  is to play  h3 , preventing Black's pawn advance.  With a white pawn on  h3  and provided White has castled short, Black has two possible ways to attack:  1. to push ... g5 - g4 , but this weakens the  f4 -square so the knight manoeuvre  Ne2 - f4  gains in strength, or  2. to sacrifice a piece on  h3 , which is most often dealt with  Bf1 ,  Qd1 - f1  and/or  Kh2 . }
11. a4{ White continues with his queenside play, where he wants to play  a5 - a6 , weakening the light squares on Black's queenside. Like White on the kingside, Black shouldn't allow this and should meet  a5  by playing ... a6 . Then White can try to open the queenside by playing  b5 , while another idea is the  d5  push, freeing the  d4 -square for a knight ( Ne2 - d4  or  Nb5 - d4  in case Black hasn't played ... a6  are the manoeuvres White utilises to take advantage of that square). }
11. h5{ Black continues with his plan. }
12. a5{ White does the same, intending  a6 . }
12. a6( { Black should stop  a6  as that would give White access to the  b5 -square and also the  c6 -square, in case of either  axb7  or  ...b6  by Black. To illustrate White's idea in addition to the extra option of castling long: }12...Bf5?! 13.a6! b6 14.b5! { (fixing the queenside weaknesses) }14...h4 15.h3! { (White doesn't repeat Black's mistake and doesn't allow ... h3 ) }15...N8h7 16.O-O-O! { This is the idea of keeping the king in the centre - with the queenside safe, it will now be White who will attack on the kingside by  Rdg1  and  g3 , opening the g-file. He will combine this play with play in the centre by  d5  and then utilise the  d4 -square. } )
13. O-O{ White can also castle queenside, but with the queenside not closed as in the last comment the position becomes very sharp. }( { Here's a sample line: }13.h3 Bf5 14.O-O-O b6 15.axb6 cxb6 16.Rdg1 { with  g4  to come when both sides will go after each other's kings. } )
13. Bf5( { Black continues with his intended set-up. Exchanging the light-squared bishops with }13...Bg4?! { only helps White after }14.h3 Bxe2 15.Nxe2 g5 16.d5! g4 17.Ng3! gxh3 18.gxh3 { is a sample line where the opening of the kingside is in White's favour - after  Kh2 ,  Rg1  White is first to use the open g-file in addition to the  d4  and  f4  squares for his knights. } )
14. Rfb1{ White prepares to open the queenside by pushing  b5  and places the rook on the b-file in advance. The rook also frees the  f1 -square for the bishop and after  Qd1  (to lend extra support to the light-squares on the kingside,  g4 -in particular, especially in case of ... g5 - g4  by Black) the rook won't be trapped on  f1 . }
14. h4{ Intending ... h3 . }
15. h3{ Of course, White shouldn't allow Black to push ... h3 . }
15. N8h7( { Black keeps both options open,  ...Ng5  or  ...g5 - g4 . To illustrate the usefulness of the  Qd1  idea, here's what happens if Black goes berserk: }15...Qd7 16.Qd1 Bxh3? 17.gxh3 Qxh3 18.Qf1 { with  Qg2  next and the queen defends the king with White being a piece up. } )
16. Qd1{ White consolidates the kingside and removes the queen from in front of the  b1 -rook. }
16. Ng5{ Black introduces ideas of a sacrifice on  h3 . }
17. Bf1{ A simple defensive move, getting rid of any threats on the kingside. Now Black's kingside play comes to a standstill, for example }
17. Qd7
18. b5{ And now the sacrifices on  h3  don't work: }
18. Bxh3( { Or }18...Nxh3?! 19.gxh3 Bxh3 20.Bxh3 Qxh3 21.Qf1 { with a transposition to the line after 18... Bxh3 . } )
19. gxh3
19. Nxh3+
20. Bxh3
20. Qxh3
21. Qf1{ The queen joins the defence and White is simply a piece up. }
21. Qf5
22. Qg2{ White's king is safe and White is a piece up with continuing play on the queenside. Other ideas are  Ne2 - f4  or  d5 ,  Ne2 - d4 . }
