5. d6{ The most critical line is when Black plays for an attack on the kingside with ... Nbd7 , ... e5 - e4  etc. All the other lines give White pleasant play. }( 5...d5?! { It's worth knowing why the Grunfeld is no longer possible for Black. }6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.e4! { There is no exchange on  c3 , so the knight stays on the board and generally just gets in the way. }7...Nb6 8.O-O { White has a full pawn centre and Black lacks the typical Grunfeld counterplay against it. }8...Bg4 9.Nbd2! { White simply replaces the knight on  f3  in case Black takes it, safeguarding the centre. This is another benefit of keeping the knight on  b1 . } )
