[White "4) Benoni: Introduction"]
[Black "The Benoni: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5{ The Benoni is a sharp, but risky opening for Black. }
3. d5
3. e6{ In the Modern Benoni Black voluntarily creates a weak pawn on  d6  in order to obtain a queenside majority and play on the semi-open e-file. }( 3...e5 4.Nc3 d6 { The Czech Benoni resembles a KID. White has a space advantage in a closed centre that he can use to stay flexible and play on both wings. }5.e4 { with the idea of  Bd3  and  Nge2 , which is a very flexible development that doesn't allow kingside attack by Black (there is no knight on  f3  to attack and White can strengthen the kingside by  f3 ) while at the same time it allows White to play on both sides of the board. Black has two ways of development now, to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop a-la KID, or to develop it on  e7 , with the aim to exchange it by ... Bg5 . White develops the same against both, and very often it is White who attacks on the kingside. } )( 3...g6 { The delayed Benoni. Black tries to stay flexible with the e-pawn and will move it to  e6  or  e5  at a later stage. }4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 d6 6.Nf3 { The development with  Nf3  and  Be2  is different from what White plays against the Czech Benoni, the reason being that White plans to derail Black's plans to transpose to a Benoni-like position with ... e6xd5 , or to a KID position by ... e5  by taking on  e6 . Therefore it makes sense to keep the d-file open. }( { There is also an additional reason for not choosing the  Bd3 ,  Nge2  set-up and this is because after }6.Bd3 O-O 7.Nge2 e6 8.O-O exd5 9.exd5 { ( }9.cxd5 { leads to a well-established Modern Benoni position)   }9...Ng4! { with the idea of ... Ne5 , Black obtains good play. } )6...O-O 7.Be2 { White keeps the d-file open and anticipates Black's next move. }7...e6 { or }7...e5 { , which makes no difference as White takes en passant. }8.dxe6 { This is the idea of the whole system. White saddles Black with a backward pawn on  d6  and obtains the  d5 -square for the knight. Black gets free piece development in return. }8...Bxe6 9.O-O { White wants to consolidate the queenside and put pressure on the  d6 -pawn. } )
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. Bf4{ This system took away most of Black's dynamism in the Benoni by limiting the counterplay - the pawn on  e3  prevents counterplay on the e-file (no pawn on  e4 ) and the queenside is controlled by  a4 . This variation has become one of the main reasons for the decline in popularity of this sharp opening and is the perfect choice for restraining the aggressive player who thrives on active play. In addition to this, White's play is simple with moves like  h3  (to prevent ... Bg4  and allow for  Bh2 ),  Nd2 - c4 ,  Be2 ,  a4  and  O-O . }
