4. d6
5. e4{ Now Black has two plans at his disposal - to develop the bishop to  e7  or  g7  (which will look very much like a KID). In both cases White's development is the same:  Bd3  and  Nge2 . }
5. Be7
6. Bd3{ White develops in the same way as in  the line with 5...g6 . }
6. O-O
7. Nge2{ This flexible set-up is well-adapted for play on both wings. }
7. Ne8( { This is Black's main plan when developing the bishop on  e7  - by playing  ...Bg5  Black wants to exchange the bad bishop. In case of }7...Nbd7 8.Ng3 { targets the  f5 -square and with the knight on  g3  White can start the advance of the h-pawn, for example }8...g6 9.Bh6 Re8 10.h4 { when the threat is  h5  and if Black stops it by }10...Bf8 11.Be3 h5 { then White regroups with }12.f3 { followed by  Qd2 ,  O-O-O ,  Rdg1 ,  Nf1  and  g4 . } )( { Another alternative for Black is }7...Nh5 8.g3 Bg5 9.Bxg5 Qxg5 10.Qd2 Qe7 { (the endgame after the exchange of queens is better for White since he can play on both wings) }11.f3 { followed by  h4 ,  O-O-O ,  g4  etc. with an attack on the kingside. } )
8. Ng3{ With the knight on  g3  White takes control of the  f5 -square and also supports the advance of the h-pawn. }
8. Bg5{ Black follows the plan to exchange the passive bishop. }
9. Bxg5{ White lures the queen to  g5  in order to win tempo by pushing the h-pawn. }
9. Qxg5
10. h4{ The advance of the h-pawn will be quite annoying for Black. }
10. Qe7
