11. Na6( { Black must somehow develop, but it isn't easy. For example, putting a knight on  d7  allows  Nf5 . In case of }11...g6 { (controlling the  f5 -square) }12.h5 { comes followed by  f3 ,  Nf1  and  g4 , with an attack on the kingside. } )( { A move like }11...a6 { is met by }12.a4 { and again Black is short of good options, for example }12...Nc7 13.f3 { when the knight will move from  g3  to  f1  or  e2  to allow for  g4 . } )
12. Nf5( { The most direct approach. Others are also possible, for example }12.f3 Nac7 13.Nf1 { (intending  g4 ) }13...f5 14.Qg5! Qxg5 15.hxg5 f4 16.Kf2 { when White can play on both wings with  a3  and  b4  on the queenside and  g3  on the kingside. } )( { Another option is }12.O-O-O Nac7 13.Rdg1 { intending  Nf5  followed by  g4 . } )
12. Bxf5
13. exf5{ White's plan is simple - advance the kingside pawns as far as possible. }
13. Nf6
