3. d5
3. e5{ This the Czech Benoni. Black closes the centre and will then need to decide whether to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop or to develop it on  e7 . }
4. Nc3{ White develops normally and takes control of the centre. }
4. d6
5. e4{ Now Black has two plans at his disposal - to develop the bishop to  e7  or  g7  (which will look very much like a KID). In both cases White's development is the same:  Bd3  and  Nge2 . }
5. g6{ The fianchetto leads to KID positions where Black had already closed the centre with ... c5 . }
6. Bd3{ White develops the pieces in the centre. From  d3  the bishop controls the  f5 -square, an important prophylactic measure against Black's typical plan of ... f5 . }
6. Bg7
7. Nge2{ The knight is flexible on  e2 . It doesn't block the f-pawn, so White can strengthen the centre with  f3 ; it can easily go to  g3 , from where it helps White exercise greater control of the  f5 -square. From  g3  the knight can also access the  h5 -square (in case of ... f5 ,  exf5   gxf5 ) or it can be further relocated via  f1  to  e3 . }
7. O-O
8. Bg5{ Petrosian's pin is very unpleasant for Black in the KID structures. Its aim is to slow down Black's kingside play by pinning the knight that needs to move if Black is to execute the ... f5  break. The bishop on  g5  also provokes the ... h6  move, a weakening move (Black no longer controls the  g6 -square and has less control over the light squares in case the  b1 - h7  diagonal is opened) and a possible hook for White after  Qd2 , when the pawn on  h6  will be under attack. }( { Apart from  Bg5 , White has a good alternative in }8.h3 { , }{ preparing  g4 . White playing and attacking on the kingside is a common theme in these lines. } )
8. h6{ Black needs to get rid of the pin before White plays  Qd2 , stopping ... h6 , when it will be very troublesome to get rid of the annoying bishop. }
9. Be3{ The natural retreat for the bishop, especially as harassing it with ... Ng4  only helps White. White's plan now includes the moves  Qd2 , attacking the pawn on  h6 ,  f3 , strengthening the centre, covering the  g4 -square, and  O-O , castling short, even though castling long is also possible. }
9. Nbd7( { Black must develop somehow. The following line serves to illustrate the problems with }9...Ng4?! 10.Bd2 f5 11.f3 Nf6 12.exf5 gxf5 13.Qc2 { and Black has problems defending the pawn on  f5  and risks coming under attack after }13...Ne8 14.O-O-O { with  g4  to come. } )
10. f3{ White follows the plan, while Black is very passive without the option to play ... f5  under acceptable circumstances. Whenever Black tries to push ... f5 , White uses the opening of the kingside to start an attack there, for example }
10. Nh7( { White's play is similar after }10...Ne8 11.Qd2 f5 12.exf5 gxf5 13.O-O { (safeguarding the king and avoiding ... Qh4  checks - without that check the pawn on  h6  is now hanging) and Black has problems defending the pawn on  h6  because }13...Kh7 { runs into }14.g4 { , while after   }13...Qf6 14.Rae1 { the queen takes away the  f6 -square from both knights when White will prepare the  g4 -push after  Kh1  and possibly  Rg1  when the opening of the kingside allows him to take full advantage of his superior and more harmonious development. } )
11. O-O( { A plan with long castling is also strong, for example }11.Qc2 a6 12.h4 { with  O-O-O  to come, but in these cases Black can at some moment go berserk and start sacrificing pawns left (with ... b5 ) and right (with ... f5 ) which objectively shouldn't be good, but in practice can muddy the game to a considerable extent. } )
11. f5
12. exf5{ This is always the reaction to Black's ... f5 . It effectively kills off any counterplay Black may have on the kingside, for example by playing ... f4  and launching a pawn storm with ... g5 - g4  in KID style. After the exchange on  f5  the black pawn on that square will need constant attention and it is White who will do the attacking on the kingside. }
12. gxf5
13. Qc2{ White immediately pinpoints the vulnerability of the  f5 -pawn and the whole  b1 - h7  diagonal. }
13. Qf6{ Black defends the pawn, but all his pieces step on each other's toes now - the queen takes away the natural square from both knights. }
14. Ng3( { The sharper }14.g4 { is also strong, as Black cannot move the  f5 -pawn due to the hanging knight on  h7 . With  Ng3  White increases the attack on the  f5 -pawn, but also threatens  Nh5 , going after the fianchettoed bishop on  g7 . Black can barely move while White can prepare  f4  with a possible piece sacrifice after ... e4 ,  Ncxe4  when he can develop an attack on Black's kingside. } )
