6. Nf3{ The simplest development of the knight to  f3  and bishop on  e2  is aimed at leaving the d-file open (so the bishop doesn't go to  d3 ) as anticipation of Black's ... e6 / e5  move. }
6. O-O
7. Be2{ The bishop on  e2  doesn't block the d-file since White's intended reaction to ... e6 / e5  is to take on  e6  and exert pressure on the backward  d6 -pawn. }
7. e6( { Black can also play }7...e5 { , but the reaction is the same, }{ . } )( { The alternatives are }7...Bg4 8.h3 Bxf3 9.Bxf3 Nfd7 ( { If now }9...e5?! { the reaction is again the en passant capture }10.dxe6 fxe6 11.e5! { with devastating effects. } )10.O-O Na6 11.Be2 { with a comfortable position for White with the bishop pair and the space advantage. Black's problem is that he cannot execute the ... b5  push and is devoid of counterplay, while White prepares an advance on the kingside with  Bg5 ,  Qd2 ,  f4  etc. } )( { In case of }7...Na6 8.O-O Nc7 9.Bf4 { (intending  Qd2 ) }9...Nh5 10.Bg5 h6 11.Be3 { White prepares  Qd2 ,  h3 ,  Rfe1 ,  Bf1 , with the aim to push  e5 . If Black pushes the e-pawn White takes en passant and after  Qd2  and  Rad1  puts pressure on the  d6 -pawn. } )
8. dxe6{ The key idea in this line. It doesn't give an advantage, but the main purpose is to give the position a different character compared to the usual Benoni/KID positions that the second player is aiming for. }
8. Bxe6( { The other recapture }8...fxe6 { is met by the typical }9.e5! dxe5 10.Qxd8 Rxd8 11.Nxe5 { when White enjoys the superior pawn structure in the endgame. The bishops will most likely come to  f3  and  e3 , putting pressure on Black's queenside. } )
9. O-O{ White finishes the development of the kingside. }
9. Nc6
10. h3{ A useful preparatory move. It takes away the  g4 -square from the black knight (useful for harassing the bishop on  e3  and for executing the ... Ng4 - e5  manoeuvre) and secures the  h2 -safe spot for the bishop in case it is developed to  f4 . }
10. Qb6( { One of the several moves Black can try in this not-so-well explored position. The immediate }10...Nd4 { is possible, when White should decline the pawn sacrifice because it gives Black good compensation and should continue with }11.Bd3! Nd7 12.Nxd4 cxd4 13.Ne2 { , }{ stabilising the position in the centre thanks to the excellent control of the light squares. Next come  b3  and  Bb2  when Black will need to defend the pawn on  d4 . } )( { After }10...Re8 11.Be3 { (controlling the  d4 -square) }11...Qb6 12.Rb1 { White will continue with  Qd2  when an idea is to play  Ng5  and go after the bishop on  e6 , while the  f4 -push can also give good chances of an attack if the pawn advances further. } )( { The move }10...Nd7 { is met by }11.Qxd6 Nd4 12.Nxd4 cxd4 13.Nd5 Re8 14.Qb4 Bxd5 15.cxd5 Rxe4 16.Bf3 { when White has a dangerous passed pawn on  d5  in addition to the bishop pair in a relatively open position. } )
11. Bd2( { While the move }11.Rb1 { is also possible, the idea of the development of the bishop is to cover the knight on  c3  as White plans  b3  and  Bd3 . Then the rook can come to  c1 . } )
11. Nd4( { Taking the pawn on  b2  is risky for Black, as }11...Qxb2?! 12.Rb1 Qa3 13.Nb5 Qa6 14.Nc7 { wins the exchange. After }14...Qxa2 15.Bc3! { is an important zwischenzug threatening to trap the queen with  Ra1 . The queen must escape, but after }15...Qa3 16.Rb3 { followed by  Nxa8  and  Rxb7  White's material advantage gives him the better chances. } )
12. b3{ White solidifies the queenside and plans to improve the position of the bishops with  Bd3  and  Be3 . }
12. Nd7( { Black's play is based on the dark squares, especially  d4  and  e5 , so the other knight aims for the  e5 -square. After }12...Rfe8 13.Be3 Nxe2 14.Qxe2 { the position is pleasant for White as the plan is to put pressure on the backward  d6 -pawn along the d-file and combine it with a timely jump to  d5 . } )
13. Rc1{ The rook is removed from the vulnerable diagonal. }
13. Ne5
14. Ng5{ An important idea for White. The black knights in the centre may look imposing, but they are not really effective. White starts his own play by freeing the path for the f-pawn to advance. If Black moves the bishop from  e6  then  Nd5  is coming. }
14. Rae8{ In case of  Nxe6  Black intends to recapture with a pawn, so in that case the rook on  f8  will already be on a semi-open file. }
15. f4{ White advances with the f-pawn. }
15. Nec6
16. f5{ The f-pawn marches forward. }
16. Bd7
17. f6{ In three moves the f-pawn attacked three opponent's pieces, now shutting the fianchettoed bishop on  h8 . }
17. Bh8
18. Bg4{ Both sides have strong outposts in the centre ( d4  for Black,  d5  for White). With the last move White exchanges the limited light-squared bishop for Black's good bishop. White's ideas include the advance of the h-pawn,  Be3  and  Nd5 . The position is very complicated with chances for both sides. }
