[White "5) Benoni"]
[Black "Benoni #4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6( { This move characterises the Modern Benoni. Black wants to open the e-file by taking on  d5 , which will also create a queenside majority that he intends to advance. The Old Benoni arises after   }1.d4 c5 2.d5 e5 { and is covered in the  Various First Moves  chapter because in that line the knight isn't on  f6  just yet. } )
4. Nc3{ White develops normally, both knights come out and then the bishop is developed on  f4 . }
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. Bd6{ This is the dubious Snake Benoni, whose idea is to send the bishop via  c7  to  a5 , but this doesn't really work, so most often the bishop drops back to  f8 , either allowing White to push  d6  or leaving Black with a very bad version of the Modern Benoni, with the bishop on  f8  rather than the long diagonal. White follows the set-up from the main line, the only difference being that since the dark-squared bishop cannot come to  f4 , it goes to  g5 , pinning the knight on  f6 . }
6. Nf3
6. O-O
7. Bg5{ The pin on the knight is quite annoying. }
7. Re8
8. e3{ As in the Modern Benoni, White keeps the pawn on  e3  in order to avoid Black's counterplay against the  e4 -pawn. }
8. a6( { A typical move for Black, aiming for  ...b5 . In case of }8...Bc7?! 9.d6! Ba5 10.Bc4 { Black's position is very sad as he can barely move and the whole queenside is undeveloped, while White threatens  Qb3 ,  Nd5  etc. } )
9. a4{ White stops Black's expansion. }
9. Bf8( { The whole idea of the Snake Benoni has to be scrapped, as again }9...Bc7?! 10.d6! Ba5 11.Bc4 { gives White an overwhelming advantage. } )
10. d6( { The pawn advance is very strong. It shuts the bishop on  c8  and opens the  a2 - g8  diagonal for  Bc4  and  Qb3 , which would expose the pawn on  f7 . White can also play in a slower manner with }10.Bd3 d6 11.h3 { , }{ followed by  O-O  when White will slowly prepare the advance in the centre with  Nd2 , and  e4  with typical Modern Benoni motifs. } )
10. Re6{ White sacrifices the pawn on  d6  but wins either the exchange or the pawn on  f7  after }
11. Bc4
11. Rxd6
12. Qb3{ The pawn on  f7  is going to fall, so Black's best chance is to give up the exchange. }
12. Re6( { Defending with }12...Qe8 { is even worse after }13.Bxf6 Rxf6 14.Nd5 Rc6 15.Ng5 { and White's overwhelming attacking forces give a decisive advantage. } )
13. Bxe6
13. fxe6
14. e4{ White is an exchange up and Black has little to show for it. The immediate threat is  e5 . White will continue with  O-O  and put a rook on the d-file, while Black still needs to finish development of the queenside. }
