[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. e6( { This move characterises the Modern Benoni. Black wants to open the e-file by taking on  d5 , which will also create a queenside majority that he intends to advance. The Old Benoni arises after   }1.d4 c5 2.d5 e5 { and is covered in the  Various First Moves  chapter because in that line the knight isn't on  f6  just yet. } )
4. Nc3{ White develops normally, both knights come out and then the bishop is developed on  f4 . }
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. Bf4{ This system has become one of White's most effective options against the Modern Benoni. The bishop is placed on the  h2 - b8  diagonal, from where it keeps a constant eye on Black's weak pawn on  d6 . White then plays  e3 , in order to keep the e-pawn protected, thus eliminating Black's counterplay on the e-file.  After finishing development with  h3  (opening a retreat on  h2  for the dark-squared bishop and preventing ... Bg4 ),  Be2  and  O-O  White usually sends the knight from  f3 , via  d2 , to  c4 , for further pressure on Black's queenside, especially the weak  b6 -square and the pawn on  d6 . A typical idea for White to paralyse Black's queenside is  a5 , sometimes followed by  Ra3 - b3 , while the plan to advance with the e- and f-pawns is also common once White has completed development. }
7. Bg7( { Often Black starts with }7...a6 { , with the idea to provoke }8.a4 { and avoid the possibility of  Qa4  on the next move. However, since this is not White's intention in this repertoire, whether Black starts with }{   }7...a6 { or }7...Bg7 { makes little difference. } )( { An attempt to 'trick' White with the early }7...Na6?! { (now  Bxa6  is not possible) backfires after }8.e4 Nc7 9.Qd2! Bg7 10.Bxd6! Qxd6 11.e5 Qd8 12.exf6 Qxf6 ( { Or }12...Bxf6 13.O-O-O { with  d6 - d7  next. } )13.d6 Ne6 14.Bb5 Bd7 15.Bxd7 Kxd7 16.O-O { with a big advantage to White - Black's king is stuck in the centre while White has a powerful passed pawn on  d6 , which will be used in the attack on the 'centralised' king. } )
8. h3( { The move }8.Qa4 { leads to massive complications after }8...Bd7 9.Qb3 b5 { , }{ where the lines can easily go 25-30 or even 40 moves deep. There is no need to go into these complications, especially as White's play is simple and safe with the natural development. } )( { The move }8.h3 { is aimed at preventing ... Bg4 , a common idea for Black in the Benoni, as getting rid of the light-squared bishop (Black's most passive piece) is considered very useful for the second player. The other idea of the move is to secure a safe spot on  h2  for the dark-squared bishop. } )
8. O-O
9. e3{ White wants to complete the development of the kingside by  Be2 , or  Bd3 , and  O-O . }
9. a6( { A typical move for Black, preparing  ...b5  and covering the  b5 -square. In the past White's move order was considered imprecise because of the option }9...Na6 { (intending ... Nc7  to prepare ... b5 ) but then it was discovered that the surprising exchange }10.Bxa6! bxa6 11.Rc1! { is an important continuation. The rook leaves the vulnerable long diagonal and defends the knight on  c3  as preparation for  b3 , which would cement White's queenside and kill off Black's counterplay on the b-file. White then continues simply with }11...Rb8 12.b3 a5 13.O-O Ba6 14.Re1 { and prepares  e4 - e5  and/or  Nd2 - c4  with excellent play. } )( { All the other options are possible after the inclusion of }9...a6 10.a4 { , moves that are inevitably played, so they are covered on the next move. } )
10. a4{ White stops Black's possible expansion. }
10. Nh5{ An attempt at a blitzkrieg attack by ... f5 - f4 , but it doesn't work. }
11. Bh2{ The move  8.h3  came in handy. }
11. f5
12. Be2{ The bishop eyes the knight on  h5 . }
12. f4( { In case of }12...Qe7 13.O-O Nd7 14.Nd2 Nhf6 15.Nc4 Ne8 16.a5 { White establishes the desired bind. } )
13. O-O{ White is fully developed while Black's queenside pieces are still on their starting positions. }
13. Qe7( { Black can try other moves, but White obtains an advantage against all. For example if }13...Nd7 14.Nd2! { (hitting the knight on  h5 ) }14...fxe3 15.fxe3 Rxf1 16.Qxf1 Ne5 17.Bxh5 gxh5 18.Bxe5! { (a powerful exchange of the two bishops for the two knights) }18...Bxe5 19.Nc4 { and the knights will bring home the win as ideas like  Ne4 ,  Qf3  and  Rf1  give White a decisive attack. } )( { After }13...Bh6 14.Nd2! fxe3 15.fxe3 Bxe3 16.Kh1 { with  Nc4  next is similarly decisive. } )( { In case of }13...fxe3 14.fxe3 Qe7 15.Qd3! { , }{ just like in the main line, intending  Ne4  or  Qe4 , is again excellent for White. } )
14. Qd3{ White establishes control of the  e4 -square, threatening  Ne4  or  Qe4 . The latter is important as the exchange of the queens will expose the weak pawn on  d6  even further - a piece defending it (the queen) will be exchanged. }
14. Bf5( { A natural move, attacking the queen and fighting for the  e4 -square. After }14...Bh6 15.Rae1 { with the idea of  Bd1  White's army is very harmoniously poised for the battle in the centre. } )( { In case of }14...Nd7 15.Rfe1 { White is ready for the opening of the e-file by taking on  f4 , while the ideas of  Bd1  and  Qe4  are still valid. } )
15. Qd2( { White has a good alternative in }15.e4 Bc8 16.e5! { (before Black establishes blockade with ... Nd7 - e5 ) }16...dxe5 17.d6 { with excellent compensation. By retreating the queen White uses the fact that Black's last move blocked the f-file and increases the attack on the pawn on  f4 . } )
15. g5( { Black tries to keep the bishop on  h2  imprisoned by keeping the pawn on  f4 . After }15...fxe3 16.Qxe3 { White returns to the idea of exchanging the queens, targeting the pawn on  d6 . } )
16. exf4{ White opens the e-file. }
16. gxf4( { Taking with the knight allows the cute shot }16...Nxf4? 17.Nxg5! { , }{ destroying the defence of the knight on  f4 . } )
17. Qd1( { A pretty move, the queen went to  d3  three moves ago and then retreated one square at a time back to  d1 ! The idea is to free the  d2 -square for the knight and hit the knight on  h5 . It's far from the only good move, for example there is nothing wrong with the natural }17.Rae1 { or }{ . } )
17. Bh6{ Black must try to hold on fast to the pawn on  f4  as without it the  d6 -pawn won't live for long, being targeted by the sniper on  h2 . }
18. Re1( { Now }18.Nd2 { is met by }18...Ng7 { , }{ so White continues to improve the position, threatening  Bd3 . } )
18. Nd7{ Black should also finish development. }
19. Bd3{ White wants to exchange the light-squared bishops as the bishop on  f5  covers the weak  e6 -square. }
19. Qf7
20. Bxf5
20. Qxf5
21. Ne4( { The rook invasion with }21.Re6 { is also strong. Black cannot defend the pawn on  d6  as } )
21. Qg6
22. Nh4{ Exposes the over-burdened black queen. }
