14. O-O
14. Rb8
15. Qc2{ Both sides have finished the development. The middlegame lies ahead where White's plans are the more concrete ones. Since fixing the queenside with  a5  is no longer possible, White turns the attention to the centre, where the main idea is to start pushing the e- and f-pawns with  e4  and  f4 . }
15. Qc7{ Black tries to become active on the queenside, threatening ... c4  and ... b5 . }
16. b3{ The simplest way to stop Black's expansion. White controls the  c4 -square. }
16. Bb7{ There isn't a better square for the bishop. Black attacks the pawn on  e4 . }
17. e4{ White follows the plan, defending the  d5 -pawn in the process. Now the threat is  f4 . }
17. g5{ Black tries to maintain the centralised knight, but moving the g-pawn leaves the  f5 -square unattended. }
18. Nc4{ White cannot chase away the knight by  f4 , but exchanging it and improving the pawn structure is not bad either. }
18. Nxc4( { Black would like to keep the knight on  e5 , but after }18...Nfd7 19.Ne3 { the gaping hole on  f5  starts to tell. } )
19. bxc4{ White is dominating here. The pawns on  d6  and  b6  are weak, as is the  f5 -square. White can attack the pawn on  b6  along the b-file and can prepare the pawn breaks  f4  and  e5 . }
