9. a6( { A typical move for Black, preparing  ...b5  and covering the  b5 -square. In the past White's move order was considered imprecise because of the option }9...Na6 { (intending ... Nc7  to prepare ... b5 ) but then it was discovered that the surprising exchange }10.Bxa6! bxa6 11.Rc1! { is an important continuation. The rook leaves the vulnerable long diagonal and defends the knight on  c3  as preparation for  b3 , which would cement White's queenside and kill off Black's counterplay on the b-file. White then continues simply with }11...Rb8 12.b3 a5 13.O-O Ba6 14.Re1 { and prepares  e4 - e5  and/or  Nd2 - c4  with excellent play. } )( { All the other options are possible after the inclusion of }9...a6 10.a4 { , moves that are inevitably played, so they are covered on the next move. } )
10. a4{ White stops Black's possible expansion. }
10. Qe7( { Black defends the pawn on  d6  in order to be able to develop the knight on  d7 . If Black tries }10...Ne8 { with the same idea, plus intending ... f5 , White plays }11.Be2 Nd7 12.O-O { and now the immediate }12...f5?! { is met by }13.Ng5! { targeting the  e6 -square when  Ne6  would lead to an exchange on that square, freeing the  d5 -square for the knight and the light-squared bishop will be dominating from  c4 ; while preparing the push with }{   }12...h6 { is met by }13.e4! { when Black cannot push ... f5  anymore. } )
11. Be2{ White continues with the usual development. }
11. Nbd7{ So does Black. }
12. O-O
12. Ne8( { The main move. Black has alternatives, but the character of the ensuing play remains the same, for example }12...Rb8 13.a5 Ne8 14.Nd2 Ne5 15.Qb3 { with the threat of  Bxa6  or  Na4 - b6 . } )( 12...Nh5 13.Bh2 f5 14.Nd2 Nhf6 15.Nc4 Ne8 16.a5 { with a similar bind. } )( { Black can try to stop  a5  by }12...b6 13.Nd2 Ne8 14.Nc4 Rb8 { but then White advances in the centre with }{ . In all cases White has a dominating position. } )
13. a5{ Fixing Black's queenside. }
13. Rb8( { The immediate }13...b5 { is only weakening, after }14.axb6 Nxb6 15.e4 Nd7 16.Qd2 Nc7 17.Bc4 { with  Rfe1  next White dominates the centre while Black is passive with a weak queenside. } )( { In case of }13...Ne5 14.Nd2 f5 15.Qb3 g5 { an important typical idea is }16.Bxe5! Bxe5 17.Na4 { when White's knights settle down comfortably on  b6  and  c4 . } )
14. Nd2( { The alternative }14.Ra3 { also looks good. } )
14. Ne5( { Keeping an eye on the  c4 -square. After }14...Nc7 15.Nc4 Ne5 { the same idea from the previous note }16.Bxe5! Bxe5 17.Na4 { stabilises White's advantage thanks to the excellent knights. } )
15. Qb3( { Threatening  Bxa6 . Here taking on  e5  is less good as }15.Bxe5 Qxe5 16.Nc4 Qg5 { gives Black some counterplay. } )
15. Nc7{ Black defends the pawn. }
16. Bg3( { White introduces the idea of  f4 . Note the cute trap after the standard, but in this position not good, }16.Na4? Nxd5! 17.Qxd5 Be6 18.Qe4 Bf5 { with a repetition as the queen cannot escape the attacks. } )
16. f5( { After }16...Bd7? 17.f4 Nd3 { (thanks to this trick Black avoids losing a piece, but he is still lost, only positionally) }18.e4 Nb4 19.e5! dxe5 20.Nde4 { and with the threat of  d6  Black is defenceless as }20...Ne8 21.Bf2! { pinpoints the weak pawn on  c5 . } )
17. Na4{ Now when Black doesn't have the  f5 -square at the disposal of the bishop this maneuver is strong. The knight wants to land on  b6 , but there is also the threat of  Nxc5  because ... dxc5  is met by the discovered check  d6 . Any threat of ... g5  and ... f4  is met by  f4  when Black's best piece, the knight on  e5 , is forced to leave the centralised position. Even visually it's clear that White's extremely solid position is in control, Black can hardly muster any counterplay. }
