1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5( { Black has three versions of the Benoni at his disposal: the Modern Benoni with }3...e6 { , the delayed Benoni by }3...g6 { , or the Czech Benoni with }3...e5 { . } )
3. e6( 3...g6 { Black delays the undermining ... e6  move. }4.Nc3 Bg7 5.e4 d6 6.Nf3 O-O 7.Be2 { White keeps the d-file open as he plans to take on  e6 . }7...e6 8.dxe6 { White saddles Black with a weak pawn on  d6  and obtains the  d5 -square for the knight. }8...Bxe6 9.O-O Nc6 10.h3 { A useful preparatory move, guarding the  g4 -square so that  Be3  cannot be attacked by ... Ng4 , or in case of  Bf4 , the bishop can retreat to  h2  if necessary. }10...Qb6 { Black develops freely as way of compensation for the structural deficiencies. }11.Bd2 { White defends the knight on  c3  before consolidating the queenside with  b3 . }11...Nd4 ( { It's worth knowing that the pawn on  b2  is not hanging because after }11...Qxb2?! 12.Rb1 Qa3 13.Nb5 Qa6 14.Nc7 { White wins the exchange. } )12.b3 { White has secured the queenside structure and on the next move will remove the rook from the long diagonal with  Rc1 . Then he will turn the attention to the kingside with  Ng5 ,  f4 - f5 . } )( 3...e5 4.Nc3 d6 5.e4 { Black has a choice - to play ... g6  and ... Bg7  or ... Be7 . }5...g6 ( 5...Be7 { The idea after ... Be7  is to exchange the bishop after moving the knight from  f6  and ... Bg5 . }6.Bd3 { White develops the pieces in the centre. Next is  Nge2 . }6...O-O 7.Nge2 Ne8 { This is Black's main plan. }8.Ng3 { White prepares for play on the kingside. The knight controls the  f5 -square and also helps the advance of the h-pawn. }8...Bg5 9.Bxg5 Qxg5 10.h4 Qe7 11.Qd2 { The queen takes over the control of the dark squares from the exchanged bishop. White's plan is to attack on the kingside by  Nf5 , or  f3 ,  Nf1 - e3 ,  g4  etc. } )6.Bd3 Bg7 7.Nge2 O-O 8.Bg5 { The aim of Petrosian's pin is to slow down Black's kingside play by pinning the knight that needs to move if Black is to execute the ... f5  break. The bishop on  g5  also provokes the ... h6  move, a weakening move (Black no longer controls the  g6 -square and has less control of the light squares in case the  b1 - h7  diagonal is opened) and a possible hook for White after  Qd2 , when the pawn on  h6  will be under attack. }8...h6 9.Be3 Nbd7 ( { Attacking the bishop with }9...Ng4?! { only helps White after }10.Bd2 f5 11.f3 Nf6 12.exf5 gxf5 13.Qc2 { and Black has problems defending the pawn on  f5  and risks coming under attack after }13...Ne8 14.O-O-O { with  g4  to come. } )10.f3 { White is very flexible and will attack on the kingside. He can do so by either castling kingside or queenside. When Black plays ... f5  after  exf5   gxf5  the  f5 -pawn will come under attack after  Ng3  and  Qc2 . } )
4. Nc3
4. exd5
5. cxd5
5. d6
6. Nf3
6. g6
7. Bf4{ One of the most solid lines against the Modern Benoni. }
7. Bg7
8. h3{ It's important to stop ... Bg4 . }
8. O-O
9. e3
9. a6( { An important idea to know is that after }9...Na6 { , }{ intending ... Nc7 , White plays }10.Bxa6! bxa6 11.Rc1 { , }{ followed by  b3 , securing the queenside and killing off Black's counterplay on the b-file. } )
10. a4( { White must stop  ...b5 . Very often White will continue with  a5  to fix Black's queenside and the  b6 -square in particular. Black has several plans here, the blitzkrieg with }10...Nh5 { and ... f5 - f4 , which is almost losing for him, or variations of the positional plan of ... Qe7  (or ... Re8 ) followed by moving the knight from  f6  and playing ... f5 , to control the  e4 -square.  White's play is universal, he plays  Nd2  (to control the  e4 -square and prevent ... Ne4 ),  Be2 ,  O-O  and if allowed  a5 , to fix the  b6 -square, which will then be followed up with  Nc4 - b6 ,  Qb3  and/or  Ra3 - b3 . White is squeezing Black on the queenside while Black has very little active counterplay left. In case Black stops  a5  by playing ... b6 , White will turn the attention to the centre and will try to expand with  f4  and  e4 , ultimately achieving the  e5  break. } )
