[Black "The Benko Gambit: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5{ The Benko is an active counterattack against  1.d4 . Black wants to clear up the a- and b-files on the queenside, put the king's rook on  b8  and exert pressure along them. It's not an easy opening to play against because Black's plan in the main line is both simple and automatic. }
4. cxb5( { I have played both }4.Nf3 { and }4.Qc2 { against the Benko and I was doing great with these lines. However, not so long ago it was discovered that Black's best in both cases is closing down the queenside with }4...b4! { . With the queenside closed like this and with Black having a space advantage, I stopped liking White's position, especially as Black is the first one to play in the centre with ... e6 . Therefore another idea was necessary. } )
4. a6
5. e3( { This is the solid approach against the Benko. Going for the main lines with }5.bxa6 { gives Black the character of play that is typical of the opening and in addition to this the modern developments after }5...g6 { (instead of the traditional main line with }5...Bxa6 { ) are quite complex to navigate. } )( { After }5.e3 { White focuses on development and doesn't mind returning the extra pawn for harmonious play. Black's best line with }5...axb5 { has nothing in common with the typical Benko positions, while insisting on them with }5...g6 { lands Black in an inferior version of those positions. In both cases the psychological advantage is with White. } )
