[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. c5
3. d5
3. b5
4. cxb5{ White takes the first pawn, but will not take the second. }
4. a6( { A rare alternative is }4...e6?! 5.Nc3 exd5 6.Nxd5 Bb7 7.e4! { when Black is really in bad shape with no compensation for the pawn because taking on  e4  leads to a lost position after }7...Nxe4? 8.Bc4 { followed by  Nf3  and  O-O  when White's initiative is too strong. } )
5. e3{ A solid approach, somewhat akin to White's approach in the Modern Benoni. Now the pawn on  b5  is defended by the bishop and first and foremost White wants to finish the development. }
5. g6{ This is an alternative approach, more in Benko-style, as Black fianchettoes the dark-squared bishop and still hopes for counterplay on the a- and b-files. }
6. Nc3{ White won't take on  a6 . The idea is to secure the queenside by  a4  and develop the kingside with  Nf3 ,  Be2  and  O-O . If Black doesn't do something faster then White will achieve the desired development and remain a pawn up. }
6. Bg7
7. Nf3{ White continues with the intended plan. }
7. O-O( { Taking on  b5  when White can recapture with the bishop in one go is not very good for Black, for example }7...axb5 8.Bxb5 Ne4 { (a tricky attempt, but easily defused) }9.Bd2! { keeps things under control on the queenside. } )
8. a4{ By keeping the pawn on  b5  White achieves two objectives - the first is to keep the queenside files closed, so Black doesn't achieve the typical Benko play with the open a- and b-files; and the second is to limit the scope of Black's pieces on the queenside, primarily the knight on  b8 , by controlling both  a6  and  c6 . }
8. d6{ Black still hopes that White will take on  a6  and sets up the Benko pawn structure. }
9. e4( { It's a game of patience - White doesn't want to move the bishop from  f1  and waits for Black to take on  b5  so that the bishop can take on  b5  in one go. By pushing  e4  White increases control of the  d5 -square and opens the diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. Another useful move in this respect is }9.Ra3!? { , }{ which places the rook on a defended square and allows for  axb5  in some positions. } )
9. axb5( { Black blinks first, but this is the best try. The alternatives are }9...Nbd7 10.h3 Bb7 11.Be3 { when White keeps making useful developing moves waiting for Black to take on  b5  when  Bxb5  comes without losing a tempo. Black's problem is that there aren't many useful moves to create any counterplay, so taking on  b5  must happen sooner rather than later, though }11...axb5 12.Bxb5 Ne8 13.O-O Nc7 14.Qd2 { gives White control and an extra pawn. } )( 9...e6 { is an attempt to undermine White's centre, }10.dxe6 Bxe6 11.Be2 d5 12.e5 Ne4 13.O-O { is good for White with  Bf4  next. The position no longer resembles a Benko but White is still a pawn up for no real compensation. } )( { Undermining the centre after }9...Bb7 10.Ra3 e6 { is met by }11.dxe6 fxe6 12.e5! { (a standard reaction when Black recaptures with the f-pawn) }12...dxe5 13.Qxd8 Rxd8 14.Ng5 Re8 15.f3 { with a great endgame for White. } )
10. Bxb5{ The preferred way to capture in these positions, though here it is also forced. }
10. Ba6{ Black threatens to take on  b5  when White would lose a pawn because of the pin on the a-file and the overburdened knight on  c3 , having to defend both the bishop on  b5  and the pawn on  e4 . }
11. Bxa6{ The simplest solution. The threat of ... Bxb5  is eliminated and White wins a tempo to castle. }
11. Nxa6
12. O-O{ White's king is safe and now the plan is to combine stabilisation of the queenside (by  Nb5  and/or  b3 ) with the central thrust  e5 . }
12. Nd7( { If }12...Qa5 13.Bd2 { only helps White, who threatens  Nb5  now. } )
13. Rb1( { Removing the rook from the long diagonal and the a-file. White has many promising options like }13.Ra3 { (with the same idea to remove the rook from the  a1 -square), }{   }13.Bg5 h6 14.Bd2 { ,   }13.Qe2 { and even }13.h4 { . } )
13. Qa5
14. Bd2{ White defends the knight and now threatens  Nb5  and  b3 , the ideal set-up for White on the queenside: pawns on  a4  and  b3  and a knight on  b5 . }
14. c4{ Black tries to be active, intending ... Nc5 - d3 ( b3 ). }
15. Ne2( { The knight goes to  e2  and not on  b5  because with a knight on  b5  White cannot push  a5  in case of }15.Nb5 Qb6 { because the  a4 -pawn defends the knight. From  e2  the knight can come to  d4  and  c6  - this is the major drawback for Black when the  c5 -pawn advances - with no control of the  d4 -square a white knight can easily end up on  c6 . } )
15. Qc5( { Black controls the  d4 -square, but the queen takes away the  c5 -square from the knights. In case of }15...Qc7 16.Qc2 { is }{ the preparatory move before  Ned4 , covering the  e4 -pawn, because the immediate }16.Ned4? Nac5 { loses a pawn due to the double attack on the pawns on  e4  and  a4 . } )
16. Bc3{ A multipurpose move, exchanging the strong fianchettoed bishop and re-establishing control of the  d4 -square. White is a pawn up and after a possible  b3   cxb3 ,  Qxb3  Black will be hard-pressed to come up with compensation. }
