12. Qe7( { Black keeps the knight on  b8  in order to discourage White from taking on  a6 , when the knight can recapture on  a6  and aim for the weakened  b4 -square. To illustrate, }12...Nbd7 { allows }13.bxa6 Bxa6 14.b3 { with further  Nb5  and  Bb2 . } )
13. Qc2{ From  c2  the queen aids both  b3  and  e4 , in the first case by defending the knight on  c3  and in the second case by controlling the  e4 -square. }
13. a5( { This may look counter-intuitive, but it's Black's best option. Black gives White a protected passed pawn on  b5 , but obtains a blockading square on  b6 . Otherwise Black couldn't conveniently finish development, for example }13...Nbd7 14.bxa6 Bxa6 15.Bxa6 Rxa6 16.e4! d4 17.Nb5 { when White is a clear pawn up and has excellent squares for the knights on the queenside:  d3 ,  c4 ,  b5 . } )( { Pushing in the centre is even worse, }13...e5? 14.e4! d4 15.Bc4 Kh8 16.Nd5 { and White obtained control of the light squares in the centre. } )
