1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. d6{ The so-called Old Indian, when Black intends ... Nbd7 , ... e5 , ... Be7  and ... O-O , though the option of a transposition to the KID is also possible. }
3. Nf3{ Stopping ... e5 . Black has now three possibilities, but the good news from White's point of view is that he plays in the same manner against all three, in line with the proposed development against the KID. }
3. Nbd7( { Black wants to push  ...e5 . He can try to do so by first getting the bishop out, for example }3...Bg4 4.e3 Nbd7 5.Be2 e5 6.Nc3 Be7 7.O-O O-O 8.b4 c6 9.a4 { , and it's clear that White pursues the same plan as in the KID. Black can try to gain space by }9...e4 10.Nd2 Bxe2 11.Qxe2 d5 { , but even here White's queenside play is much faster after }12.Ba3 { followed by  b5 . } )( { Another move is }3...Bf5 4.Nc3 g6 { , }{ which is a mix of the KID and the odd bishop on  f5 . White simply exchanges it after }5.e3 Bg7 6.Bd3 Bxd3 7.Qxd3 O-O 8.e4 { with free play. Play can continue with }8...e5 9.d5 Nbd7 10.h3! { (intending  g4  and  O-O-O  with an attack on the kingside in case Black doesn't play ... c6  on the queenside) }10...Nc5 11.Qc2 c6 ( { Otherwise after }11...a5 12.Be3 Nfd7 13.g4! { gives White good chances on the kingside. } )12.Bg5 h6 13.Bxf6 Qxf6 14.Rd1 { and White has a favourable KID position with pressure on the d-file, as  dxc6  is always an option while Black cannot really take on  d5  because White will retake with a knight. } )
4. Nc3
4. e5
5. e3{ White develops in the same manner as against the KID as Black can still play ... g6  and transpose to that opening. }
5. Be7( { Black can still change his mind and opt for the KID with }5...g6 { . } )
6. Be2{ White's play is simple, he castles and then advances on the queenside. }
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. c6
8. Qc2{ White controls the  e4 -square and frees the  d1 -square for the rook. This set-up was examined in the model game  Grischuk-Caruana , which was a KID. }
8. Re8
9. Rd1{ White follows the plan. }
9. Qc7( { Moving away from the d-file. The move }9...Bf8 { is possible, but it doesn't change much for White after }10.b4 { . }{ With the queen on  c7  Black has a tactical idea in mind against White's immediate  b4 . } )
10. b3( { Black's idea is seen after the more natural }10.b4 d5! 11.dxe5 Nxe5 12.cxd5 Nxf3 13.Bxf3 Bg4! { and we see the importance of the queen on  c7  - in case White takes on  g4  after ... Nxg4  there will be a threat of ... Qxh2 . Black obtains counterplay in this line. } )
10. Bf8
11. Bb2{ White almost finished development. Next the rook will come to  c1  when White will start the queenside advance with  b4 ,  a4  etc. }
11. g6{ The bishop will be more active on the long diagonal, but then one wonders why Black didn't play the KID in the first place and put the bishop on  g7  on move 3? Taking on  d4  only opens the d-file for White, who will recapture with knight or rook and then put pressure on the pawn on  d6 . }
12. Rac1
12. Bg7
13. b4{ With a pawn on  b4  the advance  d5  is also possible as White controls the  c5 -square. The usual advance with  a4  and  b5  is also promising. Compared to the KID it looks like Black has certainly wasted time and hasn't managed to create any active play. }
