2. b6{ This early fianchetto of the light-squared bishop is similar to the QID, but the absence of a knight on  f3  and ... e6  makes things a little different. }
3. Nc3{ Natural development, White wants to play  e4 . }
3. Bb7{ In the QID Black has good control of the  e4 -square, but here White can challenge that control with a timely  f3 , thanks to the knight still being on  g1 . }
4. Bf4( { White's most forceful move is }4.Qc2 { , }{ intending  e4  and after }4...d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.e4 Nxc3 7.bxc3 { White has a strong pawn centre and an advantage. } )( { The move }4.Bf4 { is a practical choice, offering Black to transpose to the chapter on  ... e6  Systems . } )
4. g6( { This is not very good, but it's the only independent try. In case of }4...e6 5.a3 { we have a transposition to the chapter on  ... e6  Systems  arising after }{   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Bf4 b6 4.a3 Bb7 5.Nc3 { . } )
