5. Bg7( { In case of }5...Nh5 6.Bg5 { and  e4  next White established the centre. } )( { A try to play in Grunfeld-style after }5...d5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nxd5 Qxd5 8.e4 Qd7 9.Rc1 c6 10.Bc4 { leads to a very comfortable position for White with a strong pawn centre and easy development after  Ne2  and  O-O . } )
6. e4{ The bishop on  b7  is a poor piece now, biting on granite. }
6. d6
7. Qd2{ Introducing ideas like  Bh6  and  O-O-O , but White is very flexible and can also castle short. }
7. Nbd7( { In case of }7...O-O 8.Bh6 { is natural, followed by  O-O-O  and an attack on the kingside with  h4 - h5  etc. } )( { If Black stops  Bh6  by }7...h6 { then }8.Nh3 { followed by  Be2  completes development, when White can decide where to castle, while Black is lacking space and is not able to castle short because the pawn on  h6  is hanging. } )
8. d5( { Other moves are good, too, like }8.Be3 { or }8.Nge2 { . } )
8. Ne5{ This stops  Nge2 - d4  by attacking the pawn on  c4 . }
9. Nh3{ White can also develop the knight on  h3 . Next come  Be2 ,  O-O  and possibly  Bh6 , with a dominating position. }
