2. e5( { The Budapest Gambit is sometimes used for surprise value, but objectively it is not the best opening. The Two Knights Tango with }2...Nc6 { doesn't have an independent value as after }3.Nf3 e6 4.Bf4 { we have a transposition to the chapter on  ... e6  Systems , arising after }{   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Bf4 Nc6 4.Nf3 { . } )
3. dxe5{ Taking a pawn with tempo, few things are better than that. }
3. Ng4
4. e4{ An aggressive choice for White. The idea is to build a strong centre by gaining tempi against the wandering knight. }
4. Nxe5( { The most natural move, but Black can also try the sacrificial }4...d6 { after which best is }5.Be2! { with ideas to steer the game to a position similar to the main line after }5...Nxe5 6.Nc3 g6 7.f4 Nec6 8.Be3 { with subsequent  Qd2 ,  Bf3 ,  Nge2  and  O-O . } )( { In case of }4...h5 5.Be2 Nc6 6.Nc3 Ngxe5 7.Nf3 d6 8.Be3 { White 'only' has a strong grip on the centre and excellent development after  Qd2 ,  h3  and  O-O . } )
