[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6( { After }2...e6 { Black keeps great flexibility when it comes to his choice of openings. After }3.Nc3 { he can play the Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) with }3...d5 { or the Nimzo-Indian with }3...Bb4 { , apart from the sharper option of the Benoni with }3...c5 { . } )( { In case of   }3.Nf3 { there are even more options: the Benoni is still there after }3...c5 { , there is the Queen's Indian Defence (QID) with }3...b6 { and the Bogo-Indian with }3...Bb4 { .  After }3...d5 4.Nc3 { we have another round of options for Black: }4...c5 { is the Semi-Tarrasch, }4...c6 { is the Semi-Slav, }4...Bb4 { is the Ragozin Defence, }4...dxc4 { is the Vienna and }4...Be7 { is the QGD. All these openings are among the best ones in chess for Black (except perhaps the Benoni), most of them tested in World Championship matches. } )( { White can try to sidestep all these with   }3.g3 { and go for the Catalan, but the Catalan has a complex theory on its own. So what is White supposed to do if he wishes to avoid all these theoretical jungles? I have never been convinced by systems like the London or the Torre, let alone various Colles or Zukertorts.  With all this in mind, realising the vast amount of theory that White must know in order to deal with all these options, I turned my attention to a recent trend that evades all of the above and leads to relatively unexplored positions. A lot of these positions will be equal positions, but at least they will be NEW equal positions, unlike the heavily explored ones from all the openings mentioned earlier. } )
3. Bf4( { This move has received a serious surge in popularity in the past few years. It leads to positions that are less explored and leave space for creativity and independent investigation. Black has many choices now, but they are still less than all of the choices after }3.Nf3 { . } )
