1. d4
1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. Bf4{ A recent trend. This leads to novel and less explored positions as White avoids most of the openings Black can play against  1.d4 . With the bishop on  f4 , White can develop the queen's knight on  d2 , giving the position a more original flair. Naturally, Black has a wide variety of options now. }
3. Be7{ This is a tricky move. Black still wants to play the QGD, but waits for White to develop the knight on  c3  in order to be able to recapture with ... Nxd5 , hitting both the bishop on  f4  and the knight on  c3 . }
4. Nf3( { In case of }4.Nc3 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5! { is the difference compared to the Exchange Variation in the QGD - thanks to this recapture Black successfully simplifies the position. } )
4. d5
5. e3{ If White wants to avoid a direct transposition to the QGD then the knight should be developed on  d2  rather than on  c3 . }
5. O-O
6. Nbd2( { In case of }6.Nc3 { we are at the starting position of the big main lines in the QGD when White plays  Bf4 . } )
6. b6( { In case of }6...c5 7.dxc5 Bxc5 8.cxd5 { we have a transposition to the line arising after }{   }3...Bb4 4.Nd2 c5 5.dxc5 Bxc5 6.e3 O-O 7.Ngf3 d5 8.cxd5 { . } )
7. Bd3{ White has a compact development. The knight on  d2  will recapture on  c4  in case Black plays ... dxc4 . }
7. Bb7
8. O-O{ White finishes development, while Black should decide whether to develop with ... Nbd7  or to start play in the centre by taking on  c4  and/or pushing ... c5 . }
8. Nbd7( { Immediate play in the centre with }8...c5 9.dxc5 Bxc5 { leads to a transposition to the lines arising after   }3...Bb4 4.Nd2 c5 5.dxc5 Bxc5 6.e3 O-O 7.Ngf3 b6 8.Bd3 Bb7 9.O-O d5 { . } )( { Taking on  c4  opens the long diagonal, but improves the position of the knight on  d2 , }8...dxc4 9.Nxc4 Nbd7 10.Rc1 c5 11.Be2!? { (intending  Nd6  and wanting to recapture on  f3  with a bishop in case Black takes ... Bxf3 ) with a complex middlegame position where White's pieces are more actively placed. } )
9. cxd5{ When Black has a bishop on  b7  this capture more or less forces Black to take with a piece, as taking with a pawn would make the bishop very passive. When Black takes with a piece White obtains control of the  e4 -square, so the threat of the advance  e4  becomes real. }
9. Nxd5
10. Bg3{ Now White threatens  e4 . }
10. c5{ Black should strike in the centre sooner rather than later. }
11. Rc1{ Developing the rook on the file that should soon be opened. It also allows the bishop on  d3  to drop back to  b1  if necessary. }
11. Rc8( { In case of }11...cxd4 12.Nxd4 Nc5 { the bishop can safely go back to  b1  with }13.Bb1 { , }{ thanks to the fact that the rook is not on  a1  anymore. White can then continue to improve his pieces with  Nc4 ,  Qe2 , and  Rfd1  and will try to use the good position of the bishop on  g3  with ideas like  Nb5 , targeting the  d6 - and  c7 -squares. } )
12. Nc4( { There is a wide array of available options for both sides in this complex position with all the pieces on the board. White can also play }12.Qe2 { or }12.a3 { , }{ intending a possible  b4  after the pawns on  c5  and  d4  are exchanged. By placing the knight on  c4  White immediately targets the  d6 - and  e5 -squares, combining well with the bishop on  g3 . The immediate threat is  Nd6 . } )
12. N7f6{ Black defends the  d6 -square. }
13. dxc5( { There are other moves, as well, for example }13.Nce5 { or }13.Qb3 { . }{ By taking on  c5  White lures a black piece to  c5  in hope of exploiting its more exposed position. } )
13. Rxc5( { This may look unnatural, but it's better than }13...Bxc5 14.Qe2 { with  Rfd1  to come. These positions are deceiving, Black can quickly end up in trouble since his pieces are not that well-coordinated, for example if we continue the line with }14...Qe7?! { (a natural move, moving away the queen from the open d-file) }15.a3! { with the threat of  b4  suddenly the bishop is in trouble and }15...a5 16.e4 { doesn't save Black either as he loses material after }16...Nc7 17.b4 axb4 18.axb4 Bxb4 19.Nxb6 { . } )
14. Qb3{ Putting the queen on  e2  is also possible, but the queen on  b3  prevents ... Nb4  by controlling that square. The idea is the same, putting a rook on  d1 . The middlegame is very complex with a lot of tactical possibilities present thanks to all the pieces still being on the board. White will now continue with  Rfd1  and then piece play will ensue,  Nce5 , and  Be5 - d4  are some of the ideas. The pawn push  e4 - e5  should be carefully considered as it also leaves weak squares behind, but if it can be successfully played that would give White a tangible advantage in view of the control of the  d6 -square where a knight can nicely land. }
