3. Bf4{ A recent trend. This leads to novel and less explored positions as White avoids most of the openings Black can play against  1.d4 . With the bishop on  f4 , White can develop the queen's knight on  d2 , giving the position a more original flair. Naturally, Black has a wide variety of options now. }
3. Nc6( { This could be the choice of a player who plays the Two Knights Tango and it should easily transpose from there:   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 Nc6 3.Nf3 e6 4.Bf4 { . } )
4. Nf3{ White still keeps the knight on  b1  in order to be able to play  Nbd2 . }
4. Bb4+
5. Nbd2{ Now we have some sort of a Bogo-Indian where White has already developed the bishop on  f4 . }
5. d6{ Black's plan is to play ... Qe7  and push ... e5 . }
6. a3{ White gets the bishop pair now. }
6. Bxd2+
7. Qxd2( { Taking with the bishop is also possible, for example }7.Bxd2 e5 9.Bg5 h6 10.Bh4 g5 11.Bg3 Ne4 { with unclear play. } )
7. Qe7( { Black prepares  ...e5 . Postponing it for one move with }7...O-O 8.e3 Qe7 9.d5! e5 10.Bg5 Nb8 11.e4 { allows White to comfortably occupy the centre. White's next move will be  Bd3  and then he can even contemplate a kingside attack with  h3  (or  Rg1 ) and  g4 , especially if Black had played ... h6  to chase away the bishop to  h4 . } )
8. d5( { White can also start with }8.Bg3 e5 9.d5 { , which is a transposition. } )
8. e5( { If Black retreats the knight to  b8  it will allow White to take on  e6  and open the game in the centre. So, }8...Nb8 9.dxe6 Bxe6 10.e3 a5 11.b3 { (preventing ... a4 ) }11...O-O 12.Bd3 Nbd7 13.O-O { with  Nd4  next. White's play is easier, he can use the  b5 -square for the knight or if allowed he will take the bishop on  e6 . Another idea is the transfer of the bishop to  f3  via  e2 . } )
9. Bg3( { The sharp alternative }9.dxc6 exf4 10.cxb7 Bxb7 11.Qxf4 O-O 12.e3 { leads to a double-edged position where White is a pawn up while Black seeks compensation thanks to his lead in development. It's a possible line for White, as Black doesn't have a direct way to regain the material. } )
9. Nb8
10. Qc2{ Covering the  e4 -square - this prevents ... Ne4  and plans  e4 . }
10. a5{ Black wants to establish dark-square control on the queenside, similar to how Black plays in the KID structures. He wants to play ... Nbd7 - c5  and then possibly ... a4 , to fix White's queenside. }
11. Bh4{ White improves the position of the dark-squared bishop. }
11. Nbd7
12. Nd2{ From  d2  the knight controls the  b3 -square (important in case of ... a4  and ... Nc5  for Black) and frees the  f3 -square for the pawn, so White intends  e4 ,  f3  when the bishop can drop back to  f2  and also a pawn storm with  g4  will be possible. }( { Note that there is no time for }12.b3 { in view of }12...e4 13.Nd4 e3 { with unclear play. } )
12. a4( { Black can start with }12...Nc5 13.e4 { but after }13...a4 14.f3 { we have a transposition. Fixing the queenside is part of Black's plan as not playing ... a4  can allow White to play  b3  and prepare  b4  later on. } )
13. e4{ Taking up the centre. }
13. Nc5
14. f3{ A useful move, strengthening the pawn chain and allowing for both  Bf2  and  g4 . }
14. Bd7
15. Bf2{ By retreating the bishop White takes aim at the knight on  c5 . This is important in case Black wants to undermine the centre with ... c6 , as we will see in the next comment. }
15. b6( { This is better than }15...c6 { , which allows }16.Bxc5! dxc5 17.Bd3 { followed by  O-O-O  when White has a safe position with a better structure - the pawn on  d5  is a protected passed pawn. } )
16. O-O-O{ Plans with short castle are also possible, but this is more ambitious. }
16. O-O
17. Kb1{ White improves the position of the king by putting it on  a2 , where there will be no threats of a check with ... Nb3 . Additionally, once the king clears the  b1 -square, White can use that square to activate his knight with the manoeuvre  Nb1 - c3 . }
17. Rfb8
18. Ka2{ Continuing the plan. }
18. c6( { Black tries to obtain some activity on the queenside. Note that }18...b5? { is bad in view of }19.Bxc5! { (again this idea, which always needs to be considered when Black cannot recapture with the b-pawn) }19...dxc5 20.cxb5 Bxb5 21.Rc1 { and Black's queenside is in ruins. } )
19. dxc6{ An important move. This exchange gives White access to the  d5 -square (after  Nb1 - c3 ) and opens the d-file where Black's backward pawn on  d6  will need attention. }
19. Bxc6
20. Nb1{ The knight comes to the best square  c3  from where it controls the important light squares  a4 ,  b5  and  d5 . }
20. Ne8{ A useful manoeuvre for Black - the knight will be well-placed on  c7 , covering  b5  and  d5  and perhaps intending ... Ne6  to keep an eye on the  d4 -square. }
21. Nc3{ The knight arrived at its destination. }
21. Nc7
22. h4{ One of the many possible moves. The march of the h-pawn introduces AlphaZero ideas like  h5 - h6 . The position is very complex but it is Black who needs to guard his weaknesses, whether they be the pawns on  a4 ,  b6  or  d6  or the squares  b5  and  d5 . Black's knight jump to  b3  doesn't threaten anything, so White has little to worry about. One positional idea for White is to play  Nb5 , to provoke ... Bxb5 ,  cxb5  when the light-squared bishop will come to  c4  and become a strong piece. White won't rush with this idea, improving the position further with  Be3 ,  Qf2 ,  g4 - g5  etc. is another way to play. }
