1. Nf6
2. c4
2. e6
3. Bf4{ A recent trend. This leads to novel and less explored positions as White avoids most of the openings Black can play against  1.d4 . With the bishop on  f4 , White can develop the queen's knight on  d2 , giving the position a more original flair. Naturally, Black has a wide variety of options now. }
3. b6{ A move in line with the QID. It still offers Black a chance to play ... d5  later, but it keeps flexibility for the moment. }
4. a3( { Similar to the Petrosian Variation in the QID (  }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 b6 4.a3 { ) White prepares the development of the knight to  c3  by preventing the pin ... Bb4 . } )
4. Bb7( { Black can also play the move }4...Ba6 { , an option that also exists in the Petrosian line mentioned above. After }5.Qa4 { (stopping ... c5  in view of  Bxb8  and the bishop on  a6  is lost) }5...Bb7 6.Nc3 c5 7.d5! { White has the initiative, for example }7...exd5 8.cxd5 Nxd5 9.Qe4 Qe7 10.Qf3! { maintaining the pin on the long diagonal. White can also increase the pressure on the  d5 -knight with  Rd1  if necessary. White already has an advantage here, the line can be taken further after }10...Nxc3 11.Qxb7 Qe4 12.Qc8 Ke7 13.Bxb8 Qc2 { and here the key maneuver is }14.Qc7! { with the idea of  Qe5  (check) -  Qg5  (check) -  Qc1  and the queen is in time to defend the queenside. } )
5. Nc3{ White threatens  d5 , so Black's next move is practically forced. }
5. d5( { Without a knight on  f3  the move }5...Ne4?! { doesn't work so well for Black here because after }6.Nxe4 Bxe4 { White has the important move }7.f3! { with  e4  next, building a strong centre. } )
6. e3( { An interesting alternative is }6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.Nxd5 Qxd5 { (Black should keep the long diagonal open, otherwise the bishop on  b7  becomes a bad piece) }8.e3 { when Black has the options of }8...c5 { and }8...Bd6 { , both of which lead to interesting middlegames and are worth exploring further. } )
6. Be7{ This is a natural move. }
7. Nf3{ White develops normally now. }
7. O-O
8. cxd5{ White takes on  d5  because if he developed the light-squared bishop Black would have taken on  c4 , thus forcing White to lose a tempo with the bishop. }
8. Nxd5( { Black should keep the long diagonal open, as }8...exd5 9.Bd3 c5 10.O-O { is a slightly better middlegame for White because the bishop on  b7  is quite passive looking at the pawn on  d5 . } )
9. Nxd5{ With this move White opens the c-file. He intends to play  Rc1  and attack the pawn on  c7 . }
9. Bxd5{ What was said earlier about taking with a pawn applies here, too - that would leave the bishop very passive on  b7 . Black also cannot take with a queen as that drops the pawn on  c7 . }
10. Rc1{ Developing with tempo. }
10. c5{ Black gets rid of the attacked pawn. }
11. dxc5{ White needs to finish development so he gains time by capturing on  c5  and follows up with  Bd3 . }
11. Bxc5
12. Bd3{ The position is more poisonous for Black than it may appear at first sight. The bishops on  c5  and  d5  are subject to attacks (with  b4  and  e4 ) and there are also tactical threats based on  Bxh7 . }
12. h6( { This is Black's best, avoiding any  Bxh7  problems. How strong this sacrifice is can be seen after }12...Qe7? 13.Bxh7! Kxh7 14.Ng5 Kg6 15.h4 { with the threat of  Qg4  and White is winning, for example }15...f5 16.h5 Kf6 17.b4! Bd6 18.Qd4 e5 19.Qxd5 { . } )( { The same sacrifice gives White a very dangerous attack after }12...a5?! 13.Bxh7 Kxh7 14.Ng5 Kg6 15.h4 Kf6 { and now either the positional }16.e4 Bc6 17.Qh5 Ke7 18.O-O { with  b4  and  Rfd1  to come, or the sacrificial }{   }16.Rxc5!? bxc5 17.Bd6! { with excellent attacking chances. } )( { Another natural move that is not very good is }12...Nd7?! 13.b4 Be7 14.Bc7 Qe8 15.e4 Bb7 16.Bb5 { and Black loses material. These lines nicely illustrate how dangerous the position is for Black. } )
13. O-O{ With no sacrifice on  h7 , White can castle now. }
13. a5{ Stopping  b4  ideas. }
14. Qe2{ This is a harmonious set-up for White. The queen moves out of the d-file so that the  f1 -rook can take over the control of it. From  e2  the queen also supports the  e4 -push. }
14. Nc6( { Black should also finish development. In case of }14...Nd7 15.e4 Bb7 16.Bb5 { White has a serious initiative. } )
15. Bg3( { Advancing with }15.e4 { weakens the  d4 -square, which Black can use after }15...Bb3 16.Be3 Nd4 { . } )
15. Qe7
16. Nd2{ Intending  Ne4  to win the bishop pair. }
16. f5{ This stops  Ne4 , but weakens Black's position. }
17. Bb5{ A comfortable square for the bishop, not blocking the d-file. White's position is more compact, Black weakened the  b5  and  e5  squares and White's play will evolve around them. Ideas include  Rfd1 , the  e4 -break (but careful about ... Nd4 ),  Nf3 - e5  and even  Bc4 , exchanging the bishop on  d5  in order to get closer to the  e6 -pawn. }
