3. d5{ A move that the QGD player is likely to make. }
4. cxd5{ In line with the Exchange Variation in the QGD, White takes on  d5 . }
4. Nxd5( { After }4...exd5 5.Nc3 { we have a transposition to the QGD. } )
5. Bg3{ The bishop retreats and now the threat is  e4 . }
5. c5{ Attacking the centre. }
6. e4{ White continues with the plan. }
6. Nf6( { Moving away with tempo. It's possible to go to  b6  as well, }6...Nb6 7.Nf3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 { (the endgame after }8.Qxd4 { is also playable)   }8...Bb4 9.Nc3 O-O 10.Be2 { with  O-O  next and White will enjoy more freedom as Black has issues developing the bishop on  c8 , plus the knight on  b6  is not a great piece. White's plan will be to push  e5  if possible and then try to create threats on the kingside. } )
7. Nd2{ White develops and defends the pawn on  e4 , sacrificing the  d4 -pawn in the process. }
7. cxd4{ This is another way for Black to take the pawn. The drawback is that the  d4 -pawn now serves as a great cover for White's light-squared bishop that will find its best square on  d3 . }
8. e5{ A key move for White - the  e5 -pawn is the spearhead that will serve as foundation for the upcoming attack. }
8. Nd5
9. Ngf3{ White's plan is  Bd3 ,  Qe2  and then either  h4  or  O-O . Additional useful moves will be  a3  (to cover the  b4 -square and secure the safety of the bishop on  d3  by taking away the possibility of attacks with ... Nb4 ),  Rc1 , and  Re1 , all depending on circumstances. Of course, if White can regain the pawn without disrupting his smooth development he will gladly do so by capturing  Nxd4 . }
9. Nc6( { Black defends the pawn. Otherwise White will regain it while finishing development, for example }9...Be7 10.Bd3 O-O 11.a3 { and  O-O  with  Nxd4  are coming, or }{   }9...Nd7 10.Be2 { (staying away from ... Nc5  attacks in case the bishop goes to  d3 ) followed by  Nxd4  and/or  O-O . } )
10. a3{ An important move for White in these positions. The control of the  b4 -square secures the bishop on  d3  by avoiding ... Nb4  attacks. }
10. Be7( { The somewhat artificial }10...Nde7 { with the idea ... Nf5  was played by Giri, but what came out of it you can see in the model game  Nihal-Giri . } )
11. Bd3{ White's set-up is complete. Next will be to decide whether to castle or to play  h4 . }
11. O-O
12. O-O{ White plans to play with the pieces. The rooks will come to  e1  and  c1 , the bishop can drop back to  b1  to allow for  Qc2 , and the knight can come to  e4 , threatening  Nd6  or  Neg5 , depending on circumstances. }( { The alternative }12.h4!? { is also very exciting. It introduces various attacking ideas based on  Ng5 . After }12...f5 { (Black must play this move sooner rather than later, before White's attack gathers momentum) }13.exf6 gxf6 { (keeping control of the  e5 -square) }14.Ng5! fxg5 15.hxg5 { with  Qh5  coming gives White a very strong attack. Black should be able to defend, which would lead to a messy position, but it's not an easy task! } )
12. f5{ A necessary move for Black in these positions, either closing the  b1 - h7  diagonal or getting rid of the annoying pawn on  e5 . }
13. exf6{ Keeping the  b1 - h7  diagonal open and the bishop on  d3  active. }
13. gxf6( { This is the correct recapture for Black, keeping control of the  e5 -square. In case of }13...Nxf6?! 14.Re1 { Black is saddled with weaknesses on the e-file, the pawn on  e6  and the  e5 -square, and cannot solve the problem of the bad bishop on  c8 . } )
