3. Bb4+( { This move can be played by players who play the Nimzo-Indian or the Bogo-Indian. A move that leads to a transposition to the QGD is the strange-looking }3...Nh5 4.Bd2 d5 5.cxd5 exd5 6.Nc3 Nf6 7.Bf4 { and we are in QGD territory. } )( { Another rare move to mention is }{ . After }4.Nf3 d5 5.Nbd2 { White uses the prematurely exposed knight to speed up his development. He will continue with the usual moves  e3 ,  Bd3 , which will now attack the knight on  e4 . } )
4. Nd2( { One of the main points of  3.Bf4 , White is able to cover the check without allowing the exchange on  c3  as in the Nimzo-Indian, thus keeping his structure intact. Another advantage, compared to the Bogo-Indian (after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 Bb4 4.Nbd2 { ), is that the bishop is already developed on  f4  and not stuck on  c1 . } )
4. d5{ A move in line with the Ragozin Defence. }
5. a3{ As usual, White goes after the exposed bishop. }
5. Bd6( { Taking on  d2  is suspicious as after }5...Bxd2 6.Bxd2 { Black doesn't really have anything for the relinquished bishop pair. Taking the pawn on  c4  only opens the game for the bishops, }6...dxc4 7.e3 b5 8.a4 c6 9.axb5 cxb5 10.b3 { and White will regain the pawn. } )
6. Bg5{ The exchange on  d6  is possible, but by pinning the knight White hopes to limit the influence the knight on  f6  has on the centre, primarily by preventing ... Nxd5 . }
6. h6{ A useful move for Black to insert. }
7. Bh4{ White keeps the pin. }
7. O-O
8. e3{ White wants to complete development with the natural  Ngf3  and  Bd3 . }
8. b6( { The immediate }8...c5 { is possible. After }9.dxc5 Bxc5 10.cxd5 exd5 { (this was White's idea when playing  Bg5  earlier - Black is forced to play with an IQP) }11.Bd3 Nc6 12.Ngf3 d4 13.e4 { leads to a very interesting middlegame position. Black's passed d-pawn is safely blockaded and White will try to move forward the central majority, for example after  O-O ,  Ne1  and  f4 . } )
9. Ngf3{ The usual rule of thumb is to take on  d5  once Black had played ... b6 , but here that capture can be postponed because even with a bishop on  b7  Black cannot recapture on  d5  with a piece in view of  e4 - e5 , which would win a piece. }
9. Bb7( { Striking with }9...c5 { leads to an interesting position after }10.Rc1 Bb7 11.cxd5 exd5 { (now the pawn on  d5  limits the activity of the bishop on  b7 , note that Black cannot recapture on  d5  with a bishop in view of  e4 - e5 , winning a piece) }12.Bb5 { (a common motif, limiting the knight on  b8 ) }12...c4 { (an attempt to avoid hanging pawns after  dxc5 ) }13.Ba4 Nc6 14.O-O { when White's plan is to play  Re1  and push  e4 . } )
10. cxd5{ We see the point explained in the note to White's 9th move. Black is forced to recapture with a pawn. }
10. exd5( { To illustrate, }10...Bxd5?? 11.e4 Bb7 12.e5 { wins a piece. } )
11. Bb5{ Another common motif - the bishop restricts the movement of the knight on  b8  and if Black wants to get rid of it then ... a6  or ... c6  has to be played, both of which soften Black's queenside structure. }
11. c6( { If }11...c5 12.O-O { Black still needs to solve the problem with the knight on  b8 . Note that in view of the pin on the  h4 - d8  diagonal it's not possible to play }11...Nbd7? { as }12.Bxd7 Qxd7 13.Bxf6 { wrecks Black's kingside structure. } )
12. Ba4{ The bishop remains on the  a4 - e8  diagonal, useful if Black plays ... c5 , when it will continue to dominate the knight on  b8 . }
12. Nbd7
13. Rc1{ Activating the rook with tempo by attacking the pawn on  c6 . }
13. Rc8
14. O-O{ Completing the development. The middlegame is quite complex. White has the more active pieces (the bishop on  b7  is especially passive) and the more flexible structure (Black has a weakness on  c6 ). In this set-up of a bishop on  b7  shut out by its own pawn on  c6 , the general plan is to execute the  e4 -push, opening the game and emphasising the passive bishop. This can be done with  Re1  and  e4 , for example. If Black is careful though, this plan should be prevented, when the game will enter a manoeuvring phase. A sample line with some ideas is }
14. Re8
15. Bc2{ Intending  Bf5 , harassing the knight from the other side. Another interesting positional idea for White in these positions is  Nb1 - c3 , but for this Black's possible pawn breaks need to be taken into careful consideration. }
15. g6{ Stopping  Bf5 . }
16. b4( { Increasing control of the  c5 -square, so in case Black pushes  ...c5  then after the exchanges on  c5  there will be an IQP left on  d5 . Another idea for White is }16.Re1 { (planning  e4 ) }16...c5 17.dxc5 bxc5 18.Ba4 { , }{ returning to the annoying spot on  a4 , with play against the hanging pawns. } )( { The immediate }16.e4 { leads to complications after }16...dxe4 17.Nxe4 Bf4 { . } )
16. a5
17. bxa5( { The immediate }17.e4 { is another option. } )
17. bxa5
18. e4{ Executing the main idea. }
18. dxe4
19. Nxe4
19. Bxa3
20. Ne5( { The automatic }20.Ra1 { is also fine, but this leads to massive complications. The position is objectively equal, but White is the attacking side and Black must be very careful in defence. One of the attacking ideas is to sacrifice  Bxg6  and after  fxg6 ,  Qb3  is a check that picks up the bishop on  b7 . } )
