18. Nxe5{ The exchanges eased Black's position a bit, but White still has the initiative. The pawn on  b5  is hanging and there is also the threat of  Nc6 . Ideally White would like to play  f3  (to secure the  e4 -pawn and render the bishop on  b7  passive) and  Be3 , concentrating all the forces on the queenside. Black shouldn't allow this. In some lines White may exchange the pawn on  e4  for the pawn on  b5 , obtaining a mobile queenside majority. Objectively Black should be able to defend, but it's an unpleasant task. }
