2. c4
2. e6( { The QGD is a very solid development that also offers Black various options to develop the pieces. For example, in the main lines after }3.Nc3 Be7 { (or }3...Nf6 { )   }4.Nf3 Nf6 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bh4 O-O 7.e3 { the Lasker Variation with }7...Ne4 { , the Tartakower Variation with }7...b6 { or the Kramnik's preference with }7...Nbd7 { all give Black good play. } )( { Black also has three good options after   }5.Bf4 O-O 6.e3 { : the traditional main line }6...c5 { and the two modern treatments with }6...Nbd7 { or }6...b6 { .  Apart from the theory and the number of options, what makes it difficult for White to navigate these lines are all the possible transformations of the pawn structure that can happen (to name but a few: White can take on  d5  or allow Black to take on  c4 , the same applies with the pawns on  d4  and  c5 , there are many lines where Black plays with an IQP or hanging pawns, but sometimes White plays with an IQP etc.). To limit the scope of these transformations White's most practical choice is to take on  d5  immediately, fixing the structure where the plan of White's development is more or less universal. Hence: } )
3. cxd5( { This early exchange as a way of entering the Exchange Variation has the point of eliminating 3 important options that Black has in case of the more usual }3.Nc3 { .  These are the Semi-Tarrasch, arising after }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 Nxd5 { , an extremely popular choice since Kramnik re-introduced it in modern practice at the London Candidates in 2013; the Schara-Hennig Gambit, arising after   }3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 { , where the latest analyses suggest that Black has great play for the sacrificed pawn; the line   }3.Nc3 dxc4 { , where White needs to play }4.e4 { and enter different lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA) than the ones we analyse in this repertoire } )
3. exd5
4. Nc3{ White has entered the Exchange Variation and here Black has a lot of options. The common theme for White against all of these options is the development of the bishop on  f4 , resembling the chapter ... e6  Systems where White plays  3.Bf4 . }
