1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6{ The Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) is one of the most solid openings in existence. Black supports the pawn centre in classical fashion, not giving up space. There are many variations and development set-ups that Black can employ in the QGD, so White's task with the next move is to limit them to the maximum and at the same time achieve, as much as possible, universality of his own development. }
3. cxd5( { By taking on  d5  before  Nc3  White eliminates three important variations: the Semi-Tarrasch, arising after }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 Nxd5 { , the Schara-Hennig Gambit, arising after   }3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 { , and the line   }3.Nc3 dxc4 { , where White needs to play }4.e4 { and enter different lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA) than the ones we analyse in this repertoire. } )
3. exd5
4. Nc3( { With the above options eliminated, White enters the Carlsbad structure. It's worth noting that the move }4.Bf4 { is also possible, which would most likely lead to a transposition to the analysed lines, except for the line }4...c5 { , when White should play }5.e3 Nc6 6.Bb5 { . }{ Before giving an outline of Black's options, I'd like to introduce you to the possible plans White has in this structure. These plans are:  1. The minority attack ( b4 - b5  followed by  bxc6  and then play against the backward pawn on  c6 );  2. The building of a pawn centre by  f3  and  e4  (the so-called Botvinnik plan, because he was the first one to employ it, see the origin game in the model section  Botvinnik-Keres ) or playing  f3  and  g4 ,  h4 , expanding on the kingside;  3. Play in the centre by pushing  e4  (without the support of  f3 );  4. Castling long with an attack on the kingside;  5. Planting a Pillsbury knight on  e5  (supported by  f4 ) as a focal point for a kingside attack, played with a short castle;  6. The AlphaZero plan of a short castle, allowing ... Bg4xf3 ,  gxf3  and then using the g-file for an attack on the kingside (see the model game  AlphaZero-Stockfish ). } )( { Now, after knowing White's possible plans, let's see Black's choices here: the pawn moves }4...a6 { , }4...c6 { , }4...c5 { and }4...h6 { are all possible, as are the developing moves }4...Bb4 { , }4...Be7 { and }4...Nf6 { . In spite of this variety, White's play in the next moves is very simple and consists of the following ideas: the dark-squared bishop is developed on  f4 , followed by  e3  and  Bd3  (if possible) in order to prevent Black's developing ... Bf5 . If White succeeds in this then he has the plans outlined above at his disposal. In case Black manages to play ... Bf5  before White plays  Bd3 , White will try to harass that bishop by one (or more) of the following:  Nge2 - g3 ,  Nf3 - h4 ,  h3  and  g4  or  f3  and then either  g4  or  e4 . Then White will reconsider which of the 6 plans is applicable to the situation at hand. } )
4. a6{ A move that is usually played after  3.Nc3 , so a player who has this line on their repertoire would easily make the same move here. }
5. Bf4{ White's play is straightforward in all the lines of the Exhange Variation - the bishop is developed on  f4  in all lines. Now Black needs to decide where to develop the king's knight - to  f6  or to  e7 . }
5. c6( { The more flexible choice. In case of }5...Nf6 6.e3 Bd6 7.Bxd6 { (the alternative }7.Bg5!? { is very interesting, keeping more pieces on the board and intending  Bd3  and  f4 ) }{   }7...Qxd6 8.Bd3 { is an important move that prevents the development of Black's light-squared bishop to  f5 . If White achieves this then he usually has a slight plus as the bishop on  c8  remains passive. White then continues with  h3 ,  Nf3  and  O-O  and prepares a minority attack with  Rb1 ,  b4 ,  a4 ,  b5  etc. In case Black starts play in the centre with }8...O-O 9.h3 b6 10.Nf3 c5 11.O-O Bb7 12.b3 { keeps Black at bay when eventually White will most likely take on  c5  and play against the hanging pawns. } )
6. e3{ White's development is natural and one of the main objectives is to develop the bishop on  d3  in order to prevent the black bishop to come to  f5 . }
6. Bd6{ Black's plan is to play ... Ne7  and offer an exchange of the light-squared bishops with ... Bf5  once White's light-squared bishop comes to  d3 . }( { The premature }6...Bf5 { only invites }7.g4! Be6 8.h4 { when White has expanded on the kingside and will develop with  Bd3 ,  Qf3 ,  Nge2  and  O-O-O . } )
7. Bxd6{ By exchanging White gains a tempo to continue with the development. }
7. Qxd6
8. Bd3{ This is a common feature in all the QGD lines - the bishop comes to  d3  from where it controls the  f5 -square. }
8. Ne7( { Black also continues with the plan of  ...Bf5 . Developing the knight on  f6  makes less sense as it gives White easy play and a choice after }8...Nf6 { when White can play }9.h3 { followed by  Nf3 ,  O-O  and then preparing a minority attack with  Rb1 ,  b4 ,  a4  and eventually  b5 , or White can try an alternative plan of play in the centre with }9.Nge2 { intending  O-O ,  Qd2 ,  f3  and eventually  e4 . } )
9. Qc2{ White fights for control of the  f5 -square. }
9. Bg4( { Black wants to play  ...Bh5 - g6  to exchange the bishops without weakening the kingside with  ...g6 . In that case White obtains initiative by opening the centre, a sample line is }9...g6 10.Nge2 ( { In case of }10.f3 c5! { Black obtains counterplay since thanks to the pawn being on  a6  White doesn't have the  Nb5  jump. } )10...Bf5 11.Bxf5 Nxf5 12.O-O-O Nd7 13.e4! { and Black's uncoordinated pieces and the king still in the centre make the position dangerous for the second player. } )
10. h3{ White's plan is to advance on the kingside, so this pawn move is the first step in that direction. }
10. Bh5{ Black naturally follows the plan. }
11. f4{ With this move White stops Black's idea to exchange the bishops because the threat is  f5 . Now the bishop on  h5  is in danger of being trapped with  g4  and  f5 , so Black's next move is understandable. }
11. f6{ Opening an escape square on  f7 . }
12. Nge2{ White wants to play  f5  and  Nf4 , when the knight will be excellently placed on  f4 , eyeing the  e6 -square. }
12. Nd7( { Black finishes development. Play in the centre with }12...c5 { leads to a more pleasant position for White after }13.dxc5 Qxc5 14.Nd4 Nbc6 15.Nce2 { when White has clear-cut play against the IQP. } )
13. O-O{ White does the same and now plans  f5  and  Nf4 . }
13. Bxe2{ Not ideal for Black, since the idea was to exchange the bishop for White's bishop, but since that was no longer possible it makes sense to get rid of the bishop that didn't have too many prospects. }
14. Nxe2{ White replaces the knight and renews the idea of  f5  and  Nf4 . }
14. g6{ Black tries to prevent White's plan. The idea is that after }
15. f5
15. g5{ Black controls the  f4 -square and doesn't allow  Nf4 . However, this advance weakened Black's kingside. }
16. Nc3{ The knight returns to  c3  to support the advance in the centre with  e4 . Before pushing the e-pawn White will play  Qf2  to defend the pawn on  d4 . The queen's rook can come to  d1  or  e1 . Black's problem is the position of the king - on the queenside it will be attacked by a pawn storm, while on the kingside the weakened pawn shelter can become an important factor when White opens the position in the centre. }
