2. e6{ The Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) is one of the most solid openings in existence. Black supports the pawn centre in classical fashion, not giving up space. There are many variations and development set-ups that Black can employ in the QGD, so White's task with the next move is to limit them to the maximum and at the same time achieve, as much as possible, universality of his own development. }
3. cxd5( { By taking on  d5  before  Nc3  White eliminates three important variations: the Semi-Tarrasch, arising after }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 Nxd5 { , the Schara-Hennig Gambit, arising after   }3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 { , and the line   }3.Nc3 dxc4 { , where White needs to play }4.e4 { and enter different lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA) than the ones we analyse in this repertoire. } )
3. exd5
4. Nc3( { With the above options eliminated, White enters the Carlsbad structure. It's worth noting that the move }4.Bf4 { is also possible, which would most likely lead to a transposition to the analysed lines, except for the line }4...c5 { , when White should play }5.e3 Nc6 6.Bb5 { . }{ Before giving an outline of Black's options, I'd like to introduce you to the possible plans White has in this structure. These plans are:  1. The minority attack ( b4 - b5  followed by  bxc6  and then play against the backward pawn on  c6 );  2. The building of a pawn centre by  f3  and  e4  (the so-called Botvinnik plan, because he was the first one to employ it, see the origin game in the model section  Botvinnik-Keres ) or playing  f3  and  g4 ,  h4 , expanding on the kingside;  3. Play in the centre by pushing  e4  (without the support of  f3 );  4. Castling long with an attack on the kingside;  5. Planting a Pillsbury knight on  e5  (supported by  f4 ) as a focal point for a kingside attack, played with a short castle;  6. The AlphaZero plan of a short castle, allowing ... Bg4xf3 ,  gxf3  and then using the g-file for an attack on the kingside (see the model game  AlphaZero-Stockfish ). } )( { Now, after knowing White's possible plans, let's see Black's choices here: the pawn moves }4...a6 { , }4...c6 { , }4...c5 { and }4...h6 { are all possible, as are the developing moves }4...Bb4 { , }4...Be7 { and }4...Nf6 { . In spite of this variety, White's play in the next moves is very simple and consists of the following ideas: the dark-squared bishop is developed on  f4 , followed by  e3  and  Bd3  (if possible) in order to prevent Black's developing ... Bf5 . If White succeeds in this then he has the plans outlined above at his disposal. In case Black manages to play ... Bf5  before White plays  Bd3 , White will try to harass that bishop by one (or more) of the following:  Nge2 - g3 ,  Nf3 - h4 ,  h3  and  g4  or  f3  and then either  g4  or  e4 . Then White will reconsider which of the 6 plans is applicable to the situation at hand. } )
4. h6( { This line is a mirror-image of the previous one and it usually arises after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 h6 4.cxd5 exd5 { . White's play is again straightforward: the bishop goes to  f4 , followed by  e3  and  Bd3 . } )
5. Bf4{ White develops the bishop before playing  e3 . }
5. c6( { After }5...Nf6 6.e3 Bd6 7.Bxd6 Qxd6 8.Bd3 { White managed to achieve the objective of preventing ... Bf5 . } )
6. e3
6. Bf5( { Here Black manages to develop the bishop on  f5 . In case of }6...Bd6 7.Bxd6 Qxd6 8.Bd3 Ne7 9.Qc2 { White still manages to stop ... Bf5  because }9...g6 { can be met by }10.f3! { intending to continue with  e4 . After }10...O-O ( { Black cannot play }10...c5? { as in the analogous line after  3...a6  because without a pawn on  a6  White wins a pawn after }11.Nb5  )11.Nge2 a6 12.Qd2 c5 13.O-O-O { (or }13.O-O { ) with play against the IQP after the exchange on  d4  or  c5 . } )
7. f3( { In line with the rule of thumb outlined at the beginning, when Black's bishop lands on  f5  it needs to be attacked. In this case White plans  e4  or  g4 . However, even the seemingly innocuous exchange of the bishops with }7.Bd3 { , which appears to be what Black wants, isn't toothless, as seen in the model game  Giri-Nihal . } )
7. Nf6( { Black prevents  e4 . White keeps the initiative after other moves as well. For example, }7...Bh7 8.Bd3 { (forcing Black to move the bishop again, when White develops the queen) }8...Bxd3 9.Qxd3 Bd6 10.Nge2 { followed by  O-O  and  e4  when the mobile pawn centre gives White excellent play. } )( { Another option is }7...Bd6 8.Bxd6 Qxd6 9.e4 Bh7 10.e5 Qb4 11.Qd2 { with the idea to continue with  f4  and  Nf3 . } )
8. g4{ Since  e4  isn't possible, White advances with the g-pawn. }
8. Bh7
9. h4{ By expanding on the kingside White makes it nearly impossible for Black to castle there in view of the impending attack. }
9. Bd6{ Lacking space, Black should seek exchanges. }
10. Nge2{ Now in case of exchange on  f4  the knight will occupy that square. The knight also has the alternative to go to  g3 . }
10. Qe7{ Black threatens to take on  f4  and then win the pawn on  e3 . }
11. Kf2{ Defending the pawn. The king is quite comfortable on  f2  in these structures - it doesn't impede the connection of the rooks on the first rank and the g and h-pawns can continue marching forward because the king is well protected by the pawns on  e3  and  f3 . }
11. Na6( { Black develops and keeps the  d7 -square available for the other knight. In case of }11...Nbd7?! 12.g5! { the knight on  f6  is short of good squares, for example }12...Nh5 13.Bxd6 Qxd6 14.Bh3 { threatening  Bg4  is advantageous for White, as is }{   }12...Ng8 13.Bh3 { - again the knight is a bad piece. } )
12. Ng3{ White now wants to exchange the light-squared bishops and obtain access to the  f5 -square for the knight. }
12. Nc7{ Black brings back the knight. }
13. Bd3( { White continues with the plan. It is also possible to play }13.Bxd6 Qxd6 14.Bd3 Bxd3 15.Qxd3 { with  Nf5  and  h5  to follow. } )
13. Bxd3
14. Qxd3
14. Bxf4
15. exf4{ The immediate threat is  Re1 , winning material. }
15. O-O-O
16. Nce2{ The knight didn't have much to do on  c3  so it is re-routed to  e2 , from where it has much brighter prospects: it can go to  f4  (after  f5 ) or to  g3  (after  Nf5 ) or via  c1  and  d3  to  e5 . On  e2  the knight also dissuades Black's ... c5  because after the exchange of pawns on  d4  and  c5  the knight would obtain the wonderful blockading square on  d4 .  A few words about the pawn structure on the kingside. Generally speaking it's a favourable structure for White because the pawns take away a lot of squares from Black's pieces and the doubled f-pawns mean that the first f-pawn can move forward without weakening the squares behind (most notably the  e4 -square). White has several ideas with this structure, as mentioned above  f5  and  Nf4  is one idea, another is to push  h5  and play  Nf5  to attack the pawn on  g7 .  In an endgame the  g5 -breakthrough is a potent one, taking up even more space on the kingside. Black lacks counterplay because there are no good squares for the knights, something that White cannot complain about. }
