3. cxd5( { By taking on  d5  before  Nc3  White eliminates three important variations: the Semi-Tarrasch, arising after }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 Nxd5 { , the Schara-Hennig Gambit, arising after   }3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 { , and the line   }3.Nc3 dxc4 { , where White needs to play }4.e4 { and enter different lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA) than the ones we analyse in this repertoire. } )
3. exd5
4. Nc3( { With the above options eliminated, White enters the Carlsbad structure. It's worth noting that the move }4.Bf4 { is also possible, which would most likely lead to a transposition to the analysed lines, except for the line }4...c5 { , when White should play }5.e3 Nc6 6.Bb5 { . }{ Before giving an outline of Black's options, I'd like to introduce you to the possible plans White has in this structure. These plans are:  1. The minority attack ( b4 - b5  followed by  bxc6  and then play against the backward pawn on  c6 );  2. The building of a pawn centre by  f3  and  e4  (the so-called Botvinnik plan, because he was the first one to employ it, see the origin game in the model section  Botvinnik-Keres ) or playing  f3  and  g4 ,  h4 , expanding on the kingside;  3. Play in the centre by pushing  e4  (without the support of  f3 );  4. Castling long with an attack on the kingside;  5. Planting a Pillsbury knight on  e5  (supported by  f4 ) as a focal point for a kingside attack, played with a short castle;  6. The AlphaZero plan of a short castle, allowing ... Bg4xf3 ,  gxf3  and then using the g-file for an attack on the kingside (see the model game  AlphaZero-Stockfish ). } )( { Now, after knowing White's possible plans, let's see Black's choices here: the pawn moves }4...a6 { , }4...c6 { , }4...c5 { and }4...h6 { are all possible, as are the developing moves }4...Bb4 { , }4...Be7 { and }4...Nf6 { . In spite of this variety, White's play in the next moves is very simple and consists of the following ideas: the dark-squared bishop is developed on  f4 , followed by  e3  and  Bd3  (if possible) in order to prevent Black's developing ... Bf5 . If White succeeds in this then he has the plans outlined above at his disposal. In case Black manages to play ... Bf5  before White plays  Bd3 , White will try to harass that bishop by one (or more) of the following:  Nge2 - g3 ,  Nf3 - h4 ,  h3  and  g4  or  f3  and then either  g4  or  e4 . Then White will reconsider which of the 6 plans is applicable to the situation at hand. } )
4. Bb4( { Black pins the knight on  c3  like in the Nimzo-Indian. Usually this is played after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Bb4 { and now }4.cxd5 exd5 { . } )
5. Bf4{ Again White follows the same recipe - the bishop comes out to  f4 . }
5. Nf6( { Black can also try }5...c6 6.e3 Bf5 { , but that only provokes }7.g4 Bg6 8.Qb3 Qb6 9.f3 { with  Nge2 - g3 ,  h4 ,  Kf2  to come, with pleasant expansion on the kingside. } )( { In case of }5...c5 6.dxc5 Nf6 7.e3 { we have a transposition to the line after   }5...Nf6 6.e3 c5 7.dxc5 { , though White can also try to avoid it by playing }{   }5...c5 6.e3 ( { Or }6.a3 Bxc3 7.bxc3 c4 8.f3 { with  g4 ,  Bg2 ,  e3 ,  Ne2  and  O-O  to come. } )6...c4 7.Nge2 Nc6 8.a3 Ba5 9.b4 cxb3 10.Qxb3 Be6 11.f3 { when White will finish development of the kingside with  Kf2 ,  g4 ,  Bg2 . } )
6. e3{ With the bishop on  b4 , White will likely want to develop the other knight on  e2 , in order to lend support to the one on  c3 . }
6. c5( { This active move is in line with Black's chosen opening line. Black can execute  ...c5  after castling as well, but this allows White time to complete development after }6...O-O 7.Bd3 c5 8.Nge2 { when play will diverge depending on whether Black allows an IQP with an exchange on  d4  or will advance with }8...c4 { when White's plan is to execute the advance  e4 . This can happen after }9.Bc2 Nc6 10.Bg5 { (the pin is quite unpleasant, Black needs to retreat the bishop from  b4  to break it) }10...h6 11.Bh4 Be7 12.O-O { when White will aim for  f3  and  e4 . } )( { A third option for Black is to develop the bishop to  f5  with }6...Bf5 { but that weakens the queenside (the  b7 -pawn in particular) and White can play }7.Qb3 { forcing }7...Nc6 { . Now after }8.Nge2 { followed by  Ng3 ,  Be2  and  O-O  White will have a harmonious position. } )
7. dxc5( { With this move-order White has the additional option of }7.Bb5 Bd7 8.Bxd7 Qxd7 9.Nge2 { with a comfortable position. However, as Black can play ... c5  on move 5, when White doesn't have the option to give a check on  b5  (though he has other ways to avoid the transposition that are mentioned in the comment to Black's 5th move), we look at the capture on  c5  as the main move. White now wants to play against the IQP, but Black's quick development will allow for the central breakthrough with ... d4 . } )
7. O-O
8. Bd3{ Intending  Nge2 , which will control the  d4 -square and strengthen the knight on  c3 . }
8. Bxc5{ Black's plan now is to play ... Nc6  and push ... d4 . }
9. Nge2{ White continues with development. }
9. Nc6{ Thanks to the control of the  d4 -square Black ensures that ... d4  cannot be stopped. }
10. O-O{ In anticipation of the opening of the centre White moves the king to a safe location. }
10. d4{ Black must act now, otherwise White would prevent this push with a move like  Nb5  or  Rc1  (eyeing the bishop on  c5 ). }
11. exd4{ The centre opens up now, but in view of the lead in development White maintains some initiative. }
11. Nxd4
12. Na4{ Forcing Black's reply in view of the threat to exchange the bishop on  c5 , then take on  d4  and when Black recaptures with the queen, win the queen thanks to the  Bxh7  discovered attack. }
12. Nxe2+
13. Bxe2{ The bishop is en route to  f3 . White's bishops will exert pressure on Black's queenside, making it difficult for Black to finish development. }
13. Be7{ This is the best square for the bishop, where it cannot be attacked. }
14. Bf3{ White's initiative is thanks to the powerful bishops, which target Black's queenside. Black cannot easily develop the bishop on  c8  and precise play is still required if Black is to eventually equalise. If allowed a free hand, White will place the rooks on the open central files and possibly play  Qb3  to increase the pressure on Black's queenside. }
