7. c4( { This is Black's best. In case of }7...Be7 8.dxc5 { wins a tempo as it forces Black to move the bishop again. After }8...Bxc5 9.Bb5 O-O 10.O-O Be6 11.Rc1 { White obtains a typical position against the IQP that guarantees a slight plus. } )
8. a3{ An important move that prevents ... Bb4 . In case White allows  Bb4  Black would have firmer control of the  e4 -square thanks to the pin on the knight on  c3  and the possibility to exchange it for the dark-squared bishop. }
8. Be7{ This is a neutral developing move that allows a surprising retort. }
9. Bxc4{ A shocking move! The piece sacrifice is very dangerous. }
9. dxc4
10. d5{ The pawn wants to go forward! }
10. Nxd5( { This is the safest option for Black, heading for an endgame. In case of }10...Na5 11.d6 { White has strong initiative, the main threat being  Nb5 . After }11...Nb3 12.dxe7 Kxe7 13.O-O Nxa1 14.Qxa1 { White has excellent compensation because the black king cannot easily get away from the centre and White threatens  Rd1  and  Bd6  or  e4 - e5  in combination with  Bg5 . } )
11. Qxd5{ In the endgame White's advantage is the strong centralised position of the knight on  d5 . }
11. Qxd5
12. Nxd5{ The knight is a monster. The threat is  Nc7 . }
12. Bd8
13. O-O-O{ White controls the d-file and plans to support the knight with  e4 . }
13. Be6
14. e4{ Supporting the knight and advancing in the centre. }
14. O-O
15. Nd4{ By exchanging the knight on  c6  White eliminates a piece that controls the central squares  d4  and  e5 . }
15. Nxd4
16. Rxd4{ The pawn on  c4  is hanging now. }
16. Rc8
17. Re1{ While objectively equal, the endgame is very pleasant for White. The main idea is to advance with the pawn majority in the centre, but White can also play on the queenside to blockade Black's majority with  Bd2 - b4 . Black is rather passive and without active ideas, which makes it more difficult for him to play. }
