10. Be6( { Moving away and strengthening the defence of the central pawn. In case of }10...O-O?! 11.g4 Be6 12.Bg2 h6 13.Bg3 { White has excellent chances on the kingside after  O-O ,  f4  and then either  f5  or  g5 . } )
11. g4{ White continues with the same idea as described in the previous comment. }
11. h5{ An attempt at counterplay on the kingside. }
12. g5{ The pawn was under attack so it had to move away from the attacked square. }
12. Nd7{ Now the pawn is attacked again. }
13. h4( { The simple solution, safely defending the pawn. White can also enter complications with }13.Nxc4!? dxc4 14.d5 Bxg5 15.dxe6 fxe6 16.Qd6 { , }{ which leads to messy positions that are dynamically balanced. } )
13. Nb6{ Black improves the position of the knight. }
14. Bg2( { White completes the development by targeting the pawn on  d5 . It's also possible to undermine the centre with }14.b3!? cxb3 15.Nxb3 Nc4 16.Bxc4 dxc4 17.Nd2 { with  Nde4  to come next, leading to an unclear position - White's central presence, both pieces and pawns, is huge, but there is a certain care that needs to be taken about the position of the king. } )
14. Bd6{ Black's dark-squared bishop is not particularly active, unlike White's, so Black doesn't mind this exchange. }
15. Bxd6( { White can also try }15.Qf3 Bg4 16.Qg3 Bxf4 17.Qxf4 { , }{ when after the exchange of the bishops the queen takes over the control of the dark squares. } )
15. Qxd6
16. b3{ Undermining Black's advanced  c4 -pawn. }
16. Bg4( { A bit more precise than the immediate capture on  b3 , }16...cxb3 17.Nxb3 { opens up the queenside and the threat of  Nc5  is somewhat annoying to meet. } )
17. Qb1( { It's also possible to offer the exchange of bishops with }17.Bf3 { , }{ but the bishop is very good at targeting the pawn on  d5  while Black's bishop is less effective. } )
17. cxb3
18. Qxb3{ By taking with the queen White exerts maximum pressure on the pawn on  d5 . }
18. Rd8{ Black defends the pawn. }
