1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6{ The Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) is one of the most solid openings in existence. Black supports the pawn centre in classical fashion, not giving up space. There are many variations and development set-ups that Black can employ in the QGD, so White's task with the next move is to limit them to the maximum and at the same time achieve, as much as possible, universality of his own development. }
3. cxd5( { By taking on  d5  before  Nc3  White eliminates three important variations: the Semi-Tarrasch, arising after }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 Nxd5 { , the Schara-Hennig Gambit, arising after   }3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 { , and the line   }3.Nc3 dxc4 { , where White needs to play }4.e4 { and enter different lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA) than the ones we analyse in this repertoire. } )
3. exd5
4. Nc3( { With the above options eliminated, White enters the Carlsbad structure. It's worth noting that the move }4.Bf4 { is also possible, which would most likely lead to a transposition to the analysed lines, except for the line }4...c5 { , when White should play }5.e3 Nc6 6.Bb5 { . }{ Before giving an outline of Black's options, I'd like to introduce you to the possible plans White has in this structure. These plans are:  1. The minority attack ( b4 - b5  followed by  bxc6  and then play against the backward pawn on  c6 );  2. The building of a pawn centre by  f3  and  e4  (the so-called Botvinnik plan, because he was the first one to employ it, see the origin game in the model section  Botvinnik-Keres ) or playing  f3  and  g4 ,  h4 , expanding on the kingside;  3. Play in the centre by pushing  e4  (without the support of  f3 );  4. Castling long with an attack on the kingside;  5. Planting a Pillsbury knight on  e5  (supported by  f4 ) as a focal point for a kingside attack, played with a short castle;  6. The AlphaZero plan of a short castle, allowing ... Bg4xf3 ,  gxf3  and then using the g-file for an attack on the kingside (see the model game  AlphaZero-Stockfish ). } )( { Now, after knowing White's possible plans, let's see Black's choices here: the pawn moves }4...a6 { , }4...c6 { , }4...c5 { and }4...h6 { are all possible, as are the developing moves }4...Bb4 { , }4...Be7 { and }4...Nf6 { . In spite of this variety, White's play in the next moves is very simple and consists of the following ideas: the dark-squared bishop is developed on  f4 , followed by  e3  and  Bd3  (if possible) in order to prevent Black's developing ... Bf5 . If White succeeds in this then he has the plans outlined above at his disposal. In case Black manages to play ... Bf5  before White plays  Bd3 , White will try to harass that bishop by one (or more) of the following:  Nge2 - g3 ,  Nf3 - h4 ,  h3  and  g4  or  f3  and then either  g4  or  e4 . Then White will reconsider which of the 6 plans is applicable to the situation at hand. } )
4. c6( { A natural move for Black, connecting the structure on the queenside. This position can also arise when Black employs the Triangle set-up after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 c6 { and now }4.cxd5 exd5 { . } )
5. Bf4{ White continues with the usual development, placing the bishop on  f4 . }
5. Bf5{ It is natural to place the bishop on the most active square, but it invites }
6. f3{ As one plan for White in the Carlsbad structure is to advance on the kingside with  g4 ,  h4  etc. }
6. Nf6
7. g4{ White expands with tempo. }
7. Be6
8. e3{ The so-called bathtub structure (pawns on  d4 ,  e3 ,  f3  and  g4 ) is a very flexible pawn structure that covers a lot of squares. It also allows White to develop comfortably behind it with  Bd3 ,  Nge2  and  Kf2 . }
8. c5( { This is the usual way Black combats White's expansion on the kingside. If Black stays passive there is a risk of being suffocated on the kingside. Black can postpone the  ...c5  break, but not for too long, for example }8...Bd6 9.Nge2 O-O 10.Qd2 c5 { (Black is running short of useful moves anyway) }11.Bxd6 Qxd6 12.dxc5 Qxc5 13.Nd4 { with  O-O-O  next and White has a comfortable position with play against the IQP combined with an attack on the kingside. } )
9. Bd3{ The bishop comes to the best square before developing the knight on  e2 . }
9. Nc6
10. Nge2{ White's development is harmonious. The advanced kingside pawns provide space and limit the activity of Black's pieces. }
10. cxd4( { Sooner rather than later Black will take on  d4 . For example: }10...Be7 11.O-O Rc8 12.Qd2 O-O 13.Rad1 { and if Black doesn't take on  d4  White will take on  c5  and after  Bb1  the pressure on the IQP will be unpleasant. } )
11. exd4( { It is also possible to take with the knight and to see how to play these structures after }11.Nxd4 Nxd4 12.exd4 { I invite you to take a look at the model game  Botvinnik-Petrosian , an exemplary way to take full advantage of White's advantage in this structure. } )
11. Be7
12. O-O{ Now both sides castle, completing development. }
12. O-O
13. Bg3{ The bishop frees the  f4 -square for the knight. This would require some preparation, since the knight cannot immediately jump to  f4  because the pawn on  d4  is hanging, but once on  f4  it would target the bishop on  e6  and the pawn on  d5 . Notice how White's pawns on  f3  and  g4  effectively limit the activity of the black knight on  f6  and the bishop on  e6 . }
13. Rc8
14. Qd2{ White's plan is to put the rook on  d1 , drop the bishop back to  b1  (from where it can also be used to put pressure on the pawn on  d5  by playing  a3  and  Ba2 ) and play  Nf4 , threatening to take on  e6  and obtain the bishop pair. }
