5. Bd6( { In case of }5...Nf6 6.e3 { we have a transposition to the lines after   }4...Nf6 5.Bf4 c6 { . }{ Black's move is a natural one, aiming to exchange White's active bishop on  f4 . } )
6. Bxd6{ The usual reaction is to exchange the bishops. }
6. Qxd6
7. e3{ White plans  Bd3 , to control the  b1 - h7  diagonal and the  f5 -square in particular. If allowed, Black's light-squared bishop will lack good squares and will become a passive piece. }
7. Bf5( { It's only natural for Black to put the bishop on the most active square. Black can also start with }7...Ne7 { , }{ waiting for White to put a bishop on  d3  and then play ... Bf5 , but White can start with }8.Qb3!? { to try to tie down the bishop to the defence of the pawn on  b7 . Now after }8...O-O 9.Bd3 { Black cannot play ... Bf5  because the pawn on  b7  is hanging. Still, after }9...Nd7 10.Nf3 Nf6 11.Qc2 g6 { Black manages to get ... Bf5  in. However, }12.h3 Bf5 13.Bxf5 Nxf5 14.g4! Ne7 15.O-O-O { with the idea of  g5 ,  h4 - h5 , gives White attacking chances on the kingside. } )( { Note that the move }7...Nf6 { transposes to the lines after   }4...Nf6 5.Bf4 c6 6.e3 Bd6 7.Bxd6 Qxd6 8.Bd3  )
8. g4( { As a rule of thumb, whenever the black bishop makes it to  f5 , White should look for ways to harass it. One way is to play  g4 , like here, others are }8.Nge2 { with the idea of  Ng3  or }8.Nf3 { with the idea of  Nh4 . } )
8. Be6( { In case of }8...Bg6 9.Nge2 Nd7 10.Nf4 { White will be able to obtain the pair of bishops by taking on  g6  whenever it is appropriate. } )
9. h4{ White takes more space on the kingside and plans  Nh3 - f4 . }
9. Nd7
10. Nh3{ The knight is coming to  f4 , where it will be quite active and influential. }
10. O-O-O{ With the  g4  and  h4  pawns looming, castling queenside is Black's natural choice. }
11. Nf4{ The knight is nicely centralised now. An additional option for the knight is to come to  d3 , from where it controls the important squares  c5  and  e5 . }
11. Ne7( { Black completes development, but it's clear that his pieces are lacking space and look cramped. In case of }11...Ngf6 12.f3 { the bathtub is also quite effective at limiting the mobility of Black's pieces. White will then continue with  Qe2  and  O-O-O . } )
12. Qf3{ White will also castle long. }
12. Nf6
13. Bh3{ White defends the pawn on  g4 . The bishop on  h3  can become very active in case White exchanges the bishop on  e6  and then continues with  g5 , opening the  h3 - c8  diagonal. However, this needs to be done with care because if Black can recapture with ... fxe6  and follow up with ... e5  then Black would have no problems. }
13. Kb8{ Vacating the  c8 -square for the bishop. }
14. O-O-O( { As mentioned, }14.Nxe6?! { is premature in view of }14...fxe6 15.O-O-O e5 { and Black is doing great. } )
14. Bc8
15. Nd3{ White has a pleasant position, his light pieces are much better placed than Black's. The knight on  d3  is a very good piece, controlling both  c5  and  e5 , while thanks to the queen on  f3  White has the threat of  g5 , and when the knight from  f6  moves the pawn on  f7  hangs. }
