of the 6 plans is applicable to the situation at hand. } )
4. Be7( { This is one of the main moves, as this position usually arises after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Be7 4.cxd5 exd5 { . } )
5. Bf4( { Here the development of the bishop is the main line. Now Black has two major options, }5...c6 { and }5...Nf6 { . } )
5. Nf6{ With this move Black usually seeks counterplay in the centre based on the ... c5  break. }
6. e3{ White continues with the usual development. }
6. O-O{ This is an alternative, Black plays for a quick ... c5 . }
7. Bd3{ White develops the bishop, controlling the  b1 - h7  diagonal. }
7. c5{ Black wants to continue with ... Nc6  and play in the centre. }
8. Nge2{ With this development of the knight it is easier for White to deal with a possible pin after ... Bg4 . }
8. Nc6
9. O-O{ Now Black needs to decide what type of structure he would like to play. }
9. c4( { In case of }9...cxd4 10.Nxd4 Nxd4 11.exd4 { White has a stable advantage as all his pieces are better placed than Black's. Further play is easy with  Qb3 ,  Re1  or even  Na4  with  a3  and  b4  to obtain a grip over the  c5 -square. } )( { To illustrate that the pin with }9...Bg4 { is harmless, after }10.dxc5 Bxc5 11.h3 { Black needs to take on  e2  and relinquish the bishop pair because }11...Bh5?! 12.g4 Bg6 13.Bxg6 hxg6 14.g5 Nh5 15.Qxd5 { wins a pawn for White with very little compensation for Black. } )
10. Bc2{ The bishop on  c2  doesn't interfere with the rooks on the first rank, as it would on  b1 . }
10. a6( { Black prepares queenside expansion. In case of }10...Bg4 11.h3 Bh5 12.Bg5! { puts pressure on Black's centre, as White threatens  g4 ,  Nf4  and  Bxf6 , when the pawn on  d5  would fall. } )( { Going after the bishop with }10...Nh5 { is pointless because after }11.h3 Nxf4 12.Nxf4 { White replaced one good piece on  f4  with another - the knight exerts strong pressure on the  d5 -pawn. } )
11. Be5{ A good move, White wants to follow up with  Nf4 , when the pawn on  d5  would be under attack in view of the threat  Bxf6 . }
11. Be6( { Strengthening the defence of the central pawn. Chasing the bishop with }11...Ng4 12.Bg3 { doesn't achieve much as White will continue with  Nf4  and when the knight returns to  f6  White can attack it from the other side by  Bh4 . } )
12. Nf4{ Introducing a nice tactic based on the weakness of the  d5  and  h7 -squares. White wants to take on  f6  and then on  d5 , when the move  Qh5  would be a double attack on  h7  and  d5 , thus winning a pawn. }
12. g6( { Preventing the tactic. Just to illustrate, after }12...Rc8? { White wins after }13.Bxf6 Bxf6 14.Nfxd5! Bxd5 15.Qh5 g6 16.Qxd5 { . } )
13. Qf3{ Piling up the pressure on the  d5 -pawn. The threat is  Bxf6  followed by  Nxd5 . }
13. Nd7{ The knight moves away from the square where it could be captured and attacks the bishop on  e5 . }
14. Ncxd5{ Capturing the central pawn. }
14. Ndxe5
15. dxe5
15. Nxe5
16. Qe4{ Threatening  Qxe5  or  Nxe6 . }
16. Bxd5
17. Nxd5{ The dominating knight on  d5  gives White a small plus. The follow-up is  Rad1  to support the knight and then White can try to set the central pawn majority in motion with  f4 ,  e4  etc. }
