[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) Queen's Gambit Declined"]
[Black "Queen's Gambit Declined #11"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. e6{ The Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) is one of the most solid openings in existence. Black supports the pawn centre in classical fashion, not giving up space. There are many variations and development set-ups that Black can employ in the QGD, so White's task with the next move is to limit them to the maximum and at the same time achieve, as much as possible, universality of his own development. }
3. cxd5( { By taking on  d5  before  Nc3  White eliminates three important variations: the Semi-Tarrasch, arising after }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 Nxd5 { , the Schara-Hennig Gambit, arising after   }3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 { , and the line   }3.Nc3 dxc4 { , where White needs to play }4.e4 { and enter different lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA) than the ones we analyse in this repertoire. } )
3. exd5
4. Nc3( { With the above options eliminated, White enters the Carlsbad structure. It's worth noting that the move }4.Bf4 { is also possible, which would most likely lead to a transposition to the analysed lines, except for the line }4...c5 { , when White should play }5.e3 Nc6 6.Bb5 { . }{ Before giving an outline of Black's options, I'd like to introduce you to the possible plans White has in this structure. These plans are:  1. The minority attack ( b4 - b5  followed by  bxc6  and then play against the backward pawn on  c6 );  2. The building of a pawn centre by  f3  and  e4  (the so-called Botvinnik plan, because he was the first one to employ it, see the origin game in the model section  Botvinnik-Keres ) or playing  f3  and  g4 ,  h4 , expanding on the kingside;  3. Play in the centre by pushing  e4  (without the support of  f3 );  4. Castling long with an attack on the kingside;  5. Planting a Pillsbury knight on  e5  (supported by  f4 ) as a focal point for a kingside attack, played with a short castle;  6. The AlphaZero plan of a short castle, allowing ... Bg4xf3 ,  gxf3  and then using the g-file for an attack on the kingside (see the model game  AlphaZero-Stockfish ). } )( { Now, after knowing White's possible plans, let's see Black's choices here: the pawn moves }4...a6 { , }4...c6 { , }4...c5 { and }4...h6 { are all possible, as are the developing moves }4...Bb4 { , }4...Be7 { and }4...Nf6 { . In spite of this variety, White's play in the next moves is very simple and consists of the following ideas: the dark-squared bishop is developed on  f4 , followed by  e3  and  Bd3  (if possible) in order to prevent Black's developing ... Bf5 . If White succeeds in this then he has the plans outlined above at his disposal. In case Black manages to play ... Bf5  before White plays  Bd3 , White will try to harass that bishop by one (or more) of the following:  Nge2 - g3 ,  Nf3 - h4 ,  h3  and  g4  or  f3  and then either  g4  or  e4 . Then White will reconsider which of the 6 plans is applicable to the situation at hand. } )
4. Be7( { This is one of the main moves, as this position usually arises after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Be7 4.cxd5 exd5 { . } )
5. Bf4( { Here the development of the bishop is the main line. Now Black has two major options, }5...c6 { and }5...Nf6 { . } )
5. Nf6{ With this move Black usually seeks counterplay in the centre based on the ... c5  break. }
6. e3{ White continues with the usual development. }
6. Bf5{ Black develops the bishop on  f5  before White plays  Bd3 . This is the modern treatment of the line. }
7. Nge2{ Remembering the rule of thumb, the bishop on  f5  must be harassed! }
7. O-O
8. Ng3{ The bishop now needs to abandon the  b1 - h7  diagonal. }
8. Be6( { The point is that }8...Bg6?! 9.h4! { is a dangerous idea. After }9...h6 10.h5 Bh7 11.Bd3 Bxd3 12.Qxd3 { even though Black managed to exchange the light-squared bishops, White obtained control of the  f5 -square thanks to the advance of the h-pawn. Now a knight on  f5  will be very difficult to chase away and with that knight White can try to build up a kingside attack with  f3 ,  g4 ,  O-O-O ,  g5  etc. } )
9. Bd3{ White chased away the bishop from  f5  and now occupies the  b1 - h7  diagonal with his own bishop. }
9. c5{ Black must act in the centre, otherwise there is no counterplay. }
10. dxc5{ Creating an IQP. }
10. Bxc5
11. O-O
11. Nc6{ Both sides finished development. Black's main idea is to push ... d4  and get rid of the IQP, so White needs to decide how to deal with that idea. }
12. Rc1{ White develops one more piece. }
12. d4( { Executing the idea. In case of }12...Bd6 13.Nge2 { Black won't be able to push ... d4  in better circumstances, so White will enjoy the small pull the IQP positions allow. } )
13. Nce4{ White's play is based on the activity of the pieces. }
13. Be7
14. Nxf6+( { There are other moves as well, for example }14.Ng5 { or }14.Nf5 { , }{ which can also be explored. By exchanging on  f6  White gets rid of the superfluous knight, as now the other one can occupy the  e4 -square. } )
14. Bxf6
15. Ne4( { With this move White banks on activity and dynamism. A principally different approach is }15.e4 { , when White obtains a central majority and will seek ways to set it in motion. } )
15. dxe3( { After }15...Be7 16.Nc5 Bxc5 17.Rxc5 dxe3 18.fxe3 { we have a position with similar motifs as in the main line. } )
16. Nxf6+{ White obtains the bishop pair. }
16. Qxf6
17. fxe3{ This is the dynamic approach White is seeking. Capturing with a bishop loses the pawn on  b2 , but now with an open f-file, the light-squared bishop looking down the kingside and ideas like  Qh5 ,  Rc5 - g5 ( h5 ), White has good attacking prospects. It's worth noting that the pawn on  b2  cannot really be taken as after }
17. Qxb2
18. Rf2{ The queen is short of good squares, for example }
18. Qb6( { Or }18...Qa3 19.Bd6 { , which wins the exchange for White. } )
19. Rb1{ And White will win the pawn on  b7  as the queen cannot stay on a square from where it defends it. }
