12. Bxf5{ Ideally, White wants to play  Qc2 ,  O-O-O  and then start an attack on the kingside. }
12. Re8( { A flexible move, still not showing where the bishop will be deployed, to  f8  or  b4 . In case of }12...Bb4 13.Qb3 Bxc3 14.bxc3 { White's centre is rock-solid, something that can be used to build an attack on the kingside with  h5 ,  g4 ,  f3 ,  Kf2 ,  Rag1  etc. } )
13. h5{ Grabbing more space on the kingside. If it's not possible to castle queenside White's set-up is to play  g4 ,  f3 ,  Kf2 ,  Rg1  and then  g5  to open the g-file. }
13. Nb6{ The knight goes to  c4 . }
14. Qe2{ The queen goes to  e2  in order to be able to attack the knight on  c4  by  Bd3 , thus chasing away the knight from the square from where it targets the  e3 -pawn and prevents White from playing  f3 . }
14. Bb4( { Black fights for the central  e4 -square. In case of }14...Nc4 15.Bd3 Nd6 16.O-O-O { White managed to castle long and wants to continue with  f3 ,  g4  etc. } )( { The exchange of the dark-squared bishops with }14...Bd6 15.Bxd6 Qxd6 16.O-O-O { is possible, but White's plan remains the same:  g4 - g5  and so on (in this position  f3  should likely be avoided because it would weaken the  e3 -pawn). } )
15. a3{ Forcing the exchange to stabilise the centre. }
15. Bxc3+
16. bxc3
