5. Bf4( { The main move is }5.Bg5 { , }{ but recently the development of the bishop on  f4  got a fair share of attention from the world's best players. } )
5. Bd6{ A natural move, seeking to exchange White's active bishop. }
6. Bxd6{ White exchanges on  d6  and continues with development. }
6. Qxd6
7. e3{ The idea is to play  Bd3 , to control the  f5 -square and render Black's light-squared bishop passive. }
7. Bf5( { The natural move. In case of }7...O-O 8.Bd3 { White's bishop makes it to  d3  before Black's bishop makes it to  f5 . Here I'd like to draw your attention to the original plan devised by AlphaZero. For example, if Black here plays }8...Bg4 { White would normally play }9.Qb3 { and then  h3  to chase away the bishop. However, AlphaZero, in the match against Stockfish in 2018, came up with a completely new concept. In a similar position it played }9.Nf3!? { , }{ voluntarily pinning the knight. Then it played  Qb3 , allowing Black to take on  f3  and after ... Bxf3 ,  gxf3  it started to build up a kingside attack with  Kh1 ,  Rg1 ,  f4 ,  Qd1 - f3 - h3  and doubling of the rooks on the g-file. Keep in mind this plan as it can be applied in many similar situations and it's quite unexpected! You can see how this went in practice in the model game  AlphaZero-Stockfish  (where the dark-squared bishops were exchanged at a later stage). } )
8. Nge2( { As in the line arising after   }4...Be7 5.Bf4 c6 6.e3 Bf5 7.Nge2 { , }{ White's knight goes to  g3  to harass the bishop. } )( { An alternative way to do so is }8.Nf3 { with the idea of  Nh4 . } )
8. O-O
9. Ng3{ The bishop now needs to decide on which diagonal to stay. }
9. Bg6( { This is the more ambitious approach. In case of }9...Be6 10.Bd3 { White achieved the objective to chase away the opponent's bishop and occupy the  b1 - h7  diagonal. } )
10. h4{ Intending  h5 . }
10. h6( { Opening a luft for both the king and the bishop. The sneaky }10...Re8 { sets a trap: here }11.h5? { is met by the powerful }11...Rxe3! { . Therefore White should play }{   }11.Nb5! { when the sacrifice is refuted after }11...Rxe3?! 12.Kd2! Qf4 13.fxe3 Qxg3 14.Rh3 { and White is up in material. It's better for Black not to sacrifice on  e3 , but after }{   }11...Qb4 12.Qd2 Qe7 13.h5 Ne4 14.Nxe4 Bxe4 15.h6 g6 16.O-O-O { White managed to weaken Black's kingside and will play on the kingside with  Rg1 ,  g4  etc. while also having in mind the idea to play  f3  and further harass the bishop on  e4 . } )
11. h5{ Continuing with the plan. The pawn on  h5  pins down Black's kingside and after the exchange of the bishops White will obtain the  f5 -square for the knight. }
11. Bh7
12. Bd3{ The bishops are exchanged as without it Black can no longer control the  f5 -square. }
12. Bxd3
13. Qxd3{ White's plan is simple now. Plant a knight on  f5  and continue with  f3 ,  g4  and eventually organise a  g5  break. }
13. Re8{ A flexible move for Black, still not determining the position of the knight on  b8  or the placement of the c-pawn. }
14. Rc1( { A flexible move from White, too! Black's idea can be seen in case of the more natural }14.O-O-O { when }14...Nc6! { is strong - the knight will go to  e7  to cover the  f5 -square and then Black can prepare the ... c5  push without having wasted time on ... c6 . } )( { Similar is }14.Nf5 Qe6 15.f3 Nc6! { again with the idea to challenge the knight on  f5  with ... Ne7 . That is why White plays a move that hints at possible play on the queenside. This is important in case Black still plays ... Nc6 . } )
14. c6( { White's idea is to meet }14...Nc6 { with }15.O-O! { and then Black cannot play }15...Ne7? { because }16.Nb5 { wins the pawn on  c7 . } )( { If Black prepares  ...Ne7  by }15...a6 { , then }16.Na4! { pinpoints the awkward queenside development of the black knight as White wants to play  Nc5  with easy queenside play. } )
15. Nf5{ Only now, when Black cannot challenge the knight with ... Nc6 - e7 , does White plant a knight on  f5 . }
15. Qe6
16. f3{ With a stable knight on  f5  White continues with the plan outlined in the comments to White's 13th move, with  g4 - g5  being the main idea, but also with the additional idea of  Rc2 - e2  (to cover the e-file and possibly support  e4 ). The king will take a walk to the queenside via  d1  and  c1 . }
16. Nbd7
17. Rc2{ The rook is transferred to  e2 . }
17. Rad8
18. Re2{ White will take the king to the safety on the queenside by playing  Kd1 - c1  and then can concentrate on preparation of  g4 - g5  or  e4 . The position is objectively balanced, but White has a clear ideas of what to do in the next several moves. }
