1. d5
2. c4
2. e6{ The Queen's Gambit Declined (QGD) is one of the most solid openings in existence. Black supports the pawn centre in classical fashion, not giving up space. There are many variations and development set-ups that Black can employ in the QGD, so White's task with the next move is to limit them to the maximum and at the same time achieve, as much as possible, universality of his own development. }
3. cxd5( { By taking on  d5  before  Nc3  White eliminates three important variations: the Semi-Tarrasch, arising after }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 Nxd5 { , the Schara-Hennig Gambit, arising after   }3.Nc3 c5 4.cxd5 cxd4 { , and the line   }3.Nc3 dxc4 { , where White needs to play }4.e4 { and enter different lines of the Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA) than the ones we analyse in this repertoire. } )
3. exd5
4. Nc3( { With the above options eliminated, White enters the Carlsbad structure. It's worth noting that the move }4.Bf4 { is also possible, which would most likely lead to a transposition to the analysed lines, except for the line }4...c5 { , when White should play }5.e3 Nc6 6.Bb5 { . }{ Before giving an outline of Black's options, I'd like to introduce you to the possible plans White has in this structure. These plans are:  1. The minority attack ( b4 - b5  followed by  bxc6  and then play against the backward pawn on  c6 );  2. The building of a pawn centre by  f3  and  e4  (the so-called Botvinnik plan, because he was the first one to employ it, see the origin game in the model section  Botvinnik-Keres ) or playing  f3  and  g4 ,  h4 , expanding on the kingside;  3. Play in the centre by pushing  e4  (without the support of  f3 );  4. Castling long with an attack on the kingside;  5. Planting a Pillsbury knight on  e5  (supported by  f4 ) as a focal point for a kingside attack, played with a short castle;  6. The AlphaZero plan of a short castle, allowing ... Bg4xf3 ,  gxf3  and then using the g-file for an attack on the kingside (see the model game  AlphaZero-Stockfish ). } )( { Now, after knowing White's possible plans, let's see Black's choices here: the pawn moves }4...a6 { , }4...c6 { , }4...c5 { and }4...h6 { are all possible, as are the developing moves }4...Bb4 { , }4...Be7 { and }4...Nf6 { . In spite of this variety, White's play in the next moves is very simple and consists of the following ideas: the dark-squared bishop is developed on  f4 , followed by  e3  and  Bd3  (if possible) in order to prevent Black's developing ... Bf5 . If White succeeds in this then he has the plans outlined above at his disposal. In case Black manages to play ... Bf5  before White plays  Bd3 , White will try to harass that bishop by one (or more) of the following:  Nge2 - g3 ,  Nf3 - h4 ,  h3  and  g4  or  f3  and then either  g4  or  e4 . Then White will reconsider which of the 6 plans is applicable to the situation at hand. } )
4. Nf6( { This position normally arises after   }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 exd5 { . } )
5. Bf4( { The main move is }5.Bg5 { , }{ but recently the development of the bishop on  f4  got a fair share of attention from the world's best players. } )
5. c6( { This is the usual QGD move, establishing the standard Carlsbad structure. Note that the move }5...c5 6.Nf3 Nc6 7.e3 { would lead to the Tarrasch Defence (via   }4...c5 5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Bf4 Nf6 7.e3 { ) while   }5...Bb4 6.e3 { was analysed via the move order   }4...Bb4 5.Bf4 Nf6 { . } )( { Another transposition arises after }5...Be7 { , analysed after   }4...Be7 5.Bf4 Nf6 { . } )
6. e3{ The usual move for White, planning  Bd3  in order to prevent the development of the black bishop to  f5 . }
6. Bf5{ The most principled move, developing the bishop on the most active square. }
7. Nge2( { The standard idea for White, once the bishop is on  f5  White goes after it. A very interesting alternative is }7.f3!? { with the idea of  g4  or  e4  (in some lines). Here Black's best move is }7...Nh5! { and curious complications arise after }8.Bxb8 Rxb8 9.g4 Qh4 10.Kd2 Ng3 11.gxf5 Nxh1 12.Nh3 { when White will win the knight on  h1  and have material advantage, while Black will try to organise play against White's king in the centre. } )
7. Nh5( { Black uses the fact that the queen on  d1  no longer covers the  h5 -square, so the knight can attack the bishop on  f4 . A neutral move like }7...Be7 { allows White to achieve his idea of }8.Ng3 Bg6 9.h4 { (intending  h5 ,  Bd3  and after the exchange on  d3  White will have the  f5 -square for the knight) }9...h5 10.Bd3 Bxd3 11.Qxd3 g6 { (Black covers the  f5 -square) }12.O-O-O { with very pleasant play for White who will play  Kb1 ,  f3  and prepare  e4 . } )
8. Be5{ Avoiding the exchange and leaving the knight on the rim. }
8. Nd7
9. h3{ Threatening to win a piece by  g4  and opening a luft on  h2  for the bishop. }
9. Bg6( { Avoiding the fork. In case of }9...Nhf6 10.Ng3 Bg6 11.Bf4 Be7 12.Bd3 { White obtains access to the  f5 -square and after the exchange of the bishops can also plan for short castling,  f3  and  e4 . } )
10. Qb3{ A common move when the bishop is no longer on  c8 , hitting the pawn on  b7 . }
10. Qb6( { This is one of the possible defences. After }10...b5 11.g4 Nhf6 12.Bg2 { White has a pleasant position. Note that taking the bishop on  e5  is bad for Black, for example }12...Nxe5?! 13.dxe5 Nd7 14.O-O { intending  f4  and the pawn on  e5  is poisonous, }14...Nxe5? 15.Nxd5! { is devastating. } )( { Another option for Black is }10...Nb6 11.g4 Nf6 12.Nf4 Bd6 13.Bxd6 Qxd6 14.Be2 O-O 15.h4 { with play on the kingside. White will castle long and continue pushing the pawns. } )
11. Bh2( { The bishop retreats to  h2 . This is more flexible than the immediate }11.g4 { because White keeps the option of playing  f3  and then choose whether to expand with  e4  or  g4 . } )
11. Nhf6( { The knight had nothing to do on  h5  anymore. The exchange of queens gives White a pleasant endgame }11...Qxb3 12.axb3 Nhf6 13.f3 Bb4 14.g4 { with the idea of  h4 - h5 ,  Kd2  etc. when the plan of kingside expansion is easy to follow through. } )
12. f3{ Covering the  e4 -square, thus preventing ideas based on ... Ne4 . White now wants to expand with  g4 ,  h4 - h5 . }
12. h5{ It makes a lot of sense to stop White's plan of kingside expansion. }
13. Nc1( { White needs to finish the development of the kingside and this move ensures that he does. It's important to put the knight on  c1 , from where it covers the  b3 -square. To illustrate the difference, after }13.Nf4?! Qxb3 14.axb3 Bc2! { White has problems defending the  b3 -pawn. } )
13. h4{ Fixing White's kingside. Now that  g4  is never really possible, White will switch to the plan of central advance with  e4 . }
14. Bd3{ Developing with tempo and forcing Black to take on  d3 . }
14. Bxd3
15. Nxd3{ The knight is very well placed on  d3 , from where it controls the important dark squares  b4 ,  c5  and  e5 . }
15. Be7( { In the endgame after }15...Qxb3 16.axb3 { White threatens a quick  b4 - b5  (thanks to the knight on  d3  that supports  b4 ) }16...a6 17.b4 { (threatening  b5 ) }17...Rc8 18.Nc5 Nxc5 19.bxc5 { with a pleasant pressure in the endgame thanks to the superior structure - White has only one pawn island! } )
16. Qc2{ White now prefers a middlegame with the queens on board. The main reason is that the black king is not entirely safe anywhere - on the queenside White can launch a pawn storm, while on the kingside the absence of the rook on  h8  means that the pawn on  h4  would need constant attention. Aside from these general considerations, White's plan is to execute the  e4 -advance. A sample line is }
16. O-O
17. O-O
17. Nh5
18. Kh1{ Moving away from the vulnerable  g1 - a7  diagonal. }
18. Rfe8
19. Rad1{ Lending support to the pawn on  d4 , thus preparing  e4 . }
19. Rad8{ Black also prepares for the opening in the centre. }
20. Qf2{ The final preparatory move, defending the pawn on  d4 , keeping an eye on the pawn on  h4  and doubling on the f-file, which would be particularly useful in case of ... dxe4 ,  fxe4 . White will play  e4  on the next move and this will provide possibilities for a kingside attack, either by the opening of the f-file in case Black exchanges on  e4  or by pushing  e5 , followed by  f4 - f5  etc. }
