4. Nc3{ While Black has many options here, the good aspect from White's point of view is that the reaction is universal: the bishop comes to  f4  and irrelevant whether it's exchanged on  d6  or not White follows up with  e3 , intending  Bd3  and then either  Nf3  or  Nge2 . If Black plays ... Bf5  before White plays  Bd3 , then White goes after the bishop on  f5  with  Nge2 - g3  or  f3  and  e4 / g4 . }
4. Nf6( { One of the main QGD moves, the other one being }4...Be7 { . The 'little' pawn moves }4...h6 { and }4...a6 { are met by }5.Bf4 { when play will follow the standard development of the Carlsbad structure. } )( 4...c5 { The Tarrasch Defence. }5.Nf3 Nc6 6.Bf4 { Staying in line with the development in all the other lines the bishop goes to  f4 . }6...Nf6 7.e3 { White wants to create an IQP on  d5  by taking on  c5 , possibly following up with  Bb5 . }7...c4 { This is Black's best. }( { After }7...cxd4 8.Nxd4 { with  Be2 ,  O-O  to come White has the standard IQP play with  Rc1 ,  Qa4 ,  Rfd1  etc. } )8.a3! { An important move that prevents ... Bb4 . By keeping the knight on  c3  unpinned White maintains control of the  e4 -square. }8...Qb6 ( { After the natural }8...Be7 9.Bxc4! { is a surprising sacrifice that leads to a pleasant endgame after }9...dxc4 10.d5 Nxd5 { (this is safest, otherwise after  d6  White has strong initiative) }11.Qxd5 Qxd5 12.Nxd5 { thanks to the strong knight on  d5 . } )9.Qc1 9...Be7 10.Be2 O-O 11.h3 { Not only preventing ... Bg4  but also preparing  g4  in some lines. }11...Na5 ( { The move }11...Bf5 { only invites }12.g4 Be6 13.Qc2 { , }{ with play on both wings with  Rfb1 ,  Nd2  and  b3  on the queenside and  Bf1 - g2 ,  Rfe1 ,  Rad1  and  Ne5  in the centre and kingside. } )12.Nd2 Be6 { Putting the bishop on  f5  again would be met by  g4 . }13.O-O { White has two pawn breaks,  b3  and  e4  and they are the primary positional ideas. If these don't work, then a pawn advance on the kingside with  f4 - f5 ,  g4  etc. may be possible. } )( 4...c6 { The most common move for Black in the Carlsbad structure. }5.Bf4 Bd6 ( { If }5...Bf5 { then }6.f3! { with  g4  to come, followed by  e3 ,  Bd3 ,  Nge2 . } )6.Bxd6 Qxd6 7.e3 { Intending  Bd3 . }7...Bf5 ( { If }7...Ne7 { then }8.Qb3 { ensures that when White plays  Bd3  it cannot be met by ... Bf5  because the pawn on  b7  would hang. } )8.g4 { As a rule of thumb, whenever the black bishop makes it to  f5 , White should look for ways to harass it. }8...Be6 { Dropping back to  g6  invites  Nge2 - f4 , when in an appropriate moment White will take on  g6 . }9.h4 { Grabbing space and preparing  Nh3 - f4 . }9...Nd7 10.Nh3 O-O-O 11.Nf4 { White will also castle long after  Qf3 , when the knight will come to the ideal  d3 -square, from where it controls both  c5  and  e5 . } )( 4...Be7 5.Bf4 c6 ( 5...Nf6 { With this move Black usually seeks counterplay in the centre based on the ... c5 -break. }6.e3 Bf5 ( { Or }6...O-O 7.Bd3 c5 8.Nge2 Nc6 9.O-O { when White is somewhat more pleasant in the position with a fixed centre after the exchanges of pawns and knights on  d4 , or after }9...c4 10.Bc2 a6 11.Be5 { White puts pressure on the  d5 -pawn after  Nf4 , threatening  Bxf6 . } )7.Nge2 { The standard reaction of going after the bishop on  f5  with  Ng3 . }7...O-O 8.Ng3 Be6 ( { If }8...Bg6 9.h4! h6 10.h5 Bh7 11.Bd3 Bxd3 12.Qxd3 { White obtains the  f5 -square for the knight. } )9.Bd3 c5 10.dxc5 Bxc5 11.O-O Nc6 12.Rc1 { White wants to play against the IQP with  Nb5  or  Nge2 , taking control of the  d4 -square. }12...d4 13.Nce4 Be7 14.Nxf6+ Bxf6 15.Ne4 dxe3 16.Nxf6+ Qxf6 17.fxe3 { A sharp position where White has the pair of bishops and big piece activity while Black is solid with a better pawn structure. Ideas like  Qh5 ,  Rc5 - g5 ( h5 ) are all in the air. } )6.e3 Bf5 ( { After }6...Bd6 7.Bxd6 Qxd6 8.Bd3 Ne7 9.Qb3!? { limits the mobility of Black's light-squared bishop. } )7.Nge2 Nd7 ( { This is precise, as }7...Nf6?! 8.Ng3 Bg6 9.h4! { is a typical idea for White, gaining space on the kingside by chasing the bishop. } )8.h4 { A subtlety. }( { The natural way would be to start with }8.Ng3 Bg6 9.h4 { , }{ but it turns out that here Black can take on  h4  with }9...Bxh4! { and White doesn't have much. That is why White starts with  h4  first, as now the pawn is indeed taboo. } )8...Ngf6 ( { If }8...Bxh4? 9.Qb3 Nb6 ( 9...b5? 10.Rxh4! Qxh4 11.Nxd5 cxd5 12.Qxd5 Qd8 13.Qxf5 { is crushing. } )10.a4! Bc8 11.a5 Nc4 12.e4 { with a strong initiative. } )9.Ng3 Be6 10.Bd3 { Thanks to the  Nge2 - g3  maneuver White achieved the aim of placing the bishop on the ideal  d3 -square. Next  Nf5  will come, gaining the pair of bishops when White will continue play on the kingside with  h4 - h5 , possibly  f3 ,  g4  etc. } )
