1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. dxc4{ The Queen's Gambit Accepted (QGA) has a long history and solid reputation, having featured even in World Championship matches. It was used by Petrosian in his match with Botvinnik in 1963 and by Kasparov against Kramnik in 2000. It was also used by Fischer in his match with Spassky in 1992. The idea of the opening is that Black immediately releases the tension in the centre and plans to attack White's centre either by ... c5  or ... e5 . }
3. e3( { I found this move much more pratical than the main alternatives }3.Nf3 { and }3.e4 { . The reasons are the following. In case of the former, apart from the main line   }3...Nf6 4.e3 e6 { , }{ which is the one we look at after our move-order with  3.e3 , Black has two additional options, }{   }3...a6 4.e3 b5 { (or }4...Bg4 { ) and }{   }3...Nf6 4.e3 Bg4 { . } )( { After }3.e3 { Black has only one extra option, which is }3...e5 { . } )( { The move }3.e4 { is the most ambitious one, but here Black has a wide choice of options: }3...Nf6 { , }3...Nc6 { , }3...e5 { , }3...c5 { all of which have a lot of theory developed, plus the recently very popular }3...b5 { , }{ which leads to massive complications. With all this in mind, I selected the move  3.e3  as the preferred move order. } )
3. Nf6
4. Bxc4
4. e6
5. Nf3
5. c5
6. O-O
6. a6
7. Qe2( { White has many options in this tabiya. The endgame after }7.dxc5 { is dry, though playable, the modern attempts with }7.Nbd2 { or }7.b3 { are too subtle and not direct enough. I was attracted to the old move }7.Qe2 { (first played by Rubinstein in 1908!) because it's simple to play. White continues with  Rd1 , placing the rook on the d-file when  dxc5  becomes a threat. After Black's ... b5  White plays  Bd3  and attacks the queenside by  a4 . There isn't a big variety of options for Black so the ideas for White can be grasped easily. } )
