3. e3{ The fastest way to regain the pawn. }
3. e5{ This is the only alternative. Black uses the fact that White didn't develop the knight on  f3  and strikes in the centre. }
4. Bxc4{ White regains the pawn. }
4. Nc6{ This is an alternative, keeping the pawn presence in the centre and putting more pressure on the pawn on  d4 . }
5. Nf3{ White develops, defends the pawn on  d4  and attack the pawn on  e5 . }
5. e4( { Taking on  d4  is extremely risky, }5...exd4?! 6.O-O { intending  Qb3  gives White a dangerous initiative, for example }6...dxe3 7.Qb3 exf2 8.Rxf2 Be6 9.Qxb7 { and Black is walking a thin rope not to lose immediately. } )
6. Qb3( { It's also possible to retreat the knight immediately with }6.Nfd2 { , }{ but this is more forcing, developing the queen with tempo and forcing Black to place a knight on the rim to defend the  f7 -pawn. } )
6. Nh6{ The only reasonable way to defend the pawn on  f7 . }
7. Nfd2{ Now the knight retreats and attacks the pawn on  e4 . }
7. f5( { Black defends the pawn, but weakens the  a2 - g8  diagonal. In case of }7...Qg5 8.Bf1 f5 9.Nc3 { White has similar easy development with  Nc4 ,  Bd2 , and possibly  g3  or  h4 . } )
8. Nc3{ White develops naturally. }
8. Bd6
9. Be2{ This retreat allows the knight to come to  c4  and go after the bishop on  d6 . }
9. Nf7{ Black needs to shut the  a2 - g8  diagonal if he wants to castle short. }
10. Nc4{ White continues with the plan. }
10. Be7{ Black avoids the exchange because the dark-squared bishop is his more active one, as the one on  c8  has very limited mobility in view of the pawn on  f5 . }
11. O-O{ White is almost finished with development. }
11. O-O
12. Rd1( { This is natural. A good alternative is }12.d5!? Nb8 13.Rd1 { , }{ but White can simply finish development with  Bd2  and start play on the queenside with  a4 - a5  etc. } )
12. Kh8{ Getting away from the vulnerable diagonal. }
13. Bd2{ White's development is complete. It is possible to further consolidate the position with moves like  Bf1  and  Be1 , but it's also possible to start queenside play immediately by advancing the a-pawn as far as possible. The idea to push  d5  is still viable, as are ideas to use the c-file later on, the knight transfer  Ne2 - f4 ,  Na4 - c5  etc. }
