14. Qxh6+
14. Nh7( { The only move, as }14...Kg8? 15.Ne5 { wins for White. } )
15. Ne4{ Bringing the reserves with tempo. Because Black's pawn is on  c6  the bishop on  d6  is undefended and this is the reason why the sacrifice works only in this case - with a pawn on  c7  Black can play ... Bf5  and repel White's attack. }
15. Be7
16. Ne5{ Continuing the onslaught. }
16. Bf5( { This is Black's best defence. Taking on  d4  leads to a better endgame for White after the forcing }16...Qxd4?! 17.Nxf7 Rxf7 18.Bxf7 Qxe4 19.Rae1 Qh4 20.Qxh4 Bxh4 21.Re4! { (double attack on both black pieces on the 4th rank) }21...Bf6 22.Rxb4 { and the three connected passed pawns on the kingside are a big factor in the endgame. } )( { Another try is }16...Nd5 { but after }17.f4 Bf5 18.Ng5 { White has a strong initiative. } )
17. Qf4( { Defending the knight on  e4  and attacking the bishop. White can also take a third pawn with }17.Bxf7 { , which forces Black to seek an endgame after }17...Bg5 18.Nxg5 Qxg5 19.Qxg5 Nxg5 20.Bb3 { , }{ when the three connected passed pawns on the kingside are not inferior to the piece. } )( { Another option is }17.Rae1 { , which keeps all the tension in the position. } )
17. f6( { In case of the simpler }17...Bxe4 18.Qxe4 { the pawn on  f7  still hangs and the unsafe position of the black king makes White's position much easier to play. By playing ... f6  Black removes the pawn from the attacked square. } )
18. Nf7+( { Winning the rook. In case of }18.Qxf5 fxe5 19.Qxe5 Bf6 { Black manages to coordinate his pieces. } )
18. Rxf7
19. Bxf7
19. Qd7
20. Bc4{ The bishop was exposed on  f7 , so White brings it back to a safe square. The position is very complicated, and is materially and dynamically balanced.  White's rook and two pawns will be stronger than Black's two light pieces in an endgame, which makes White's long-term prospects favourable, but for the time being there are a lot of pieces on the board. White wants to use his rooks in the centre, either on the e and d-files or to double on the e-file. Another idea is for  Ng3  to push back the bishop from  f5 . White will combine play in the centre and on the kingside. }
