1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. dxc4
3. e3{ The fastest way to regain the pawn. }
3. Nf6{ This is the main move, which in the vast majority of cases would lead to the main line and tabiya that arises on move 6. }( { Black can also start with }3...e6 4.Bxc4 Nf6 { etc. or   }3...a6 3.Bxc4 e6 4.Nf3 c5 5.O-O Nf6 { . } )( { Another transposition occurs after }3...c5 4.Bxc4 cxd4 5.exd4 Nf6 6.Nc3 e6 7.Nf3 Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Qe2 { , }{ which is analysed via the 3... Nf6  move-order, when on move 6 Black plays 6... cxd4  ( }{   }3...Nf6 4.Bxc4 e6 5.Nf3 c5 6.O-O cxd4 { ). } )( { One of the oldest opening traps in chess happens after the naive }3...b5? 4.a4 c6 5.axb5 cxb5 6.Qf3 { , }{ when White wins a piece. Surprisingly, this still happens a lot in online chess! } )( { Black can try to defend the pawn on  c4  with }3...Be6?! { but this leaves him with clumsy development after }4.Nf3 c6 5.Nbd2 b5 6.a4 Qa5 7.Ra3! { and White will regain the pawn and remain with a better structure after }7...b4 8.Ra1 c3 9.bxc3 bxc3 10.Nb3 Qc7 11.Nc5 { as the pawn on  c3  won't live for long. } )
4. Bxc4{ Pawn regained. }
4. e6( { Black's moves include  ...c5  and  ...a6  later on, though it's also possible to start with }4...a6 5.Nf3 e6 { . } )
5. Nf3{ White continues the development of the kingside. The queenside remains still for the time being as White keeps the flexibility with the development of the queen's knight as depending on circumstances it can be developed to  c3  or  d2 . }
5. a6{ This can also lead to the main line, but there is an independent variation where Black first develops with ... b5  and ... Bb7  before playing ... c5 . }
6. O-O
6. b5( { Obviously, }6...c5 { would lead to the main line. } )
7. Bd3{ The bishop stays on the  f1 - a6  diagonal because White's plan is to undermine Black's prematurely advanced pawns on the queenside with  a4 . }
7. Bb7( { Playing }7...c5 { is dubious, after }8.dxc5 Bxc5 9.a4 { Black's queenside is under attack and }9...b4 10.Qe2 { gives White easy play after  Nbd2 - b3 ,  e4 - e5  etc. } )
8. a4{ White starts the attack immediately. }
8. b4
9. Nbd2{ Now we see the benefit of the delay in the development of the queenside. The queen's knight has excellent perspectives on  b3  or  c4 . }
9. c5
10. Nc4{ The knight is very active on  c4 . From there it can support the  a5  advance, which would fix the weak  b6 -square. }
10. Nbd7( { Black covers the  b6 -square. This move is inevitable once White plays  a5  as Black would like to defend against  Nb6 . Note that physically stopping White's  a5  with }10...a5? { is bad as the weakening of the  b5 -square makes it even worse for Black after }11.Nce5 { with  Bb5  to come next. } )
11. a5{ Fixing Black's queenside and taking away the  b6 -square. }
11. Be7
12. Re1{ The advance of the e-pawn is one of White's main ideas. The rook is used to support the pawn because later on the queen can come to  g4  in one go. Additionally, the rook frees the  f1 -square for the bishop on  d3 . }
12. O-O
13. e4{ The pawn will go one square further. }
13. cxd4{ This exchange frees the  c5 -square for the knight. }
14. e5{ White gains space before capturing on  d4 . The pawns on  a5  and  e5  take away the  d6  and  b6 -squares and as a result severely limit the mobility of Black's pieces. }
14. Nd5( { After }14...Bxf3 15.Qxf3 Nd5 16.Qh3 g6 17.Bh6 Re8 18.Re4 { White regains the pawn and has an edge thanks to the dominating knight on  c4  and the pawns on  a5  and  e5 . } )
15. Nxd4{ Both knights and the pawns on  a5  and  e5  control the vacant squares on the 6th rank and this makes Black suffer for lack of space. }
15. Nc5
16. Bf1{ The bishop stays on the  f1 - a6  diagonal to have the important knight on  c4  safely protected. }
16. Rc8
17. Bd2{ Developing the last light piece. White will play  Qg4  next (threatening  Bh6 ) and then  Rac1  or  Rad1 . Strategically White will aim for  Bg5 , to exchange the defender of the  d6 -square. }
