14. Nxe5
15. Bxe5{ It's also possible to take with a pawn. The bishop remains active on the  h2 - b8  diagonal and safely defends the pawn on  d4 . White plays on the queenside, a known, but not very often seen play in a position with an IQP. The reason why it works is that Black has weakened the queenside by advancing the b-pawn, so the  c5 -square is weak and White's knight is ideally positioned to take advantage of it. }
15. Bd5{ As a way of compensation, Black has control of the  d5 -square. }
16. Qd3( { A good alternative is }16.Rac1 { , a natural move that controls the c-file and helps the  Nc5  jump. Equally natural is the immediate jump }16.Nc5 { . }{ White will continue with  Rac1 ,  Nc5 , and possibly  Qg3 . In case of ... Bxb3 ,  axb3  will be the correct recapture as that opens the a-file (so the rook can use it to target Black's a-pawn) and it lends extra cover to the  c4 -square, which White can use for a rook (to double on the c-file) or in some cases for the queen.  The position is objectively equal, though it is certainly White who has more concrete ideas to play with, as Black, while solid, doesn't have active possibilities. } )
