8. Qc7{ Black postpones the ... b5  push and removes the queen from the d-file. }
9. Nc3{ White continues development and now the idea is to push  d5  or to take on  c5  in case Black moves the dark-squared bishop, thus winning tempo for development. }
9. b5( { In case of }9...Be7 10.dxc5 { wins a tempo. After }10...Bxc5 11.b3 { followed by  Bb2  White has easy development while Black has to develop the bishop on  c8  and his queen on  c7  is not well placed as after White's  Rac1  the queen will be vulnerable on the c-file. } )
10. Bd3( { The bishop stays on the  f1 - d3  diagonal in order to target Black's  b5  and  a6 -pawns after  a4 . White has a very sharp alternative in the piece sacrifice }10.d5!? Nb4 11.d6 Qb8 ( 11...Bxd6?! 12.Bxb5 { is good for White, who remains with a better structure. } )12.e4 bxc4 13.Bf4 { with excellent compensation. } )
10. Bb7( { In case of }10...Nb4 { the sacrifice }11.Nxb5! { is very promising. After }11...axb5 12.Bxb5 Nc6 13.dxc5 { White obtains three pawns for the piece plus the initiative. Note that Black cannot take on  c5  because that opens the c-file and exposes the pinned knight on  c6 : }13...Bxc5?! 14.Qc4! Nd7 15.Bd2 Bb7 16.Bc3 { and in view of the threat  Bxg7  and  Rxd7 , when the bishop on  c5  is hanging, White has an advantage. } )
11. Bd2{ White finished development and is now ready to play on the queenside and in the centre. The main ideas are  Rac1 ,  dxc5 ,  e4 - e5  and  a4 . }
11. c4( { This is safest for Black, as it deals with most of White's ideas. To illustrate, }11...Be7?! 12.dxc5 Bxc5 13.Rac1 { followed by  e4 - e5  gives White the initiative. } )( { Or }11...cxd4 12.exd4 Be7 13.Rac1 O-O 14.Ne4 { targeting the  c5 -square and with ideas like  Ne5 , taking advantage of the vulnerable position of the queen on  c7 , White has easy play. } )
12. Bb1( { This retreat avoids attacks with  ...Nb4 , but it is in fact possible to allow it. For example, }12.Bc2 Nb4 13.Bb1 { with the idea of  e4 , but here Black has the temporary pawn sacrifice }13...Nd3!? 14.Bxd3 cxd3 15.Qxd3 b4 16.Na4 Bxf3 17.gxf3 Qc6 18.b3 Qxf3 19.Qf1! { with  Qg2  next, which leads to unclear play. } )
12. Be7( { If Black plays }12...Rd8 { , }{ intending to prevent  e4  by putting pressure on the  d4 -pawn, White undermines Black's queenside with }13.a4 b4 14.Ne4 { when Black's pawns on  c4  and  b4  are somewhat loose. } )
13. e4{ White advances in the centre and wants to play  e5 . }
13. e5{ Stopping  e5 . Otherwise White pushes  e5  and then starts play on the kingside with the help of the h-pawn by pushing it as far as possible. }
14. dxe5( { Unfortunately, }14.d5?! Nd4 { doesn't work for White, so by taking on  e5  White establishes a majority in the centre and kingside. } )
14. Nxe5
15. Bf4{ Activating the dark-squared bishop by attacking the knight on  e5 . }
15. Nxf3+
16. Qxf3
16. Qc5
17. Qh3( { White removes the queen from the pin on the long diagonal and threatens  e5 . There are several alternatives, like the sharp }17.g4!? { or }17.Be3 { . } )
17. Bc8( { Black wants to get rid of the queen on  h3  in order to allow for castling. In case of }17...Qc8 18.Qxc8 Rxc8 19.Bc2 { with  f3  to come the endgame is complex. White's structure of  g2 ,  f3  and  e4  limits the activity of the bishop on  b7  and White can more easily centralise the king with  Kf2  and even  Ke3 . Additionally, White can undermine Black's advanced majority on the queenside by  a4 . } )
18. Qe3{ White doesn't mind the endgame. }
18. Qxe3
19. Bxe3
19. Be6
20. Bc2{ Connecting the rooks. White can then continue with  a3 ,  f3 , and  Kf2 , stabilising the queenside and intending to advance the kingside majority or  a3  and  h3 , intending to push  e5  and  f4 , activating the majority in a more immediate manner. }
