7. b5( 7...Nc6 { This is the alternative to the push of the b-pawn, though Black will have to push that pawn sooner rather than later. }8.Rd1 b5 ( { Or }8...Qc7 9.Nc3 b5 10.Bd3 { ( }10.d5!? { is a sharp alternative) }{   }10...Bb7 11.Bd2 { with  dxc5  and  Rac1  to play on the queenside, while after }11...c4 12.Bb1 { White will push  e4 . } )9.dxc5 { This is the difference for White when allowed to have the rook on  d1  - it is just in time to allow for this capture. }9...Qc7 10.Bd3 { White's plan is to attack the queenside with  a4 . }10...Bxc5 11.a4 bxa4 ( { Pushing }11....b4 { is worse as }12.b3 { followed by  Bb2 ,  Nbd2  and  Rac1  gives White rich play on the queenside thanks to Black's over-extended pawns. } )12.Rxa4 { Now the a-pawn comes under attack, which gives White the initiative. } )
8. Bd3
8. Nbd7( { In case of }8...cxd4 9.a4 bxa4 10.Rxa4 { is a promising pawn sacrifice that gives White free development with  Bxe3 ,  Nc3  and  Rd1 . } )
9. a4
9. c4
10. Bc2
10. Bb7
11. e4{ White will play on the kingside with  Bg5 ,  e5 ,  Qe4 - h4 ,  Nbd2  etc. }
