[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) Slav: Introduction"]
[Black "Slav: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6{ The Slav Defence is tough opening. For example, it has been one of Anand's main defences against  1.d4  since his Candidates match against Karpov in 1991 and it was definitely the opening that won him the match against Kramnik in 2008. The Slav is a difficult opening to play against because Black has a wide choice of good variations: the Semi-Slav, the Classical Slav, the Schlechter Variation, and the Chebanenko are all extremely solid. }
3. cxd5{ The Exchange Slav is by far the most practical approach White can take when facing this popular opening. It cuts down all Black's options (no more Semi-Slav, Classical Slav, Schlechter Variation, or the Chebanenko) and immediately takes the game down a path that White has chosen. }
3. cxd5
4. Nc3( { The main lines of the Exchange Variation start with }4.Bf4 { (a move White can play immediately or after }4.Nc3 { first) and these have developed a huge theory of their own. I have played these lines with a lot of success, but it was never an easy task to revise and memorise all the delicate intricacies of the move orders before each game when I expected the Slav! } )
4. Nc6
5. Nf3
5. Nf6
6. Ne5( { How I came up with this rare move is very intriguing. I was agonising for many days about what to suggest against the Slav. I was aware that even in the Exchange Variation, where }6.Bf4 { is the main move, which can be played with or without a knight on  f3 , there is a lot of theory and nuances of move orders and ideas. What helped me was a divine intervention (!). Quite unexpectedly, I was blessed with a fortuitous insight one night. } )( { As I was sleeping, in my dream I clearly saw the board with the four knights on  c3 ,  f3 ,  c6  and  f6  and then move }6.Ne5 { appeared! I didn't remember what happened next in the dream, but this was enough. Luckily, I still remembered the move when I woke up and I didn't waste time - I immediately started analysing it. It turned out that this rare move led to interesting and original play. } )
