1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6
3. cxd5
3. cxd5
4. Nc3{ Since the knights will be developed to  c3  and  f3 , it makes little difference with which knight White starts. However, the opponent doesn't know that, so starting with the knight from  b1  keeps the options open, for example to play  Bf4  and  e3  before developing the knight from  g1 . }
4. Nf6( { Black can also start with this or with }4...Nc6 5.Nf3 { and now in case of the rare }5...a6 { White can also play a useful waiting move like }6.a3 { waiting for }6...Nf6 7.Ne5 { , }{ when  a3  is more useful than ... a6  - it takes away the  b4 -square from Black and sometimes supports  b4 , while ... a6  prevents Black from playing ... Ba6  in some lines. } )
5. Nf3
5. Nc6( { The usual choice. The alternatives are moves like }5...a6 { or }5...e6 { , but against both White can play in the same way with }6.Ne5 { when sooner rather than later Black will put the knight on  c6 , or in case of }{   }5...e6 6.Ne5 Nbd7 7.e3 Nxe5 8.dxe5 { we have a transposition to the lines we look at after   }5...Nc6 6.Ne5 e6 7.e3 Nxe5 8.dxe5 { . } )
6. Ne5( { Here comes the surprise. This very rare move won't bring an advantage, but it does take the game down less explored paths. The main move is }6.Bf4 { , but then }6...Nh5 { , }6...Bf5 { and }6...a6 { are all major options for Black. } )
6. Qb6{ This is a direct attempt to take advantage of the fact that the knight no longer defends the  d4 -pawn. }
7. e3( { White defends the knight and intends to support the centralised knight with  f4 . An alternative is to take on  c6 , }7.Nxc6 bxc6 8.a3 e6 9.Na4 Qc7 10.g3 { with  Bg2 ,  Bf4  (if possible) and  O-O  to come, when White will concentrate on the c-file where Black has a backward pawn on  c6  and a weak square on  c5 . } )
7. e6( { Black cannot really develop the light-squared bishop on  f5  as }7...Bf5?! 8.Bd2 { with the threats of  Rc1 ,  Na4  and even  g4 - g5  (since the pawn on  d5  is only defended by the knight on  f6 ) White has an unpleasant initiative. } )
8. f4{ One of the typical positions White is aiming in this line with  6.Ne5 . The knight serves as a guide for future play on the kingside. White's play is simple, with  Bd3 ,  O-O ,  Bd2 - e1 - h4 , and possibly  g4 - g5 , to create an attack on the kingside. }
8. Be7
9. Bd3{ Both sides develop naturally. }
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. Bd7
11. a3{ A useful move for White. It takes away the  b4 -square from the black knight on  c6 , thus ensuring that the bishop on  d3 , which is a very important attacking piece for White, remains safe. }
11. Rfc8{ The only side where Black can create counterplay is the queenside. By putting a rook on  c8  Black intends ... Na5 - c4 . }
12. Bd2{ White finishes development. Since the dark-squared bishop is not very active, it is often activated via  e1  and  h4 . }
12. Be8( { Taking the pawn on  b2  leads to loss of the queen after }12...Qxb2?? 13.Na4 { . } )( { To illustrate the danger that Black faces, look at what happens if Black continues with the natural }12...Na5?! 13.g4! { (threatening  g5  to win the bishop on  d7 ) }13...Be8 14.g5 Nd7 15.Bxh7! Kxh7 16.Nxd7 Bxd7 17.Qh5 Kg8 18.Rf3 { and the attack is decisive. After }18...g6 19.Qh4 Bf8 20.f5! gxf5 21.Rg3 { with  g6  next is winning for White. } )
13. Be1( { The immediate }13.g4 { is also possible, after }13...Nxe5 14.fxe5 Nd7 15.Be1 { White also has the initiative. } )
13. Na5{ Black plays on the queenside as planned. }
14. Qe2{ The queen is effective on  e2  - it defends the pawn on  b2  and the  c4 -square, thus preventing ... Nc4 . White is now ready to advance with  g4 - g5  and/or  f5  and attack on the kingside. }
