5. Nf3
5. Nc6( { The usual choice. The alternatives are moves like }5...a6 { or }5...e6 { , but against both White can play in the same way with }6.Ne5 { when sooner rather than later Black will put the knight on  c6 , or in case of }{   }5...e6 6.Ne5 Nbd7 7.e3 Nxe5 8.dxe5 { we have a transposition to the lines we look at after   }5...Nc6 6.Ne5 e6 7.e3 Nxe5 8.dxe5 { . } )
6. Ne5( { Here comes the surprise. This very rare move won't bring an advantage, but it does take the game down less explored paths. The main move is }6.Bf4 { , but then }6...Nh5 { , }6...Bf5 { and }6...a6 { are all major options for Black. } )
6. Bf5{ This is another natural move, to develop the bishop before playing ... e6 . }
7. f3( { White wants to expand with  g4 , though tactical ideas with  e4  may also be possible. There are alternatives, for example }7.Nxc6 bxc6 8.a3 { (covering the  b4 -square) }8...e6 9.g3 { with  Bg2  and  O-O  to come. When Black plays ... c5  White will have a reversed Grunfeld position, akin to the line mentioned in the comment to White's 7th move after }{   }6...e6 7.e3 { (where taking on  c6  followed by  g3  is also possible). } )( { The move }7.e3 { is interesting, too, intending  g4 , for example }7...Rc8 8.g4 Be6 9.f4 g6 10.Bd3 { with unclear play ahead. } )
7. Rc8( { Black should be careful, for example }7...h5?! { stops  g4 , but allows }8.e4! dxe4 9.Bb5 Bd7 10.Nxd7 Nxd7 11.d5 { with strong initiative. } )( { Also dubious is }7...e6?! 8.g4! Bg6 9.h4 { when Black is forced to allow the wrecking of his kingside structure after }9...h5 10.Nxg6 fxg6 11.Qd3 Kf7 12.g5 { with an advantage to White. } )( { Taking on  e5  shouldn't be good either, }7...Nxe5?! 8.dxe5 d4 9.Qa4 Qd7 10.e4! { and with the threat of  Bb5  White is practically winning. } )( { The move }7...a6 { is possible, }8.g4 Bd7 9.g5 { ( }9.Bf4 { is an alternative)   }9...Ng8 10.Nxd7 Qxd7 11.e4 { leads to sharp play. } )
8. g4( { The immediate }8.Bf4 { is an alternative. } )
8. Bd7( { The retreat to  g6  only invites }8...Bg6?! 9.h4 { with  h5 . } )
9. Bf4{ White develops the bishop before playing  e3 . }
9. e6( { Black wants to develop the dark-squared bishop after taking on  e5  followed by  ...Bc6  and  ...Nd7 . A sharper alternative is }9...Qb6 10.Nxd7 Nxd7 11.Nxd5 Qxb2 12.Qb1 Qxb1 13.Rxb1 { with an unclear endgame where White has the bishops in a messy position. } )
10. e3{ The light-squared bishop belongs to  d3 . }
10. Nxe5( { Liberating the  c6 -square for the bishop. In case of }10...Be7 11.Bd3 O-O 12.h4 { White expands on the kingside and will connect the rooks with  Kf2  with further ideas like  a3  and  Qc2 , or  Qb1  (eyeing the  h7 -pawn), or  Rc1 . } )
11. Bxe5
11. Bc6
12. Bd3{ Completing the development of the light pieces. }
12. Nd7
13. Bg3{ The bishop should be preserved. }
13. Be7
14. h4{ Castling is also possible, but sometimes White may play  Kf2  and keep the rook on the h-file. }
14. Nb6( { If Black castles then }14...O-O 15.Qc2 { forces ... g6  or ... h6 , both of which can be used as hooks for the pawn storm with  h5  or  g5 . } )
15. Qe2{ Defending the  e3 -pawn in advance and developing the queen. }
15. Nc4
16. Kf2{ White wants to chase away the knight with  b3  or to advance with  e4 . Further advance on the kingside is also possible. The middlegame is quite complex with mutual chances. }
