7. e3( { Just like in the line after  6...Qb6  White plays  e3  and plans  f4 . A very interesting alternative is }7.Nxc6 bxc6 8.g3 { when White wants to continue with  Bg2  and  O-O  and then concentrate on the queenside with ideas like  Na4 ,  Bd2 / e3 / f4 ,  Rc1 , targeting the backward pawn on  c6  and the weak  c5 -square. Black should avoid this and play }8...c5 { immediately, when after }9.Bg2 Be7 10.dxc5 Bxc5 11.O-O O-O { White has a wide choice of options, }12.Na4 { , }12.Qc2 { , }12.a3 { , }12.Bd2 { , }12.Bf4 { , }12.Rb1 { , }12.b3 { , }{ all of which lead to complex middlegame play where White tries to activate the queenside majority. } )( { After }7.e3 { Black needs to make a decision - to take on  e5  or not, in the latter case allowing White to play  f4  and support the knight on  e5 . } )
