9. Bd3{ The best square for the bishop. }
9. Ne8{ Black wants to deal with the knight on  e5 , either by chasing it away by ... f6  or by locking in the centre with ... f5 , thus reducing the risk of a kingside attack, possibly followed by exchange on  e5 . An additional idea is to play ... Nd6 , as from  d6  the knight controls  f5 ,  e4  and  c4 . }( { In case of }9...Bd7 10.O-O Rc8 11.Bd2 { White follows the usual development, intending  Be1 - h4 ,  Qf3 ,  g4 - g5  with an attack on the kingside. } )
10. O-O{ White castles and now Black needs to decide what to do. }
10. Nb4{ Black avoids a possible exchange on  c6 , as seen in the comments to Black's 10th move, and plans to lock in the kingside by pushing ... f5 . }
11. Bb1{ White keeps the important bishop on the  b1 - h7  diagonal. }
11. f5( { By closing the centre like this Black reduces the risk of an attack against his king. To illustrate, }11...f6?! { allows }12.Bxh7! Kxh7 13.Qh5 Kg8 14.Ng6 { with ideas like  g4 - g5  and  Rf3 - h3  and White has a dangerous attack. } )
12. Na4{ With the kingside locked, White turns his attention to the queenside. The bishop will be developed to  d2  and the knight on  a4  eyes the  c5 -square. }
12. Nf6
13. Bd2{ White would gladly exchange the passive bishop for a knight. }
13. Qe8( { Intending  ...Bd7  to harass the knight on  a4 . If the knight retreats with }13...Nc6 { then after }14.Nxc6 bxc6 15.Bd3 { followed by  Qe2 ,  Rac1  White has easy play on the queenside targeting Black's weaknesses on the c-file, the backward pawn on  c6  and the  c5 -square. } )
14. Bxb4{ White gets rid of the most passive piece. }
14. Bxb4
15. Bd3{ Improving the position of the bishop and freeing the rook's access to the open c-file. }
15. Bd7( { Black also continues with the plan to harass the knight on  a4 . Jumping on  e4  is premature, }15...Ne4?! 16.Bxe4 fxe4 17.Qb3 { gives White the advantage: in closed positions the knights are stronger than the bishops. } )
16. Nc5{ The knight goes forward. }
16. Bxc5( { Tolerating the knight is difficult, especially as after }16...Bc6 17.Rc1 { White now has the option of taking on  c5  with the rook. } )
17. dxc5{ The pawn structure has been transformed and White obtained a pawn majority on the queenside. }
17. Bb5{ Black manages to exchange the passive bishop. }
18. Rc1{ The rook belongs behind the pawn. After the bishops are exchanged both sides will have great knights, White on  e5  and Black on  e4 , but in addition to that White will have access to the  d4 -square, which allows for a blockade of Black's  d5 -pawn and support of his own queenside majority. Black, on the other hand, doesn't have active play as his pawn structure is worse (Black has only the  e4 -square, White has both  e5  and  d4 ) and he needs to defend against White's queenside advance. }
