1. g6{ The moves  1...g6  and  1...d6  are very flexible choices for Black. Depending on White's choices the option of a KID, a Leningrad Dutch a Modern, an Old Indian or the lines with early ... Bg4  are all possible, with different move-orders to take into consideration. In view of our preferred KID set-up with  e3  and  Be2  and the intention to meet the Dutch Defence with  2.Nc3 , it is impossible to navigate all the possible transpositions. Therefore, a practical choice is to take Black out of the comfort zone of the preferred move orders and change the scenery altogether. This can be achieved by the move  2.e4 .  After  2.e4  Black is very limited in its choice, especially in view of the proposed set-up with  Nf3 ,  Bd3  and  c3 , which eliminates the ideas with early ... c6  and ... b5  or ... a6  and ... b5  that are a popular option in the Modern Defence or the Pirc. }( 1...d6 2.e4 Nf6 ( { Or }2...g6 3.Nf3 { with a transposition. } )3.Bd3 { By keeping the knight on  b1  White eliminates all plans when Black advances with ... b5 , either after ... a5  or ... c6 , as there is no point in playing ... b5  without a knight on  c3 . After  3.Bd3  Black has two choices - the Philidor with }3...e5 { (with a further choice of applying the Hanham set-up with ... Nbd7 , ... Be7 , ... O-O  etc. or to take on  d4  by ... exd4 ) or the Pirc with }3...g6 { . }{ Against both White places a pawn on  c3  to limit the activity of the fianchettoed bishop, or to support the central  d4 -pawn. } )
2. e4{ Black can now still transpose to the Pirc after a later ... Nf6 , while staying in Modern territory by postponing the development of the king's knight doesn't bring much in view of the solidity of White's centre after  c3  - the ideas with ... b5  just don't work anymore and only weaken the queenside that White can attack by  a4 . }
