4. Nf3{ Now both sides develop their kingsides and castle. }
4. Bg7
5. O-O
5. O-O
6. Re1{ An important move that gives more power to the possible  e5 -push. Generally speaking, now Black has only one critical plan and that is to push ... e5 . This is so because the other undermining move ... c5  is easily parried with  c3 , when Black doesn't really put any pressure on White's centre. White's play in the upcoming lines is guided by several rules of thumb.  They are the following: if Black threatens to push ... e5  in any other way than ... Nc6  (for example with ... Nbd7  or ... c6  and ... Qc7 ) the reaction is to push  e5  (here the importance of the position of the rook on  e1  becomes visible); the move ... Nc6  is met by  d5 , forcing the knight to move either to  b8  or  b4 ; then Black will either undermine White's  d5 -pawn by ... c6 , in which case White will support it with  c4 , or will go for KID structures with ... e5 , in which case White will prevent that by taking en passant. Following these general guidelines White can navigate the opening with ease. }
