7. d5{ White stops Black's plan immediately. Black won't get a position with a King's Indian structure after ... e5 . }
7. Nb4{ This is an alternative, Black wants to take the bishop on  d3  and gain some space on the queenside by ... a5 . }
8. Bf1{ White keeps the bishop. }
8. Bg4{ Black threatens to take on  f3  and then double White's f-pawns as the queen must remain on  d1  to protect the  c2 -pawn. }
9. Na3{ White develops and defends the pawn on  c2 . }
9. e5( { Black goes for a KID structure. In case of }9...a5 10.h3 Bd7 11.c3 Na6 12.Bf4 { White will aim for the  e5 -push. } )
10. h3( { This is the only exception to the usual rule to always take en passant when Black goes for  ...e5 . It's possible even here, for example }10.dxe6 fxe6 11.h3 Bxf3 12.Qxf3 Nh5 13.Qb3 { with rather unclear play, but the main move is just stronger because of the difficulty of the stranded knight on  b4  to return to the game. } )
10. Bc8{ If Black takes on  f3  his kingside play will lack the necessary control of the light squares, while if Black retreats to  d7  White continues in the same manner with  c3  and  b4 . }
11. c3{ The knight has a very tough time getting back into the game. }
11. Na6
12. b4{ Taking away the  c5 -square. The knight on  a6  is stranded and needs even more time to go to  b8  and  d7  but even on  d7  it doesn't have clear prospects. This means that White's queenside play is so much faster than Black's play on the other side of the board as  Rb1 ,  c4 - c5 ,  Nc4  come very fast. }
