1. d6( 1...g6 2.e4 Bg7 3.Nf3 { White goes for the same set-up with  Bd3  and  c3 . Now the Modern arises after  3...d6  while the Gurgenidze is after  3...c6  followed by ... d5 . }3...d6 ( 3...c5 4.d5 { This is the simplest. White transposes to a favourable Benoni-like structure. The key is the absence of a pawn on  c4 , a square White can use for a piece - the light-squared bishop or the king's knight ( Nd2 - c4 ). White's plan is quite simple: he plays  Nc3 ,  Be2 ,  O-O ,  Re1 ,  Bf1 , and  Bf4  and aims for the  e5 -push. On the queenside he will inevitably play  a4  to stop Black's ... b5 . }4...d6 5.Nc3 { The move }5.c4 { is perfectly possible, with a likely transposition to the delayed Benoni from the chapter on the Benoni. }{   }5...Nf6 6.Be2 { The bishop can be developed to  c4  or  b5 , but plain and simple development is easiest to remember. }6...O-O 7.O-O { White finished development and will play along the outlines lines:  Re1 ,  Bf1 ,  Bf4  and  e5 . On the queenside the move  a4  will be played. The move  h3  can be useful and played while the knight manoeuvre  Nd2 - c4  should also be kept in mind, especially in positions where Black had managed to play ... e6  and had taken on  d5 , forcing a symmetrical position after  exd5 . In such positions the knight on  c4  would pose tremendous pressure on the weakened pawn on  d6 . } )4.Bd3 Nd7 { By delaying the development of the knight on  g8  Black avoids White's reaction of  e5  and intends to play ... e5  himself. }( { In case of }4...e5 5.dxe5 dxe5 6.O-O { White's plan is to play  a4 - a5  (if allowed) and then  c3  and  Na3 - c4  to put pressure on the  e5 -pawn and control the  d6 -square. } )5.O-O { White completes the development of the kingside by castling there. }5...e5 6.dxe5 { This is an important moment. }( { The natural move }6.c3 { is possible, but after }6...Ngf6 { we have been move-ordered out of the recommended line against the Pirc Defence, i.e. to meet ... Nbd7  with  e5 . } )6...dxe5 ( { In case of }6...Nxe5 7.Nxe5 dxe5 { (taking with the bishop invites  f4 ) }8.Na3 Nf6 9.Nc4 { gives White excellent play on the queenside with  b4 ,  a4  and  Bb2 , also targeting the  e5 -pawn. } )7.Bc4 { White activates the bishop. In this symmetrical structure the  a2 - g8  diagonal is the best one for White's light-squared bishop. }7...Ngf6 8.Nc3 { White develops the knight and defends the pawn on  e4 . From  c3  the knight can jump to  d5  at some point, so Black must cover that square with }8...c6 ( { After }8...O-O 9.a4 { Black cannot avoid the move ... c6  for too long. } )9.a4 { This prevents a possible expansion on the queenside with ... b5  and also plans to grab more queenside space with  a5  at an appropriate moment. }9...O-O 10.Qd6 { A powerful move, the queen is dominant on  d6 . It paralyses Black's development (for example Black cannot play ... Qe7  now) and it attacks the pawn on  e5 . Black is already under serious pressure. } )
