[White "27) Dutch: Introduction"]
[Black "The Dutch Defence: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. f5{ Whenever the Dutch Defence is mentioned, I remember the famous words by the 9th World Champion, Tigran Petrosian, who said something along these lines: 'When your opponent wants to play the Dutch Defence, the most important thing is to let him!' This surely says something about what the wise Champion thought about this opening!  The Dutch is considered a fighting opening, with Black choosing from three set-ups: the Stonewall (placing the pawns on  e6 ,  d5  and  c6 ), the Leningrad (fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop and then most often playing for the ... e5  push) or the Classical (where Black plays ... e6  and then develops the dark-squared bishop either to  e7  or  b4 ).  My choice against the Dutch was motivated by the desire to limit Black's choices as much as possible. The best move to do so is }
2. Nc3{ This is a very practical choice against the Dutch, which here may resemble a mirrored Sicilian Defence. White threatens  e4 , but most importantly, in view of this threat, the Classical and the Leningrad are not possible anymore. This means that Black is practically forced to play a Stonewall structure, which may not be to everybody's liking. In addition to this, the Stonewall gives White easy play thanks to the weaknesses of Black's dark squares, and the  e5 -square in particular. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Dutch"]
[Black "Dutch #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. f5{ There are three possible Dutch Defences that Black has at his disposal: the Stonewall, setting up the pawns on the light squares  f5 ,  e6 ,  d5  and  c6 ; the Classical, with ... e6  and then either ... Be7  or ... Bb4  followed by ... d6 ; and the Leningrad, characterised by the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop. }
2. Nc3{ White wants to play  e4 , so Black's choices are limited. The Leningrad and the Classical are no longer possible, so Black is forced to enter a Stonewall formation. }
2. Nf6( { The main move, as the knight goes to  f6  in all the variations of the Dutch. Obviously a move like }2...g6 { is met by }3.e4 { . } )( { The immediate }2...d5 { is less precise as the bishop can come to  f4 , from where it controls the weakened  f4 -square, so }3.Bf4 c6 4.Nf3 Nf6 5.e3 e6 6.Bd3 Be7 7.O-O O-O { and here the key move is }8.Ne2 { with the idea to advance with  c4  next. Generally, White's plan is to advance on the queenside. } )
3. Bg5{ This looks like a mirrored Rossolimo, only with a worse version for Black, who has a weakened kingside. }
3. d5( { Establishing the Stonewall formation, which gives Black a firm control of the  e4 -square. The alternatives are weaker, for example }3...g6?! 4.h4! { (this is a typical thrust against the fianchetto) }4...Bg7 5.h5! Nxh5 { (otherwise White plays  h6 ) }6.e4! fxe4 7.Rxh5! gxh5 8.Qxh5 Kf8 9.Bc4 Qe8 10.Qh4 { and White is on the verge of a victory. } )( { In case of }3...e6?! 4.e4 fxe4 5.Nxe4 Be7 6.Bxf6 Bxf6 7.f4 { (establishing control over the dark squares in the centre) }7...O-O 8.Nf3 { with  Bd3 ,  Qd2 ,  O-O-O  and  h4  to follow White has good attacking chances. } )( { An odd move like }3...Nc6 { is met by }4.d5 Ne5 5.Nf3 Nf7 6.Bxf6 exf6 7.Qd3 { with  O-O-O  next, when White has a big lead in development. } )
4. e3{ White develops naturally with  Nf3  and  Bd3 . }
4. e6( { The fianchetto with }4...g6?! { is again met with }5.h4! Bg7 6.h5! Nxh5 7.Rxh5! gxh5 8.Qxh5 Kf8 9.Nh3 { with  Nf4 ,  Be2 ( d3 ) and  O-O-O  to follow with excellent compensation for White - Black's rooks are still undeveloped while White's light pieces are all cooperating wonderfully. } )
5. Nf3
5. Be7
6. Bd3{ With natural moves White almost finished development. On the next move he will castle and then his plan is to move the knight from  c3  and push  c4 . }
6. Ne4( { Black can also start with }6...O-O 7.O-O Ne4 8.Bxe7 Qxe7 10.Ne2 { when we have a transposition. } )
7. Bxe7{ White gladly exchanges the dark-squared bishops, which is one of the main strategic goals for him in the Stonewall. With Black's pawns all on light squares, the dark-squared bishops are particularly useful in covering the dark squares. Now, without them, White has a good light-squared bishop and Black is left with a bad one. }
7. Qxe7
8. O-O{ White wants to play  Ne2  and  c4 . }
8. O-O( { If Black starts with }8...c5 { then }9.Ne2 O-O 10.b3 { is a transposition to the main line. Taking on  c3  only helps White as after  bxc3  it's possible to play  c4  twice, first  c3 - c4  and then  c2 - c4 ! } )
9. Ne2{ White wants to push  c4 . }
9. c6{ This is a standard move in the Stonewall, but here it is very passive. }
10. c4{ White continues with the plan. }
10. b6( { Black doesn't have time to send the bishop on the traditional route  d7 - e8 - h5  as White is quick with play in the centre and on the queenside, for example }10...Bd7 11.Ne5 Be8 12.f3 Nd6 13.Qb3 { with pressure on the queenside. } )
11. Rc1{ The c-file will soon be opened, so White places the rook to be ready. }
11. Bb7
12. cxd5{ Opening the c-file to increase the pressure on the queenside. }
12. exd5( { Taking with the c-pawn is worse as after }12...cxd5?! 13.Qa4 { Black can barely move as  Ne5  and in case of ... Nd7 ,  Rc7 , are coming. } )
13. Ne5{ The main problem with the Stonewall is the weakness of the dark squares,  e5  in particular. }
13. Nd6{ Black wants to get rid of the knight by challenging it after ... Nf7 . }
14. Nf4{ Improving the position of the other knight. }
14. Nf7
15. Nf3{ White avoids the exchange because Black's knight is the defensive one, needing to guard the  e5 -square. Additionally, now the pawn on  f5  is hanging so Black needs to move knight again. }
15. Nd6
16. h4{ White doesn't want a repetition and instead takes control of the  g5 -square, stabilising the knight on  f4  by preventing a possible ... g5 . }
16. Nd7
17. Qa4{ A multi-purpose move. The queen takes control of the  a6 -square and attacks the pawn on  c6  (the idea behind  Ba6  is to weaken the pawn on  c6  by exchanging its defender, while the exchange sacrifice  Rxc6  is also in the air). White also wants to double the rooks on the c-file by  Rc2  and  Rfc1 . White definitely has an advantage, though Black's position is solid and it will require manoeuvring by White to further improve the position. }
