1. d4
1. b6{ The Owen's Defence. Not particularly good, but via this move-order we will also explore the Hippo, where Black's development of fianchettoing both bishops and placing the pawns on  e6  and  d6  and the knights on  e7  and  d7  cannot be prevented. }
2. e4{ White takes over the centre. }
2. Bb7
3. Bd3{ Defending the pawn. }
3. g6{ Via this move-order we will examine how to play against the Hippo, whose idea is to develop with ... Bg7 , ... e6 , ... d6 , ... Ne7  and ... Nd7 , possibly adding ... a6  and ... h6 , and then hit at White with one or a combination of ... c5 , ... d5 , ... e5 , ... f5  or even ... h6 , ... g5  and ... Ng6 . Black can use the Hippo via different move-orders, basically with any combination of ... g6 , ... d6 , ... e6  and ... b6 . White, in turn, can use the same set-up as against the Modern Attempts with  Nf3 ,  c3 ,  O-O ,  Re1  followed by the knight transfer  Nbd2 - f1 - g3 . }
4. Nf3{ White will develop in the same manner as against the Pirc and Modern set-ups, only this time not worrying about the ... Bg4  idea. }
4. Bg7
5. c3{ Blunting the long diagonal. }
5. d6{ Black can also start with ... e6  and ... Ne7 , but it doesn't really matter - both knights will come to  d7  and  e7 . }
6. O-O
6. Nd7
7. Re1{ Freeing the path for the knight. }
7. e6
8. Nbd2{ The knight is en route to  g3  via  f1 . }
8. Ne7{ Black completed the Hippo set-up. }
9. Nf1{ White continues with the knight transfer and also prevents one of Black's plans - now the plan with ... h6  and ... g5  is met by  Ng3 - h5 , which is unacceptable for Black. }
9. h6{ The most flexible move. }
10. Ng3{ White effectively prevented ... g5 , which would now be met by  Nh5 . }
10. O-O( { The move }10...c5 { is met by }11.Be3 { and  Qd2 ; }{   }10...d5?! 11.e5 { only shuts both Black's bishops; }{   }10...e5 11.Be3 O-O { would transpose to }{   }10...O-O 10.Be3 e5 { and   }10...f5? 11.exf5 exf5 12.Nh4 { just loses as Black loses material after }12...O-O 13.Rxe7! Qxe7 14.Nxg6 { . } )( { The moves }10...a6 11.a4 { can be inserted at any point and they don't affect the general lines of play. } )
11. Be3{ White continues the central build-up. }
11. e5( { The move }11...Nf6 { is simply controlled by }12.h3 { , }{ covering the  g4 -square. } )( { The attack from the other side with }11...c5 { is an alternative. White continues with }12.Qd2 Kh7 13.Rad1 Qc7 14.h4! { when the idea is to probe Black's kingside with  h5 . After }14...Nf6 15.Nh2 { (covering the  g4 -square and intending  f4  in the future) White slowly puts pressure on Black's kingside and this continues even after }15...e5 16.h5 { when White also has the option to close the centre with  d5 . } )
12. Qd2{ Finishing development with tempo. }
12. Kh7
13. Rad1{ Complete centralisation! White is now ready to play on the whole board. }
13. Ng8( { Black cannot become active, }13...f5? { backfires against White's compact position after }14.dxe5 dxe5 15.exf5 gxf5 16.Nh4 { when Black's position collapses. } )
14. a4{ White probes on the queenside. The threat is  a5 - a6 . }
14. Ngf6
15. h3{ Preventing ... Ng4 . }
15. a6( { As noted earlier, these two moves,  a4  and  ...a6 , could have been played at any stage. For the sake of completeness, in case of }15...a5 16.Nh2 { , }{ intending  f4 , gives White an initiative even after the exchanges in the centre after }16...d5 17.exd5 Nxd5 18.dxe5 Nxe5 19.Bd4 Nxd3 20.Bxg7 Kxg7 21.Qxd3 { with the threat of  c4 . } )
16. a5{ The following transformation is typical and useful to know. }
16. b5
17. dxe5{ White stabilises the central structure before attacking Black's queenside. }
17. dxe5
18. c4{ Black's queenside is under pressure now. }
18. c6{ This is passive, but it keeps Black's queenside structure in place. Still, after }
19. b4{ Followed by  c5  White will have free hands to penetrate on  d6  (for example after  Bc2 - b3  and  Qd6 ) and increase the pressure on Black's position with  Bd2 - c3  and  Qb2 . Eventually White can also organise a breakthrough on the kingside. }
