4. c5( { The move }4...Nf6 { is met by }5.e5 Ne4 6.Qe2 f5 7.Nbd2 { with a big lead in development in addition to the central space advantage. } )( { After }4...d5 { White has the pleasant choice between }5.e5 { with a favourable French structure or }5.exd5 Qxd5 6.c4 { with free development after  Nc3 ,  O-O ,  Qe2 ,  Bf4  and  Rad1 . } )
5. c3{ White supports the pawn on  d4 . }
5. Nf6{ The idea of the Owen's Defence, Black attacks the  e4 -pawn and intends to continue that attack with ... d5 . }
6. e5( { The more practical choice. The move }6.Qe2 { is a good alternative, but it allows both }6...Be7 { and }6...d5 { , from which with different types of positions can arise. By advancing directly White cuts down Black's options. } )
6. Nd5
7. dxc5{ White exchanges the pawns and aims for a position where Black has a pawn island in the centre consisting of pawns on  d7  and  e6 . }
7. Bxc5( { Taking with the pawn after }7...bxc5 8.Na3 Be7 9.O-O Nc6 10.Re1 O-O 11.Qc2! h6 12.Qe2! { (threatening  Qe4 ) forces Black to weaken the structure again with }12...f5 13.exf6 Rxf6 14.Nc4 { when Black's pawn island of three pawns (c, d and e) cannot easily advance and this makes Black's position inflexible while White has smooth development after  Bd2 ,  Rad1  with pressure along the central files. } )
8. O-O{ White tucks away the king and plans  Nbd2 - e4 . }
8. f5( { A move that Black cannot avoid, for example }8...Nc6 9.Re1 { and Black must again move the f-pawn as }9...O-O? { runs into the thematic }10.Bxh7!  )
9. exf6{ White opens the central files. }
9. Nxf6( { Taking with the queen is worse, }9...Qxf6? 10.Bg5 { gives White a strong initiative. } )
10. Bf4{ White develops in the centre. The plan is to put the  d7  and  e6  pawns under pressure along the central files. }
10. Nh5{ Black goes after the bishop pair. }
11. Bg3{ White doesn't mind losing the pair of bishops because a bishop or a knight on  e4  won't be inferior to any of Black's bishops. }
11. Nxg3
12. hxg3
12. O-O
13. Nbd2{ White's play is straightforward with  Ne4 ,  Qc2  and putting the rooks on  e1  and  d1 . }
13. Qc7{ Attacking the pawn on  g3 . }
14. Ne4{ Centralising the knight, defending the pawn on  g3  and threatening to take the bishop on  c5 . }
14. Be7{ If Black doesn't keep the pair of bishops there won't be any compensation for the worse structure, but this is only temporary. }
15. Neg5{ White provokes a weakening of Black's kingside. }
15. g6
16. Qc2{ Threatening  Bxg6  and forcing Black to part with the light-squared bishop. }
16. Bxf3
17. Nxf3{ White has a stable advantage here - the better structure, two pawn islands against three, with Black's problem being that it is not possible to easily advance the central pawns because any advance would leave weaknesses. White also has the safer king. The plan is to centralise the rooks on  d1  and  e1  (or even double on one of the files if appropriate) and then pin down Black's d and e-pawns. }
