1. d4
1. c5( { Black wants to enter Benoni territory while keeping the knight on  g8 . The move }1...Nc6 { leads to a transposition to the Chigorin Defence after }2.Nf3 d5 3.c4 { . } )( { After }1...a6 2.e4 e6 { (after }2...b5 { we have a transposition to the lines after   }1...b5 2.e4 a6 { ) }{ a nice line to avoid all transpositions to the French after ... d5  is }{   }3.Be3!? d5 4.Nd2 { when White threatens  e5  and  c3  with the bishop on  e3  and not on  c1  like in the French. So after }4...c5 5.dxc5 Nf6 6.a3! dxe4 7.Ne2 { White plans  b4  and  Nc3 , securing the queenside pawn mass and attacking the over-extended pawn on  e4 . } )
2. d5
2. e5{ In the Old Benoni Black closes the position and keeps all pieces on the board, but the problem is that the White's space advantage and better options for the pieces make it a difficult opening to play. }
3. e4{ White takes up the centre. }
3. d6
4. c4( { The disruptive check on  b5  is an excellent alternative, which is analysed in the model game  Colovic-Abergel . Keeping the  c4 -square for a knight or a bishop is another very good alternative. For example a nice regrouping is }4.Nd2!? Be7 5.Ne2 { when the knights are coming to  c3  and  c4 . Playing  c4  is a practical choice as White employs the same set-up of  Nc3 ,  Bd3  and  Nge2  as against the Czech Benoni analysed in the chapter on the Benoni. } )
4. Be7{ As opposed to the Czech Benoni, where the knight is already on  f6 , here Black has the option to exchange the dark-squared bishop by ... Bg5 . }
5. Nc3{ White develops along the intended path. }
5. Bg5( { Putting the knight on  f6  would lead to a transposition to the Czech Benoni from the Benoni chapter. The move }5...f5 { only frees the  e4 -square for White's knight after }6.exf5 Bxf5 7.Bd3 { , }{ followed by  Nge2 - g3  with absolute control of the  e4 -square. } )
6. Bd3{ With  Nge2  to come next. Taking on  g5  followed by  h4  is an alternative. }
6. Bxc1
7. Qxc1{ By taking with the queen White replaces the bishop with a queen to control the dark squares and keeps the rook on  a1  in order to have the option to castle long. }
7. Ne7( { This is a more flexible development than putting the knight on  f6  as it allows for  ...f5  or  ...Ng6 . After }7...Nf6 8.Nge2 O-O 9.f3 { White can start a kingside attack with  g4 ,  h4 ,  Qd2 ( e3 ),  O-O-O  etc. } )
8. Nge2{ White's development is flexible because it allows him to play on both wings - there is a pawn break of  b4  on the queenside and  f4  on the kingside. }
8. O-O
9. Qd2( { White stays flexible, keeping the king in the centre with the option to castle long. It's also possible to castle short, }9.O-O Nd7 ( { After }9...f5 10.f4! { White is better prepared for the opening of the position because his pieces are the more active ones. } )10.f3 { with a manoeuvring play ahead where White will probe on both wings, with  b4  on the queenside and  g3 ,  Nd1 - e3 - f5 ,  Kh1 ,  Rg1 ,  g4  on the kingside. } )
9. f5( { This activity helps White, who is better placed for the opening in the centre, but }9...Na6 10.h4 Nc7 11.f4 { is very passive for Black who already is under attack on the kingside. } )
10. f4( { The standard reaction. The alternative }10.exf5 Nxf5 11.O-O { is also good, for example }11...Nd4 12.f4! { . } )
10. Nd7( { If Black takes any of the pawns it only activates White's pieces, }10...exf4 11.Nxf4 { targets the  e6 -square and }{   }10...fxe4 11.Bxe4 Nd7 12.O-O { is extremely passive for Black who can barely move a piece. } )
11. O-O{ White is fully developed now. }
11. exf4{ Black cannot stand the tension anymore as White was threatening to take twice on  f5  and continue with  Ng3 . }
12. Nxf4{ The obvious threat is  Ne6 . }
12. Ne5
13. exf5{ White clears up the centre so in the end the knight jumps to  e6 , when after the exchange a strong passed pawn appears on that square. }
13. Nxf5
14. Bxf5{ White eliminates the knight that could have come to  d4 . }
14. Rxf5{ Taking with the bishop is met by the same  Ne6 . }
15. Ne6{ Black must take the knight. }
15. Bxe6
16. dxe6{ White established a strong passed pawn on  e6  and obtained the  d5 -square for the knight. White is almost winning, a sample line is }
16. Qg5
17. Qxg5
17. Rxg5
18. b3{ Calmly defending the pawn on  c4  before continuing the attack with  Ne4  (hitting the rook on  g5  and the pawn on  d6 ) or  Nd5 . }
