6. Bf5
7. g4( { This move was Botvinnik's invention and it revolutionised White's treatment of the Carlsbad structure. He discovered that White could safely advance on the kingside not only to create an attack, but also to squeeze Black by taking up space. The move was very topical for decades, and while still playable, lately improvements were discovered for Black, so in the theoretical section we look at }7.Nge2 { with the idea of  Ng3 . } )
7. Be6
8. h3( { Later Botvinnik introduced }8.h4 { , but modern engines found that Black is fine in the complications after }8...Bxh4! { . } )
8. Nf6
9. Bd3
9. c5
10. Nf3
10. Nc6
11. Kf1
11. O-O
12. Kg2
12. cxd4
13. Nxd4
13. Nxd4
14. exd4{ This is the position that is of interest for our understanding of the positions with a fixed centre. The key in these positions is the control of the central squares controlled by the pawns:  c5  and  e5  for White and  c4  and  e4  for Black. The pressure on the central pawn is also important, as is the control of the open c- and e-files.  In this position we see that White can control the  e4 -square thanks to a pawn on  f3 , which renders the knight on  f6  very passive. White's dark-squared bishop can use the  e5 -square, which is also a factor in White's favour. Additionally, White can control the e-file and Black cannot in view of the bishops on  e6  and  e7  blocking it. On the c-file, for the time being, neither White nor Black can make great use of the  c4  and  c5  squares (they will become of interest later in the game), so everything will evolve on the e-file. }
14. Nd7{ Black improves the position of the knight, which after  f3  would be rather prospectless, by taking control of the vulnerable  e5 -square. }
15. Qc2{ A good move, either forcing the knight to return or provoking a weakness on the kingside. }
15. Nf6( { Petrosian decides to avoid weakening of the kingside, but now after White's next move the knight is a poor piece. After }15...h6 16.Qd2 { threatens  Bxh6 , so the knight has to go back anyway, while after }{   }15...g6 16.Bh6 { ( }16.Nb5 { is another option, taking the initiative on the queenside)   }16...Re8 17.f4 { Black risks an attack. } )
16. f3{ An important move, limiting the knight's mobility. }
16. Rc8
17. Be5{ White has a strong bishop on  e5 . }
17. Bd6{ Black wants to exchange the strong bishop on  e5 , but the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is in White's favour. After the exchange White is left with a good light-squared bishop and Black is left with a bad one, being limited by both the pawn on  d5  and White's kingside pawns on  f3 ,  g4  and  h3 . }
18. Rae1
18. Bxe5
19. Rxe5{ Now the rook took over from the bishop. Play in positions with fixed centre is straightforward, with both sides aiming to use their strong squares ( c5  and  e5  for White) and control the opponent's strong squares ( c4  and  e4  in this case for Black). We can see that White is much more successful in achieving both aims. }
19. g6{ Black puts another pawn on a light square. White's threat was  g5 , to win the pawn on  h7 , but another pawn on a light square means an even bigger weakening of the dark squares. }
20. Qf2{ The queen moves away from the pin on the c-file. }
20. Nd7
21. Re2{ White will double on the e-file. }
21. Nb6{ Black finally manages to make use of one of his strong squares, the  c4 -square. However, this won't help him much because the rest of his pieces are passive and White easily deals with the control of the  c4 -square by playing  b3 . }
22. Rhe1( { The aggressive }22.h4 { with  h5  was quite strong, but Botvinnik follows his plan. } )
22. Nc4
23. Bxc4{ Now White will play with a good knight vs. a passive bishop. }
23. Rxc4( { Taking with a pawn loses to }23...dxc4 24.d5 { with  Qxa7  next. } )
24. Rd2{ A nice regrouping: the rook defends the pawn on  d4  in order to allow for  Re3 , which would defend the knight on  c3 , which in turn will allow for  b3 , to control the  c4 -square and chase away the rook. }
